<HEADLINE> Aceh Rebel Leader Assassinated  </HEADLINE>
By RANJAN ROY
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- An Indonesian rebel leader living
in exile in Malaysia was assassinated in a restaurant, press
reports and rebel sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The execution-style shooting of Teuku Don Zulfahri, secretary
general of the Free Aceh Movement, or GAM, came hours before a
landmark cease-fire agreement between Aceh separatists and
Indonesian troops was to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented agreement is designed to break a cycle of
violence that has raged for more than 25 years in Aceh province,
1,100 miles northwest of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the killing was not immediately clear, but a
spokesman for the rebels in Aceh accused the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   ''Teuku Don Zulfahri used to also work for Indonesian
intelligence and the military and then about five days ago he went
on Malaysian television voicing his support for the cease-fire in
Aceh,'' said Free Aceh Movement spokesman Ismail Syahputra. ''This
really upset the military, so they killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said the killing was a violation of the
cease-fire. ''The international community must investigate this and
find out who killed him. Malaysian police must investigate this
properly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Malaysian national news agency reported the killing, but did
not identify Teuku Don by name. It quoted police sources as saying
that a 40-year-old Indonesian man was fatally shot late Thursday at
a restaurant in Kuala Lumpur's Ampang suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The man was shot twice -- once in the back of the head and once
in the left arm -- while having a drink with three friends. The
gunman, who was wearing a gray helmet, fled through the back door
of the restaurant after the shooting, the Bernama news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not made any statement about the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Teuku Don's body was still in the morgue at
Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia Hospital. A few friends and
relatives were present, but no funeral plans were announced.
</P>
<P>
   The Aceh newspaper Serambi said in its Friday edition that Teuku
Don's widow, Puteri Mei Abdullah had made an appeal to the people
of Aceh for help. She told the newspaper by telephone that she did
not know what the killer's motive could have been.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is sad that he had to die before he could witness the
implementation of the truce,'' she told the Serambi newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Teuku Don was a supporter of the three-month cease-fire
agreement, signed in Geneva, Switzerland, on May 12. It went into
effect midnight Thursday. Since it was signed, 32 people, including
two soldiers and two police officers, have been killed in clashes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
