<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, June 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Aceh Rebel Leader Assassinated
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- An Indonesian rebel leader living in exile in
Malaysia was assassinated in a restaurant, press reports and rebel sources said
Friday. The execution-style shooting of Teuku Don Zulfahri, secretary general of
the Free Aceh Movement, or GAM, came hours before a landmark cease-fire
agreement between Aceh separatists and Indonesian troops was to take effect. The
unprecedented agreement is designed to break a cycle of violence that has raged
for more than 25 years in Aceh province, 1,100 miles northwest of Jakarta.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Peacekeepers Enter S. Leone Battle
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- U.N. peacekeepers will not be dragged into an
offensive war in Sierra Leone despite signs the country's rebels are massing
ahead of a pullout of British troops, a U.N. official said Thursday. Many Sierra
Leoneans, terrified of a possible rebel attack on the capital, Freetown, have
pleaded for a strong military response by the international community. So far,
the U.N. peacekeeping mission, known as UNAMSIL, has used force infrequently,
and only when attacked.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Denies Asylum In Elian Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- A federal appeals court sided with the government Thursday
and denied an asylum hearing for Elian Gonzalez -- a ruling that could send the
6-year-old shipwreck survivor back to Cuba with his father within weeks. The
unanimous ruling from a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals blocked Elian from leaving the country immediately and gave his Miami
relatives two weeks to appeal -- either to the full appeals court or the Supreme
Court. Family lawyer Kendall Coffey said he hadn't decided on a course of
action.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Warned On Missile Defense
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Displaying a new sense of boldness in dealing with Germany's
staunchest postwar ally, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder warned President Clinton
on Thursday not to start another arms race with a proposed new national missile
defense system. Washington's proposal to build the system -- a scaled-down
version of the shield against incoming ballistic missiles once championed by
President Reagan in the 1980s -- represents for many Germans the most serious
split in thinking with the United States since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Little Progress In Mideast Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians have little to show for
six months of peace treaty talks, and time is running out for President Clinton
to produce a deal that has become increasingly elusive. Instead of negotiating,
Israelis and Palestinians have been engaging in name-calling and accusing each
other of foot-dragging and intransigence. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
spent much of his meeting with Clinton on Thursday in Lisbon complaining that
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat was not making a serious effort to reach an
agreement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, In First, Grants Reprieve
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- With less than a half-hour before a convicted
killer's scheduled execution tonight, George W. Bush approved his first reprieve
in a Texas death penalty case. Bush issued a 30-day reprieve for Ricky McGinn
who was set to die for killing his 12-year-old stepdaughter seven years ago.
Bush has allowed 131 lethal injections over his 5{ years as governor of the
nation's busiest execution state.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't Names 12 To Drug Kingpin List
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House Thursday put 12 suspected international
drug kingpins on a new U.S. government blacklist aimed at financially isolating
traffickers and their associates. The list contained no surprises. Most, if not
all, of the suspects named were already under indictment. The list consisted of
six Mexicans, a Burmese warlord, a Chinese national operating in Southeast Asia,
two from St. Kitts-Nevis and two from Nigeria. The White House submitted the
list to Congress late Thursday, meeting a June 1 deadline set in a law enacted
last year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Up in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose Friday morning as investors were cheered by
an overnight rally on Wall Street. The Nikkei gained 195.19 points, or 1.17
percent, to 16,889.49 at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Stars 2, Devils 1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Brett Hull, one of the greatest clutch scorers
in Stanley Cup playoff history, scored two goals Thursday night -- the second
with 4:16 to play -- and the Dallas Stars rebounded from one of their worst
playoff losses ever to beat the New Jersey Devils 2-1 in Game 2. Dallas
goaltender Ed Belfour turned aside 27 of 28 shots and give the Stars the road
split they were fearful they wouldn't get after Tuesday's dismal game.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
