<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire-safe cigarette issue reignited in Legislature  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A week after Gov. George Pataki vetoed a
bill mandating so-called fire-safe cigarettes, a new bill is
circulating that would require manufacturers to certify that the
new cigarettes are no more toxic than traditional ones.
</P>
<P>
   While the new bill would give cigarette makers until mid-2003 to
comply, anti-smoking groups said Thursday that the industry already
knows how to provide a cigarette less likely to start fires without
making it more dangerous to smokers' health.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of increased toxicity was an objection Pataki
raised in vetoing the bill. It would have made New York the first
state in the nation to require cigarettes that have extra bands of
paper to self-extinguish.
</P>
<P>
   ''Such technology can greatly reduce the incidence of
cigarette-caused fires without increasing the risk of cancer, lung
and heart disease in smokers,'' said a letter signed by the
American Cancer Society, the American Lung Association, the League
of Women Voters, New York Public Interest Research Group and other
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for a Tobacco Free New York on Thursday announced it
had a document ascribed to Philip Morris which concluded that
fire-safe cigarettes the tobacco company was working on would be no
more toxic than traditional ones.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would seem to indicate with these tests Philip Morris has
solved the problem which the governor raised in his veto message,''
said Russell Sciandra, of the Center for a Tobacco Free New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''Results of smoke chemistry analysis, cytotoxity testing,
genotoxicity testing, and inhalation revealed only minor,
inconsistent changes,'' the document said. Philip Morris officials
later confirmed they presented the report at a scientific
conference in March.
</P>
<P>
   The group acknowledged that the document was only further
evidence of what company officials already said about initial tests
-- that cigarettes with an experimental paper did not present added
health risks to humans. The document was used mainly to counter
Pataki's argument.
</P>
<P>
   The previous bill would have required fire-safe cigarettes to be
sold in New York in April 2002. The new bill from Assemblyman
Alexander Grannis, a Manhattan Democrat, pushes that back to
mid-2003.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor's suggestions are ones we agree with,'' said Sen.
Frank Padavan, a Queens Republican, who said he will introduce the
same bill as Grannis. ''We will include them in the new bill and
pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also cited potential illegal sales of traditional
cigarettes as a reason for his veto. Grannis' office and Padavan
said separate bills in both houses of the Legislature would deal
with bootlegging concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Fuschillo has offered a bill to ban Internet sales
of tobacco and increase bootlegging penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is ''definitely interested'' in Grannis' legislation,
said spokeswoman Suzanne Morris. He is ''committed to having a bill
and passing it this session and he's hopeful that's going to
happen,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
