<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More fourth graders passing tougher English test  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- More New York fourth grade pupils are
meeting the minimum scores in the state's tougher English test,
state Education Commissioner Richard Mills says.
</P>
<P>
   When the tests were first administered last year, 52 percent
failed while only 48 percent met all the standards. This year,
nearly 60 percent of New York's fourth graders met the minimum
scores in the state's tougher English test.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, 41 percent of 216,649 pupils who took the test in
January failed to achieve the standards. In the state's five
largest cities, more than half the pupils either ''need extra help
to meet the standards'' or have ''serious academic deficiencies,''
the test results showed.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said he was ''very encouraged'' by the ''big jump'' in the
percentage of pupils who met the English standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been an improvement across the board,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of pupils in the Level 1 range -- the lowest
possible out of four levels -- dropped by just 1 percentage point to
10 percent. Fourth graders in this category had scores between 455
and 602 out of a possible 800 points.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen percent of the fourth graders scored between 692 and a
perfect score of 800, which means they exceeded the English
standards. Last year only 5 percent of the pupils achieved scores
in that range. In both 1999 and 2000, 43 percent of pupils met the
standards, scoring between 645 and 691.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of pupils who scored between 603 and 644, meaning
they need extra help to meet the standards, dropped from 41 percent
to 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, 42 percent of the pupils met the standards,
compared to 33 percent last year. However, 58 percent were still
below standards. Combined figures for the next four largest cities
-- Buffalo, Syracuse, Rochester and Yonkers -- showed that 39 percent
of pupils met the standards, up 10 points from last year's 29
percent. But 61 percent still failed to meet all the standards.
</P>
<P>
   Mills acknowledged that there are ''large gaps'' between the
big-city figures and the statewide averages.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's still not yet enough. There are still gaps that need to
be closed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He singled out Yonkers as a district that has put in significant
effort to improve student performance. Fifty-three percent of
fourth graders in Yonkers passed the test, up from 33 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have a very, very focused effort ... and the instruction
is very purposefully aligned with the standards,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth grade tests are part of the state Board of Regent's
effort to raise the education standard of New York schools. Pupils
do not have to score at a certain level in order to advance to the
fifth grade. However, pupils who performed at the Level 1 category
would be required to take some kind of assessment test in the fifth
grade. Fourth graders who are retained will have to retake the
English test next year.
</P>
<P>
   Schools will get individual student reports on each of the
fourth graders who took the test, and Mills said the data should
serve as a guide for teachers on how to help pupils improve.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said schools should also keep motivating pupils who have
achieved the standards and provide additional help for those who
need it. Help could mean extra time in class, before or after
school or summer school, and pupils who were at the bottom should
also get ''significant intervention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Kremer, the executive director of the state School Boards
Association, agreed that pupils in Level 1 should get the most
help. Noting that there was just a one percentage-point difference
between 1999 and 2000 results in this category, Kremer said:
''That's going to be a tough group that we're going to need to
concentrate our resources and efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonia Cortese, vice president of the New York State United
Teachers, said the overall improvement among fourth graders
promises an ''up trend.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Ultimately what we have to do is make sure that it isn't just
seen as a fourth grade test. This is an accumulation of what kids
learn kindergarten through grade four ... the skills are not
compressed into a short fourth grade time period,'' Cortese said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
