<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spitzer: Family Dollar will adopt uniform check policy  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A discount merchandise chain has agreed to
adopt a uniform personal check policy in all its stores in New
York, state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer says.
</P>
<P>
   Family Dollar Stores Inc., based in Charlotte, N.C., Thursday
signed a consent decree with Spitzer, promising to accept checks
from all individuals and follow a single set of requirements in all
130 of its New York outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said Family Dollar Stores usually accept personal checks
that are preprinted with the customer's name and address, along
with proper identification, for purchases $150 or less. But some of
its stores in inner-city neighborhoods with large minority
populations refused to accept checks even when customers met the
requirements, he charged.
</P>
<P>
   This practice has been going on for ''at least a couple of
years'' and violated federal and state civil rights laws, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It harmed minority individuals and it fostered prejudice,''
Spitzer said. ''Our consent judgment ... ensures that minority
citizens receive full and fair accommodations in all aspects of our
state's economy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the investigation stemmed from a customer complaint in
one of Family Dollar's store in Buffalo. His office had petitioned
to a state Supreme Court justice, seeking penalties from Family
Dollar Stores and the chain's immediate enactment of a statewide
policy on accepting personal checks.
</P>
<P>
   George Mahoney, executive vice president of Family Dollar
Stores, denied claims that some stores had selectively refused to
accept check payments. He said a ''limited number'' of stores in
New York had a no-checks policy ''to keep our costs down.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Our experience with bad checks at a limited number of stores
caused us not to accept checks at those stores,'' Mahoney said.
''There's nothing wrong in making that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the consent decree, Family Dollar Stores agreed to
maintain a uniform policy for one year. After that time, the
company must notify the attorney general if any one of its stores
deviates from the policy. Then the attorney general would have the
power to conduct an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The store chain did not admit any wrongdoing in reaching the
deal with agreement with the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-02-00 0022 </TRAILER>
