<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A government critic bowing out of litigating -- mostly  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Robert Schulz was clearly not himself.
</P>
<P>
   The critic of government borrowing and gimmick financing read
through the five-page court ruling in silence punctuated by deep
sighs. An appeals court panel in Albany had just dismissed his
latest court challenge unanimously, rejecting every substantive
point he raised weeks earlier in person, acknowledging no merit in
Schulz' arguments.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter wanted to know what he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ''No comment,'' Schulz said, discarding the ruling, his face now
an angry crimson hue.
</P>
<P>
   No comment?
</P>
<P>
   ''No comment,'' he repeated and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   The one comment people would never expect from Schulz is no
comment.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a quarter century he has always seemed to have
something to say, if only to sputter at government actions he found
brazen and unconstitutional or to attempt to explain, in often
excruciating detail, how courts erred in failing to uphold his
legal challenges to those governmental misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   But no comment?
</P>
<P>
   The next week, Schulz explained that that court ruling and other
recent events in his life -- chiefly the arrival of his 60th
birthday -- have dictated changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a wake up call,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz said he is going to stop filing and arguing so many cases
-- ''I am not taking on any new cases. Well, I am resisting.'' -- and
begin to build an organization based in Albany to challenge
improper government actions throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants to remake the existing ''We The People
Foundation for Constitutional Education'' by staffing it with
bright, young lawyers willing to challenge misappropriations and
other questionable state and local government actions in court.
</P>
<P>
   He is trying to line up 25,000 people who will pledge $10 a
month for the next three years to generate adequate funding for the
foundation, $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz is also creating what he calls ''Tyranny Response Teams''
of sympathizers to attend meetings of local and state government
agencies to identify bad or illegal policies, try to stop them and
to warn elected officials ''it may be necessary'' to bring legal
action if they do not desist.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to dismiss Schulz as a gadfly, the kind of
annoying but ineffectual critic buzzing around every city hall and
state capitol, except for this: he has channeled his grievances
into more than 100 court cases. Most have ultimately lost, but they
include two he argued successfully before the state's highest
tribunal, the Court of Appeals, two of the six times he has
appeared before that court.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz, who lives near Glens Falls in Warren County, is not a
lawyer and said he has never taken a class on the law in his life.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nefarious governmental deeds that have prompted Schulz
suits: the use of publicly funded materials by state Comptroller H.
Carl McCall to advocate for passage of a state constitutional
amendment in 1995 restricting borrowing practices; the legality of
the New York City Transitional Finance Authority and of members of
the Court of Appeals to hear the case because many personally hold
tax-free municipal bonds; Gov. George Pataki's giveaway of free ski
lift tickets or State Fair passes to volunteers who provided
emergency services during the ice storm of 1998 in northern New
York.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest setback in the ice storm case which prompted
Schulz's uncharacteristic ''no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   He won before the Court of Appeals in cases invalidating a sewer
bonding initiative in Warren County in the late 1970s and former
Gov. Mario Cuomo's attempt to charge taxpayers with the cost of
printing pro-Bill Clinton pamphlets for distribution in New York
City in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz said he believes judges know he was right in scores of
other cases, but that they ruled against him to avoid the chaos of
undoing governmental actions or because judges had personal
conflicts of interest which prevented them from rendering unbiased
rulings.
</P>
<P>
   He is, in fact, darkly suspicious of government at all levels.
He believes that unless checked, government will seek as much power
over citizens and their tax money as it can.
</P>
<P>
   He enumerates a litany of what he calls modern government
''tyrannies'' -- the tyranny of ''corporate welfare,'' the tyranny
of the late state budget, the tyranny of state debt without voter
approval, etc. -- which have also become standard operating
procedure in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz, an engineer by training, ran as Libertarian Party
candidate for governor in 1994. He said he does not find his court
work remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can read and comprehend,'' he said. Of all non-lawyers,
Schulz said engineers have the best grasp of the law ''because
things have to add up. They're used to reading and they're used to
studying. Underneath it all, things have to add up and they just
don't add up.''
</P>
<P>
   Things might ''add up'' better, Schulz said, if young people in
New York are taught about the protections they are accorded under
the state constitution. It is, in fact, a requirement under law
that the constitution be taught each year to all older school
children. It is another tyranny that the requirement is ignored,
Schulz said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is not surprising,'' he said. ''It is in the natural
order of things for government to seek to expand its size, scope,
cost and it is also in the natural order not to teach them about
popular sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
