<HEADLINE> Onondaga merchant must pay $4.75 million for gas spill cleanup  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) --A former Onondaga Nation merchant will pay
a hefty price for refusing to clean up a massive underground
gasoline spill at his reservation gas station.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, U.S. District Judge Norman Mordue ruled that Oliver
Hill was liable for a $4,746,500 penalty for defying the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency's 1995 cleanup order.
</P>
<P>
   The fine was based on a recommendation by U.S. Magistrate
Gustave DiBianco following a short trial in January. It is the
largest ever imposed for violation of an EPA cleanup order, said
EPA Regional Administrator Jeanne M. Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators blamed Hill for 10,000 gallons of gasoline
that leaked from underground tanks at his gas station on the
reservation just south of Syracuse. The spill contaminated three
private drinking wells as it spread into a local aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government sued Hill after he refused to clean up
the gasoline spill. Hill operated the gas station and adjoining
grocery store for nearly a decade before he was banished from the
reservation in 1994 for failing to pay a tax to the Onondaga Nation
on cigarette sales.
</P>
<P>
   The station was closed in 1993 but Hill never removed
underground storage tanks from the property, siphoned gasoline from
the tanks or inspected the underground pipes connecting the tanks
to the gas pumps. The leak was discovered in October 1994 when a
resident living near the gas station reported a strong odor of
gasoline coming from a well he was digging on his property.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Hill's actions amounted to a depraved indifference to the
safety of adjacent residents of the community,'' said U.S. Attorney
Daniel J. French.
</P>
<P>
   The January trial showed Hill had ample resources to pay the
penalty and French said authorities would make every effort to
collect it.
</P>
<P>
   Fox called Hill's indifference to the EPA's cleanup order -- and
to the harm his negligence posed to the environment and to the
health of residents -- ''shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He totally failed to comply with EPA's order to clean up the
mess he caused, and for that, he will pay a very hefty price,'' she
said, justifying the magnitude of the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Clean up of the site, which began in 1994, remains ongoing, said
Joseph Heath, an attorney representing the Onondaga Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are still thousands of gallons of product in the ground.
It's a problem that's not going to go away for a long time,'' Heath
said.
</P>
<P>
   EPA and state Department of Environmental Conservation have
spent approximately $1.6 million on remedial efforts so far.
Initial tests of groundwater in the area revealed levels of harmful
contaminants -- such as toluene, xylene and ethyl benzene -- at
concentrations 10,000 times greater than allowed in drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials asked Hill to assume the costs of the
cleanup but he denied responsibility for the release. Hill, who
defended himself in the case, could not be located for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-02-00 0024 </TRAILER>
