<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Sign Peters, Milley  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres signed draft picks
Andrew Peters and Norman Milley just before Thursday's deadline,
but lost out on Western Hockey League MVP Brad Moran.
</P>
<P>
   Although disappointed in losing the rights to Moran, who now
becomes an unrestricted free agent, Sabres general manager Darcy
Regier was pleased with the additions of Peters and Milley, both
forwards that were selected in the second round of the 1998 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ''They add some ingredients that I think down the road will pay
off. It gives us additional depth and talent,'' Regier said. ''It
was something that fit into our salary structure with respect to
other signings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres had until midnight to sign players selected in the
1998 draft or lose their rights. Peters and Milley, had they not
signed, would have re-entered the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Moran will not re-enter the draft because he is 21. The Sabres
also relinquished the rights to two other '98 draft picks, center
Mike Pandolfo (selected 77th overall) and Edo Terglav (249th).
</P>
<P>
   Terms of Peters' and Milley's deals were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in signing Moran came down to economics as well
as the fact that the Sabres had seen little progress in his
development during two stints at training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brad is an outstanding junior player. Hopefully, he can have a
good professional career,'' said Regier. ''Organizationally, it
comes down to choices. You can't always sign everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Selected 191st overall, Moran had a stellar junior career with
Calgary. He recorded three straight 100-plus point seasons, and led
the WHL with 120 points this past season. Moran had 161 goals and
340 points over 215 games in his last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Art Breeze, Moran's Calgary-based agent, was upset.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never in my 15 years (as an agent) have I ever seen a player,
and especially one of Brad's elite status, treated with such
cavalier indifferent arrogance,'' Breeze said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the business of negotiating contracts, there's tough smart
and tough stupid. And the Sabres' attitude toward Brad takes
absurdity to a whole new depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Milley, selected 47th overall, had 52 goals and 112 points in 68
regular-season games last season for Sudbury in the Ontario Hockey
League. Peters had six goals and 19 points in 42 games for
Kitchener in the OHL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
