<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dems Hope Gun Debate Will Help Gore  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats predict the debate over guns will
rally voters -- especially women -- to support Al Gore for president.
Polls offer little evidence of that now, however.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the likely Democratic presidential nominee, has no clear
advantage over Republican George W. Bush on the issue. Polls show
the two about even when people are asked who they trust on guns.
</P>
<P>
   And Republicans argue that the debate may actually help their
candidate because of Bush's call for tougher enforcement of
existing gun laws, instead of new legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not clear to me that this is a one-sided issue moving
toward the Democrats at all,'' says GOP pollster Linda DiVall.
''There's no question that there is a significant gender gap on
guns, with women calling for more gun control and men calling for
tougher enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   DiVall noted that Texas Gov. Bush ''has been clever in taking a
stand'' on trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before Mother's Day and the Million Mom March, a
women's movement advocating tougher gun control, Bush announced a
trigger lock giveaway in Texas. He also has said he would sign
legislation requiring that trigger locks be sold with guns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also backs increasing the minimum age for gun possession
from 18 to 21 and has signed legislation increasing the penalties
for selling guns to juveniles and for parents who leave guns where
children can get them, campaign aides say.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association is viewed fairly positively by
the public, with more than half in a recent Gallup poll having a
favorable view. NRA President Charlton Heston's popularity was
about the same as Gore's in recent polls. When an NRA official was
caught on tape saying the group could work from the White House if
Bush was elected, Bush quickly rejected the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats acknowledge Bush has softened his image on the gun
issue, but they insist the debate will eventually work in Gore's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Leigh Blek, a lifelong Republican who lost her 21-year-old
son to gunfire in 1994, said the gun debate must be fully aired.
</P>
<P>
   ''I observed the reactions of some of the women when Bush came
up with this trigger lock distribution,'' said the registered nurse
from Orange County, Calif., who now runs the Million Mom March
organization. ''They were like 'Are you kidding?'''
</P>
<P>
   ''The women see right through that,'' Blek said.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the gun debate is ''key toward winning over the
compassionate conservative women,'' said Democratic pollster
Celinda Lake. ''Right now, white married moms are strongly
supportive of Bush. They really like him and they really trust
him.''
</P>
<P>
   When women are told Bush ''is for concealed weapons in public
places including malls they're just flabbergasted,'' Lake said. The
concealed weapon law that Bush signed in Texas is aimed at allowing
law-abiding citizens to carry concealed weapons for their own
protection, aides say.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a growing sense across the country that the best
solution is tough enforcement of existing law, along with
reasonable and rational gun safety measures,'' said Bush spokesman
Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   And the gun debate may be strengthening the NRA, which now
boasts a record 3.6 million members.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has outlined what aides describe as an aggressive stance
toward guns, while trying to signal sportsmen that he doesn't want
to take away their guns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore has no quarrel with gunners and sportsmen who are
members of the NRA,'' spokesman Doug Hattaway said. ''He's been a
hunter. He grew up shooting a gun, but he disagrees with the
increasingly extreme agenda of the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he will push for mandatory child safety locks on new
handguns, ban ''Saturday night specials,'' increase the minimum age
for handgun possession, increase criminal penalties for dealers who
sell guns illegally and oppose special legal protections for gun
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The issue also could be tricky in key Midwestern states with
many rural voters who generally support gun rights, DiVall says.
</P>
<P>
   Blek says continued gun violence is changing the political
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have seen a sea change -- I started to see it after Columbine
(the Colorado high school shooting). Many of these women are new to
the issue, but they are passionate,'' Blek said. ''I didn't get it
until after my kid was shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Will Lester covers polling and politics for The
Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
