<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Executes Convicted Killer  </HEADLINE>
By ASHLEY ESTES
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATMORE, Ala. (AP) -- A man convicted in the 1983 stabbing deaths
of a disabled woman and her daughter was executed by electrocution
early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Pernell Ford, 35, was pronounced dead at 12:12 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy final statement, Ford told Warden Charlie Jones he
wanted to apologize to the family of his victims for the pain and
suffering he had caused. Awaiting execution, Ford recited biblical
passages, took deep breaths and at times closed his eyes and rested
his head on the back of the electric chair, said Alabama Department
of Corrections Commissioner Mike Haley.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was condemned for the murder of Willie C. Griffith, a
74-year-old disabled woman, and her daughter, 42-year-old Linda
Gail Griffith, during a burglary at their home in Jacksonville, in
northeast Alabama. Both were stabbed multiple times.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, then 18, was found in Illinois driving Gail Griffith's car
and wearing bloody clothes. Prosecutors said he confessed.
</P>
<P>
   During his trial, he wore a sheet during the penalty phase and
said he wanted the victims' bodies brought to court so God could
resurrect them.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun County District Attorney Joe Hubbard, the prosecutor in
the case, has said he believes Ford acted mentally ill in an
attempt to avoid execution.
</P>
<P>
   Ford dropped his appeals and fired defense attorney LaJuana
Davis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Davis won a stay of execution for Ford last July after raising
questions about his sanity. But a federal appeals court ruled last
November that Ford was competent to drop his appeals and fire his
attorney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0203 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Attends Governors Gathering  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT LINDLAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Keeping the focus on international
affairs and making fresh overtures to Hispanic voters, George W.
Bush is sharing the stage with eight other U.S. and Mexican border
governors at a two-day conference.
</P>
<P>
   But the brightest spotlight shined on California Gov. Gray
Davis, chairman of the Border Governors Conference and a staunch
ally of Democrat Al Gore, Bush's presidential rival.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Republican governor of Texas, joined Davis and the
leaders of Arizona, New Mexico and five Mexican states to open the
18th gathering of border governors. They were to focus today on
border issues relating to the environment, education and the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrived here Thursday after an environmental policy address
in Nevada. His appearance at the conference's opening ceremony was
added to his schedule less than an hour before it began.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Tomas Yarrington Ruvalcaba, governor of the Mexican
state of Tamaulpas and conference vice chairman, addressed about
200 dignitaries. Bush and the others did not speak.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's presence was meant to remind voters of his
credentials as an international leader and to send a signal to
Hispanic voters, said Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This does highlight the fact that Governor Bush, as governor
of Texas, has had some foreign policy experience when it comes to
dealing with Mexico,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Governors Conference also was ''an opportunity to
remind all Americans that he's been an inclusive governor and has
reached out to Hispanics in our state,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was careful not to mention the White House race, but
indirectly referred to the politics of the California-Mexico
relationship, which strained under his predecessor, Republican Pete
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, like Bush, fought for tougher border enforcement,
portraying the boundary as a porous wall that allowed Mexicans to
overrun the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he envisioned the U.S.-Mexico area as one region, not
two divided by a fence.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Davis announced that Blue Shield of California will
become the first U.S. health maintenance organization licensed by
the state to provide health services to workers on both sides of
the border. The plan is aimed at the estimated 40,000 Mexicans who
cross the border each day to work legally in the San Diego area.
</P>
<P>
   While the opening ceremony was upbeat, Yarrington raised one of
the ugliest border issues: vigilante justice by U.S. ranchers and
others, particularly in Arizona, against illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   He decried ''an increase in terms of violence on behalf of those
who have decided to take the law into their own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Also attending the conference are Arizona Gov. Jane Hull; New
Mexico Gov. Gary Johnson; Alejandro Gonzalez Alcocer of Baja
California; Lic. Enrique Martinez y Martinez of Coahuila; Fernando
Canales Clariond of Nuevo Leon; and Patricio Martinez Garcia of
Chihuahua.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
