<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Economy Rebounds  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID E. KALISH
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like more and more companies in Russia these days, Saint Springs
Water is flying high. Thirsty consumers are buying its distinctive
clear bottles, shaped like a Russian Orthodox church dome, twice as
fast as last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Moscow bottled water maker itself is a tough sell --
attracting tepid demand from potential corporate buyers able to pay
top dollar for the company, its U.S. owners say.
</P>
<P>
   Saint Springs Water is hardly alone.
</P>
<P>
   Since Russia's ruble meltdown in August 1998, the economy has
staged an unexpected comeback, buoyed by soaring oil prices,
favorable currency rates, rising incomes and pent-up domestic
demand for consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of many outside observers, Russian businesses
are flourishing and foreign companies from Gillette razors to the
Ikea retailer are expanding.
</P>
<P>
   Russia attracted more than twice as much foreign capital in the
first five months of 2000 -- $10 billion -- as during all of last
year, the Russian government says. That's on top of a 27 percent
jump in foreign investment and loans in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many foreign companies and investors are holding back, still
smarting from the 1998 fiscal emergency. They're waiting to see if
the Russian recovery sticks and if President Vladimir Putin
institutes much-needed reforms of the nation's Soviet-era
regulatory systems.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns form an uncertain backdrop to President Clinton's
first summit with Putin this weekend. Weapons talks top the agenda,
though the stage could be set for later economic discussions on
trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The perception is still that Russia is a difficult place, one
that could have many bumps in the road before you would turn a
profit, and one whose tax and legal systems are opaque,'' said
Douglas Lamont, a professor of international marketing at DePaul
University.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is tough to forget. Following the ruble plunge,
foreign corporations and investors lost billions, Russia missed
debt payments, and accusations flew of government money laundering
and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Owing little thanks to its government, Russia's economy is
reviving.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the recent spurt in global oil prices -- which have
buoyed tax collections and monetary reserves for the big energy
exporter -- can't last.
</P>
<P>
   Another shaky economic foundation is the ruble's two-year
plunge, which helped domestic industry compete against imports that
soared in price compared with Russian-made goods.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, moreover, has yet to reveal plans to overhaul the
nation's confusing and -- some say -- cronyism-tainted systems for
regulating bankruptcy, banking and corporate accounting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The improvements in the economy are welcome, but not
sustainable,'' said Helena Hessel, an analyst for New York-based
Standard and Poor's, a credit-rating agency. ''We need to see more
structural reforms so we can be sure of real improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the skepticism, hardy investors are returning to a
Russian economy that grew 3.2 percent last year for its strongest
showing since the Soviet Union's collapse in 1991, according to the
U.S. Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is a potentially lucrative market of 146 million
people, largely well educated, with scarce competition from other
foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Gillette Co., for one, is investing $40 million in
a St. Petersburg factory that can turn out more than 600 million
razors and blades a year. The factory expansion will be unveiled
during Clinton's visit, which begins Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette says sales in Russia soared 40 percent in the first
quarter and represent the company's fastest-growing major market.
</P>
<P>
   Also bullish is the U.S. Russian Investment Fund, which invests
U.S. government money in Russian startups -- including $3.5 million
in Saint Springs in 1995 -- with the hope of profiting one day by
selling holdings.
</P>
<P>
   It expects to take stakes in eight Russian companies by summer's
end -- up from zero in 1999. They include $1 million in a major
Russian Internet portal, $5 million in a cable TV distribution
system and $20 million in a mortgage bank.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's commonly believed that the country is turning around,''
said David Jones, the fund's president. ''But we've seen it more at
the grass-roots level -- the little businesses doing better.''
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors outside Russia are starting to enjoy the
ride. The $75 million Lexington Troika Dialogue Russia Fund, a New
Jersey-based mutual fund that focuses on Russian companies, was the
No. 1 performing emerging market fund last year, racking up gains
of 160 percent -- in contrast to its 83 percent loss in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   One Russian company it's hot on is Gaz, maker of the once-boxy
Volga car that has since been streamlined and now comes in a
rainbow of colors and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economic conditions now are night and day compared to
1998,'' fund manager Richard Hisey says.
</P>
<P>
   Hope for a sustainable Russian recovery springs from Putin, who
paints himself as an energetic reformer and has appointed
pro-market economist German Gref as Minister for Economics and
Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Putin disclosed plans to simplify taxes, boost
collections and crack down on massive tax evasion. Other reforms
ranging from banking to accounting regulation may be unveiled in an
upcoming strategy document from Gref's team.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts hope to find out then if the Putin administration will
try to shore up the battered ruble, a divisive move domestically
that is important for restoring Russia's credibility on the world
economic stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
