<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cigarette Cos. Seek Suit Dismissal  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cigarette makers are asking a judge to dismiss
a lawsuit by the federal government that seeks billions of dollars
to repay the cost of treating smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The government has no claim under federal law in seeking to
recover money spent by Medicare and other federal health programs
to treat such illnesses, the tobacco industry's lawyers contend.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is urging the judge to keep the case
alive, arguing that the cigarette companies pose a continuing
threat to the American public's health.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Gladys Kessler scheduled a three-hour court
session today to hear arguments from lawyers representing the
tobacco companies and the Justice Department. It was unclear when
she might rule on the cigarette makers' bid to fend off the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's lawsuit alleges the cigarette companies
conspired since the 1950s to defraud and mislead the public about
the dangers of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   When the lawsuit was filed last September, Attorney General
Janet Reno said federal health plans spend more than $20 billion a
year treating smoking-related illnesses, which take 400,000 lives a
year. She accused the industry of putting its own profits above the
public health by concealing data that showed nicotine is addictive
and that smoking causes disease.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials vowed last fall to fight the lawsuit rather
than settle like they did in 1998 by agreeing to pay the states
$246 billion over 25 years to cover the cost of treating sick
smokers in the Medicaid program, which serves the poor and
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers filed before today's argument, the tobacco
companies' lawyers said, ''The government is asserting causes of
action for Medicare recovery that have never been recognized by any
court before, that it has never asserted before, that it has
publicly stated it does not have, and that it has to this date
never asserted against anyone other than this group of
defendants.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco industry lawyers also argue that many of the federal
government's non-monetary demands are already required by the state
settlements, such as a ban on attempts to target children in
advertising and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department responded in legal papers that federal
law does authorize the federal government to recover Medicare
costs. The lawsuit also invoked a federal anti-racketeering law.
</P>
<P>
   ''What makes this suit unique is the conduct of these
corporations, which for decades have deliberately and successfully
addicted millions of citizens to a product that defendants have
long known causes suffering and death,'' Justice Department lawyers
said in court papers. The tobacco companies ''pose a continuing
threat to the health and well-being of the American public,'' they
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0211 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0033 </DOCNO>
