<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Players Offer Own Realignment Plan  </HEADLINE>
By JOSH DUBOW
<TEXT>
<P>
   While baseball's owners can't get together on a realignment
plan, the players are offering their own proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Player representatives are circulating a union counterplan that
will move the Houston Astros from the NL Central to the AL West to
create two 15-team leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The players' plan is much simpler than the main one being
considered by owners. That proposal would have Tampa Bay and
Arizona switching leagues, the elimination of the wild card in the
NL, and a six-team AL Central to go along with six four-team
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I reviewed it, I thought it was definitely a better
plan,'' Tampa Bay representative Mike DiFelice said. ''You at least
have the leagues evenly spilt and have the wild card. I think the
wild card is good for the fans, I think it's good for the teams.''
</P>
<P>
   But the players' plan does create one major problem. With an odd
number of teams in each league, interleague games will need to be
played most days of the season.
</P>
<P>
   With two 15-team leagues, there would have to be at least one
interleague game scheduled for every Friday, Saturday, Sunday; most
Tuesdays and Wednesdays; and some Mondays and Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also does not address Texas' desire to leave the AL
West, where the Rangers play all of their division road games in
the Pacific time zone.
</P>
<P>
   This plan would solve that only slightly -- and by creating a
rivalry with the Astros, it presumably would guarantee sellouts
when the teams face each other.
</P>
<P>
   Because Texas has been in the AL West and Houston in the NL
Central, the teams have not met in interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   But a top Astros official, speaking on the condition he not be
identified, said the team had no desire to leave the National
League. Astros owner Drayton McLane has said many times he is happy
where the Astros are. McLane can veto any league switch.
</P>
<P>
   Owners had been expected to meet in Detroit on June 13-14 to
discuss realignment, but commissioner Bud Selig postponed that
meeting. A meeting is expected to take place in late June or early
July.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something has got to get done,'' Tampa Bay's Roberto Hernandez
said. ''We can't have one league with more teams than the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan most discussed, Arizona would move from the NL
West to the AL West, Texas would move from the AL West to the AL
Central and Tampa Bay would move from the AL East to the National
League, which would realign into four four-team divisions with no
wild card.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what they are talking about with a four-team division
in the NL and the elimination of the wild card, won't go through,''
Boston player rep Tim Wakefield said.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox, Twins and Royals, who would be part of the
six-team AL Central, have objected, saying it would be harder to
reach the postseason. In addition, Arizona wants to stay in the NL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0213 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Neighborhoods Seek Tourists  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER ANDES
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- District of Columbia officials want to draw
the estimated 21 million annual visitors to the nation's capital
away from the august statuary and into the city's neighborhoods,
where other, lesser known monuments can be found.
</P>
<P>
   Many tourists never see the mural dedicated to the Father of
Jazz and native Washingtonian Duke Ellington, the Byzantine-style
Franciscan Monastery with catacombs like those in Rome, and
hundreds of other historic and cultural sites because the don't
venture past the National Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The district government and partners, including the Metro System
and National Endowment for the Humanities, want to change that.
</P>
<P>
   They launched a ''Beyond the Monuments'' initiative Thursday to
help tourists ''find their way off the Mall and into the living
city ... and spend some money while they're at it,'' said Kathryn
Smith, executive director of the Heritage Tourism Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The partners created a map detailing cultural and historic sites
in nine of the city's neighborhoods in an effort to boost economic
revitalization throughout the city. Saturday, they're offering free
walking tours through five historic neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   That's just the beginning, Smith said. Walking tours, costumed
guides, and maps of historic trails in additional neighborhoods all
are on the horizon, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At $4.2 billion a year, tourism is the district's top
private-sector industry. City leaders estimate the initiative could
move $100 million of that into the neighborhoods and boost overall
tourism even more.
</P>
<P>
   A proposed City Museum, to be built by 2003 eight blocks north
of the Mall, would serve as a base for visitors who want to
experience the city, said Barbara Franco, executive director of the
Historical Society of Washington. ''Visitors want and need to know
more about the city beyond the monuments,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0214 </TRAILER>
