<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Sending Albright to Mideast  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
will visit the Middle East next week to measure progress in
Israeli-Palestinian peace treaty talks and help President Clinton
decide whether he should get involved as a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's trip was announced by Clinton on Thursday despite
growing Israeli-Palestinian tensions and uncertainty over the
resumption of the negotiations that were interrupted two weeks ago
because of an outbreak of violence in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Little progress has been made in six months of talks on the
terms of Palestinian independence, including final borders and the
status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat accused each other Thursday of foot-dragging, saying the
other was not serious about reaching an agreement by a Sept. 13
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after a meeting with Barak in Lisbon, Clinton
acknowledged that ''tough work'' was ahead for both sides, but said
an agreement was ''within view.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright is expected to arrive in the Middle East by the middle
of next week. She will consult with Arafat and Barak, and then
Arafat will visit Washington to see Clinton. Albright will have to
make at least one more trip to Israel and the Palestinian areas
before a Camp David-style summit can be convened in the last phase
of the negotiations, said a U.S. official who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of his term drawing near, Clinton does not have
much time to make up his mind about whether to get personally
involved in the negotiations and try to secure a place in history
as a Mideast peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Israeli official, briefing reporters on Barak's plane,
suggested that the decision would be made by the end of the month.
''The leaders who sat in the room felt it was important to advance
the peace process during the month of June,'' said the official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the gaps remain wide.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials say they recently rejected an Israeli
offer to give up more than 90 percent of the West Bank. The
Palestinians want to establish a state in all of the West Bank,
Gaza Strip and east Jerusalem -- areas Israel captured in the 1967
Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   The thorniest issue remains Jerusalem. Barak said Thursday that
he would never relinquish Israel's control over all the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only someone who does not understand the depth of feeling of
the Jewish people for Jerusalem ... can even consider the
possibility of an Israeli concession in part of Jerusalem,'' Barak
said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations were suspended May 21 after a Palestinian firebomb
attack seriously burned a 2-year-old Israeli girl. Talks were to
have resumed Wednesday, but by Thursday evening it was not clear
whether the negotiators had met.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, was guardedly optimistic that after Israel's
troop withdrawal from Lebanon last week, Syria will be encouraged
to resume peace talks with Israel, the Israeli official said,
adding that Barak did not have high hopes.
</P>
<P>
   However, Barak made a new overture to Syria on Thursday, saying
that ''we respect the dignity of Syria and its sovereignty'' and
that Israel is prepared to resume talks on the principle of trading
land for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Talks broke down in January after Israel rejected a Syrian
demand that it be given control of the northeastern shore of the
Sea of Galilee, Israel's main source of water. Barak has suggested
he will give up virtually all of the Golan Heights, captured in
1967, but that he will not give Syria access to the shore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0216 </TRAILER>
