<HEADLINE> Stanford Big Winner in Second Day  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID DROSCHAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- A Stanford runner fell in the men's 10,000
meters. It was the only stumble for the Cardinal on the second day
of the NCAA Outdoor Track and Field Championships.
</P>
<P>
   A 1-2-4 finish in the final event of the day gave Stanford 31
points Thursday at Wallace Wade Stadium, while eight-time champion
Arkansas was reeling in 16th place with five.
</P>
<P>
   ''We decided we were going to make our own definition of what
success was going to be for us,'' Stanford coach Vin Lananna said
after watching Brad Hauser win the 10,000 meters in 30 minutes,
38.57 seconds and teammate Jason Balkman come in second.
</P>
<P>
   ''We weren't going to pay attention to what anybody else was
doing. The next question is, 'Does it make any difference that
Arkansas had a bad day? I don't have any idea what Arkansas did.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford was denied its second straight 1-2-3 finish in the
10,000 when Brent Hauser became dizzy and began pulling up with
about 40 meters left.
</P>
<P>
   He dove across the finish line, but Jason Lehmkuhle of Drake
beat him for third in the slowest 10,000 in the NCAAs since 1956.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you have a twin brother and you run together every day,
you want to win together,'' Brad Hauser said of Brent.
</P>
<P>
   Both will have a full day to recover before running in the 5,000
meters on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''At 150 (meters) out, he was saying, 'Hold up, hold up,''' Brad
Hauser said of Brent. ''We were going to try to cross the finish
line together. He was saying hold up and the coach was yelling that
another guy was coming. We had to get the team points.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was sad for Brent, but we got 23 points. We're on our way
to a big meet,'' Lananna said.
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks' chances of winning a ninth consecutive title
were damaged when shot putter Marcus Clavelle, projected among the
top three, and 10,000 runner Adam Dailey, one of the favorites who
was bumped onto the inside of the track while running fourth, both
failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a long meet, it's a long way from being over,'' Brad
Hauser said. ''We're not going to concentrate on a team score now.
This is halfway over. We got the points we needed to get. We'll go
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   While Stanford stole the team show, individual accolades went to
UCLA's Seilala Sua, who won the discus for a record fourth straight
time.
</P>
<P>
   Sua's win made her the first woman to claim the same field event
four times. Wisconsin's Suzy Favor is the only other woman to win
the same event four times, the 1,500 meters from 1987-1990, with
her final victory also coming here.
</P>
<P>
   Sua, who hoped to defend her shot put title today, also tied
Favor for the most overall outdoor NCAA titles by a woman. Favor
also won the 800 in 1990. Indoors and outdoors, Sua has six NCAA
titles, including this year's indoor shot put crown. Favor finished
her career with nine.
</P>
<P>
   ''A great accomplishment,'' UCLA coach Art Venegas said of Sua's
four wins. ''She has to get ready for the shot put, so her job is
nowhere near over, but I'm very proud of her. She has been a dream
to work with the last four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite winning by 13 feet, Sua was disappointed with her throw
of 200 feet, 9 inches. She apologized to her coach after the win,
admitting she wasn't very motivated by a lack of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first (title) was better than the last because I didn't
throw very far,'' she said. ''But I'm happy to put my name down in
the record books. UCLA is such a great throwing school I just want
to be known for the next 20, 30 or 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In other finals, Christi Smith became the first NCAA champion
from Akron, taking the heptathlon with 5,797 points; Texas' Erin
Aldrich won the women's high jump at 6-2}; and LSU's Russ Buller
took the men's pole vault at 18-4{.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Joachim Olsen of Idaho won the men's shot put at 66-5};
Houston's Jenny Adams took the women's long jump at 21-5{; and
SMU's Libor Charfreitag won the men's hammer throw at 253-4,
breaking the 25-year-old stadium record with a throw that qualified
him for the Olympics for Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Brigham Young was atop the women's team scoring with 23 points,
while Arkansas and Nebraska are tied for second with 18. Houston is
fourth with 16.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn was second to Stanford on the men's side, 10 points back
with 21, while Southern Methodist was third with 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0217 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
