<DOCNO> APW20000602.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cease-Fire Takes Effect in Aceh  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL COONEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A cease-fire took effect today in
Indonesia's Aceh province, ending 25 years of separatist violence,
but the historic step toward more autonomy was overshadowed by a
rebel leader's assassination.
</P>
<P>
   In Malaysia, Kuala Lumpur police said unidentified gunmen killed
Teuku Don Zulfahri, head of the Malaysian chapter of the Free Aceh
Movement, while he was having drinks in a restaurant Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the killing was not immediately clear, but a
spokesman for the rebels in Aceh accused the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   ''About five days ago he went on Malaysian television voicing
his support for the cease-fire in Aceh,'' said Free Aceh Movement
spokesman Ismail Syahputra. ''This really upset the military, so
they killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Tono Suratman, an Indonesian military spokesman in
Jakarta, rejected the accusations. ''The Indonesian military did
not do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's Minister for Human Rights Hasballah Saad said the
killing could be a result of a factional war among the rebels.
''But I am not going to speculate as to who killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Despite anger over the killing, both sides pledged to prevent
further bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Aceh was relatively calm during the first hours of the
cease-fire today. There were no reports of clashes between rebels
and security forces.
</P>
<P>
   However, police said separatists threw gasoline bombs into a
wooden building owned by police near the provincial capital, Banda
Aceh, soon after the truce took effect at midnight. The building
was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement today, Indonesian police Col. Ridhwan Karim
and rebel leader Nashiruddin Bin Ahmad promised to ''work together
in a spirit of cooperation and goodwill to provide humanitarian
assistance to those in need and to improve the security in Aceh.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men are the highest representatives for each side on a
joint cease-fire committee, tasked with monitoring the truce.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a lasting peace in Aceh is a major test for Indonesia,
which has embarked on a painful transition to democracy and
economic reform after years of corrupt authoritarian rule.
</P>
<P>
   The world's fourth most populous country is made up of hundreds
of different ethnic groups and languages spread over thousands of
islands. Aceh is rich in oil and gas and many residents support
independence
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid, who came to power last October, had
direct involvement in the delicate negotiations that led to the
three-month cease-fire deal signed in Geneva, Switzerland, last
month.
</P>
<P>
   He has pledged to end years of human rights abuses by the
Indonesian military in Aceh and to deliver greater political and
economic autonomy to its 4.3 million people. But he has repeatedly
rejected full independence for the province.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised address on Thursday night, Wahid said an end to
the violence would allow Aceh to develop economically and to pursue
an Islamic way of life that is regarded as more devout than in
other parts of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Since the truce was signed on May 12, 32 people, including two
soldiers and two police officers, have been killed in clashes.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented agreement is designed to break a cycle of
violence that has raged for more than two decades in Aceh, 1,100
miles northwest of Jakarta. More than 5,000 people have died in the
past decade, 345 this year alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0218 </TRAILER>
