<HEADLINE> Old affair still haunting Albert Pirro  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- It happened 17 years ago, but Albert
Pirro's extramarital fling is still haunting him as he tries to get
past federal tax-evasion charges and get on with his life as a
suburban mover and shaker.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he had his DNA tested and had to acknowledge he
was the father of an Indiana teen-ager, daughter of a woman he met
a few years after marrying Jeanine Pirro, now the Westchester
district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   In the early stages of his trial, he had to endure testimony
about the money he spent on lawyers and investigators as he tried
to discredit the woman, Jessica Marciano. Prosecutors say the funds
were among the personal expenses he claimed as business deductions.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday, he was confronted with questions about whether
he was responsible for the airport arrest that kept Marciano away
from the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's absolute nonsense,'' he said as he arrived at federal
court in White Plains. ''It was just a question of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pirro, a lobbyist and real estate developer, said he wouldn't
have cared if Marciano had shown up as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ''Miss Marciano and that extremely unfortunate episode in my
life happened 17 years ago,'' he said. ''It is a personal matter
between my wife and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Jeanine Pirro, who attended the trial as
usual, would not comment on Marciano's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro complained that by linking the woman's paternity
case against him to the tax evasion trial, federal prosecutors were
aiding ''all the geeks out there trying to look into our personal
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his brother Anthony are accused of claiming more than $1
million in personal spending as business deductions.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano spent Wednesday and Thursday nights in the Essex County
Jail's annex for women in Caldwell, N.J., after her arrest at
Newark International Airport, where she got off a flight from Great
Britain with Pirro's 17-year-old daughter en route to attend the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Essex County spokeswoman Joanna Noonan said Marciano went by
several names and was listed in the jail as Merri Farber.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Pitz, a U.S. Customs spokeswoman, said Marciano was
taken into custody on a warrant from Brevard County, Fla., where
she was wanted for failing to pay back her victims after a
grand-theft conviction. An extradition hearing is scheduled for
today in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro said he wanted to make sure his daughter was taken care
of.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rest of it is just theater,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In court on Thursday, the deputy chief investigator in Jeanine
Pirro's office, Patrick Spatafore, testified that he runs a private
investigation company on the side. He said he was hired by Albert
Pirro to check for wiretaps on phone lines at the Harrison and
Manhattan homes of Marvin Singer, a friend of Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had the work done by two contractors -- one of them
another district attorney's investigator -- and submitted a bill for
$1,077.50 to Baumeister Enterprises, one of Pirro's companies, as
Pirro directed. That company then sent him a check for the same
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, prosecutors showed the jury an invoice from
Baumeister Enterprises to Singer's clothing company, Depeche Mode,
for an ''audio countermeasure survey'' for $2,693.75. Court papers
indicate they will claim that Pirro had the amount inflated,
possibly so Singer could claim a larger deduction.
</P>
</TEXT>
