<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Date Set For Fiji Hostages Release  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Armed rebels holding hostages in parliament
plan to release them this weekend, the leader of the group said
today -- adding that Fiji's tribal chiefs will then have final say
over ending the standoff.
</P>
<P>
   George Speight said his rebels and the military agreed to put
two options to the chiefs: let the military keep running Fiji until
a new constitution is drawn up and elections called or allow a
civilian government led by Speight to guide Fiji to elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Council of Chiefs is scheduled to meet Monday, and in
the most positive sign yet that the more than 30 hostages will soon
be released, Speight said he wants the meeting to be ''uninhibited
or untainted by ... issues,'' including the fate of the captives.
</P>
<P>
   ''All going well, my plan is to release them before the Great
Council of Chiefs meeting,'' Speight said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the chiefs hold little formal power, they command
considerable respect and influence among the indigenous majority in
this Pacific island nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have agreed the GCC decision will be binding and we will
both abide by the outcome,'' Speight said.
</P>
<P>
   The military has not said whether it will agree to let the
chiefs resolve the dispute, but Speight was meeting today with
Fiji's martial law ruler, Commodore Frank Bainimarama, for a second
time.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, at which a delegation from the chiefs also was
present, broke up briefly but was due to continue into the evening.
In a brief statement, the groups participating said their talks
were positive and they remained resolved to reaching a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's hostages include deposed Prime Minister Mahendra
Chaudhry, the first ethnic Indian elected to the position. Speight
says he is acting on behalf of the indigenous Fijian majority and
wants Fijians of Indian ancestry barred from leading the country.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier today, about 100 Speight supporters were involved in a
standoff with troops and police outside the gates of parliament. It
was the latest in a series of skirmishes since a roving mob killed
a policeman and ransacked state-owned Fiji TV on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing to put the civilian and military government options to
the chiefs was a key development in negotiations to free the
hostages, taken May 19 when Speight and six masked gunmen stormed
parliament in the capital, Suva.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough came late Thursday after Speight met with
Bainimarama, who declared martial law and took executive control of
the country on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After that meeting, the military said the hostages would likely
be freed within 24 to 36 hours, while a Speight spokesman suggested
they would be held until after the chiefs' meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking power, the army has accepted Speight's major
demands: scrapping the 1997 constitution blamed by indigenous
Fijians for giving too much power to the ethnic Indian minority,
deposing President Ratu Sir Kamisese Mara and offering Speight and
his rebels amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   Speight claims he has the chiefs' backing for the formation of a
civilian government with himself at its head.
</P>
<P>
   What appears clear is that Fiji will become an international
outcast whichever option the chiefs back.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Australia and New Zealand have all threatened
sanctions if Fiji, 2,250 miles northeast of Sydney, Australia, is
not returned to democratic rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0246 </TRAILER>
