<HEADLINE> N.J. Senate Hopefuls Target Voters  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- While their Democratic counterparts are
capturing most of the headlines in the race for New Jersey's open
Senate seat, four Republicans are campaigning away in relative
obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, Republicans say, the attention focused on the
primary battle between former investment banker Jon Corzine and
former Gov. Jim Florio will work in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whoever our candidate is, I think the guy is going to do very
well because the other two guys on the other side are beating each
other up,'' said Republican State Committee Chairman Garabed
Haytaian. ''When all is said and done, we don't have to do a whole
lot of opposition research on those guys. They'll have done it for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The seat is being vacated by Democrat Frank Lautenberg, who is
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the GOP has offered nothing comparable to the
extravagant Corzine-Florio fight to grab the public's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has spent $2 million a week on glossy television ads
touting his ''bold ideas,'' while Florio has crisscrossed the
state, picking up newspaper endorsements, courting traditional
Democratic groups and defending the $2.8 billion tax increase that
sent him packing after one term.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Republicans -- William L. Gormley, a state
senator from the Atlantic City area; Essex County Executive Jim
Treffinger; Bob Franks, a central New Jersey congressman, and
Ramapo College professor Murray Sabrin -- are wooing voters with
direct mail and limited television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   They have appeared together in several uneventful debates, with
negative campaigning aimed at Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''There really are two different games being played,'' said
Charlie Smith, a spokesman for the Franks campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, 54, has a financial edge, drawing on support from the
casino industry in his district. Franks, 48, is a former state
party chairman who portrays himself as a moderate Republican in the
mold of Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger, 49, touts fiscal responsibility, while Sabrin, 53, a
one-time Libertarian, ran for governor against Whitman in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Former Republican Gov. Tom Kean is hopeful about his party's
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've got probably three candidates who could very easily go
up the middle of either Florio or Corzine,'' Kean said. ''As a
Republican, I'm very optimistic this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's cash, however, could prove a big advantage over any of
the Republicans, said political analyst and Rider University
professor David Rebovich.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is almost a mindset in the state that this is a guy that
will spend twice as much in the general campaign,'' Rebovich said.
''If a former governor can't beat him, what can four lesser-known
guys do?''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Whitman first committed to run, then backed out,
also puts the Republican candidates at a disadvantage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately,'' said Rebovich, ''they have the look of
second-string about them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 0250 </TRAILER>
