<HEADLINE> Clarke family seeks to interview witness to 8-year-old's slaying  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Attorneys representing the family of
8-year-old Leroy Brown and his mother, Karen Clark, in a civil
lawsuit are seeking to interview the woman who claims to have
witnessed their murders.
</P>
<P>
   The family wants to talk to Josephine Lee in connection with the
federal lawsuit they have filed against Bridgeport police, claiming
authorities failed to protect the boy.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. and his mother were shot to death in January, 1999.
Prosecutors claim Russell Peeler had his brother Adrian kill the
mother and son to prevent the boy from testifying against Russell
in the 1998 slaying of Clarke's boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Joseph Moniz, representing the family, asked U.S.
District Judge Christopher F. Droney to allow him to immediately
take a deposition from Lee, who has told authorities she played the
role of lookout during the shootings. Moniz said he was concerned
that Lee, who has AIDS, would not be healthy enough to testify
during the civil trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a key witness, the only eyewitness to the crime,'' Moniz
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant State's Attorney Joseph Corradino told Droney that
a deposition could interfere with the prosecution of Russell
Peeler, now on trial in the double homicide, and the later trial of
Adrian.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Laske, a lawyer defending Bridgeport against the lawsuit,
said he could be cast in the awkward role of trying to impeach
Lee's credibility during a deposition, potentially giving
ammunition to the defense in future criminal prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to be in the position of tearing her apart in a
civil deposition,'' Laske said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's credibility has come under attack in Russell Peeler's
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In letters obtained by the defense, Lee repeatedly has said she
lied when implicating the Peelers, though on the witness stand she
has dismissed the letters as lies.
</P>
<P>
   Moniz told Droney that it is hard to believe Lee could further
harm her credibility in a deposition. ''You can't get a more
damaging statement than, 'What I told you about the murders is a
lie,''' Moniz said. ''It can't get any worse than it already is.''
</P>
<P>
   Droney made no immediate ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
