<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mosquito testing begins in southern Connecticut  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state Department of Environmental
Protection has begun trapping mosquitoes to test for the West
Nile-like strain of the encephalitis virus.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, carried by house mosquitoes, touched off a scare last
fall after killing seven New Yorkers and infecting birds in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   But since November, the virus, which in rare cases can cause
deadly inflammation of the brain, has been found in only a single
hawk that died in Westchester County, N.Y., and in a small number
of mosquitoes trapped at a single location in Queens, New York.
</P>
<P>
   The state began its seasonal trapping program Thursday. It has
doubled the number of trapping stations from 36 last season to 73
this year, DEP Commissioner Arthur Rocque Jr. told The Advocate and
Greenwich Time during a meeting yesterday in Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   Three trapping sites will be set up in Stamford and Greenwich
and two in Norwalk. Traps also will be set at two sites each in
Darien, New Canaan and Westport.
</P>
<P>
   The first mosquito test results are expected June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Because the mosquito population does not build up until late
August and early September, larvicide, a pesticide used to
eradicate mosquito larvae, has not been spread, Rocque said.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquito larvicide programs will begin in the middle of this
month and continue through next month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the new trapping sites the DEP established this year are
in lower Fairfield County and New Haven County, where infected
mosquitoes and dead crows were found last year.
</P>
<P>
   Two trap types will be used in Fairfield and New Haven counties,
Rocque said. The trap designed to capture host-seeking adult female
mosquitoes will be used throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Another, designed to trap blood-fed adult female mosquitoes,
will be used in Fairfield and New Haven counties where evidence of
West Nile virus was detected last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquito trapping will be conducted daily through October. It
takes about 10 days from the time the mosquito is caught to
identify a virus.
</P>
<P>
   State officials will notify local officials whether the virus is
confirmed in birds or mosquitoes. They will notify the public the
next day. State and local officials will work together to determine
how to increase surveillance efforts and prevention of the disease
and what actions to direct the public to take.
</P>
<P>
   Based on recommendations from the U.S. Department of Agriculture
and the CDCP, the state DEP will initiate a program to evaluate
suspicious neurological disease in domestic animals and poultry for
the West Nile-like form of the virus, Rocque said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are remarkably well prepared,'' said DEP Deputy
Commissioner David Leff. ''Decisions will not be based on
supposition or fear but on science and field results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-02-00 0300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 07:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holly Hunter Praised for 'Harlan'  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Holly Hunter responded to the idea of ''Harlan
County War'' the same way viewers might on first hearing about it:
What, again?
</P>
<P>
   Hunter was being asked to star in a drama about a Kentucky coal
miner's wife; a year-long labor strike; danger, poverty and pride.
</P>
<P>
   ''But Barbara Kopple had made that amazing documentary'' -- the
Oscar-winning ''Harlan County, U.S.A.'' about the real-life mining
strike of 1973-74 -- ''so I kind of went, 'What for? Kopple's done
it,''' Hunter says.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then,'' she goes on, ''I read the script, and I wanted to say
the words out loud. That's always a signal that I'm very, very
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the many scripts she reads, too many are set in her native
South. ''And that Southern material is almost always lousy,'' she
says. ''It's almost always inauthentic to me. The dialogue sounds
canned and the people are stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ''But in this case,'' she happily reports, ''I thought the
writing had an incredible integrity and the dialogue was
impeccable.''
</P>
<P>
   So off she headed last fall to Toronto (Toronto!) to make the
film, which is set in the backwoods of Appalachian coal country a
quarter-century ago. Directed by Tony Bill from the screenplay by
Peter Silverman, it premieres Sunday at 8 p.m. Eastern on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   A touching, human portrait of a hardscrabble life, ''Harlan
County War'' swallows Hunter whole as she becomes Ruby Kincaid, the
strong, devoted wife of Silas, played by Ted Levine, who similarly
vanishes into his character.
</P>
<P>
   As Hunter discovered when she first read the screenplay, the
part of Ruby -- spirited and wry of wit -- nearly leaps off the page.
Not so Silas, who in a lesser actor's hands would come across as
little more than a 'shine-swilling victim.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ted's part was not there in the script, man,'' says Hunter,
savoring how Levine turned a hirsute shell into flesh-and-blood.
''It was a beautiful thing to watch him work.''
</P>
<P>
   Completing the dramatic triangle is Stellan Skarsgard as Warren
Jakopovich, the union organizer who, with his quiet intensity,
arouses Ruby to the struggle, and (shades of ''Norma Rae'') other
things.
</P>
<P>
   Jakopovich first encounters Ruby knee-deep in chores -- and
suspicious of his call to arms.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're just gonna sit around,'' he presses her, ''and let the
company do what they want?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Sit around?'' Ruby snaps. ''I got tah clean a house that don't
never get clean, cook up for supper, keep my young-uns from fallin'
down a mine pit, and it'd tickle the heck outta me if you'd let me
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking back on scenes like that, Hunter marvels at the speech
patterns she was called upon to mimic. ''It's incredibly musical,''
she says over tea at her Manhattan hotel. ''And it was far harder
than I thought it was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the character she plays, Hunter is a tangy brew.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-2, she combines a pixieish frame with a towering
presence.
</P>
<P>
   She is winsome one moment (''Ah, you're making me blush,'' she
says when told she looks unglamorously lovely in the film).
</P>
<P>
   The next moment, she is suffer-no-fools direct: ''I don't work
nearly as much as I'd like. No way, man. My choice is not to do
pure, unadulterated (crap). I'd much rather be home, walking my
dog.''
</P>
<P>
   These opposing forces serve her well as Ruby, just as they have
throughout two decades of diverse roles. (Compare her TV producer
in ''Broadcast News'' to her Oscar-winning performance as a mute
Scotswoman of the 19th century in ''The Piano.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter, who grew up on a farm outside Atlanta, has tapped
straight into her Southernness for numerous projects, from the
stage production and film of ''Miss Firecracker'' to the feature
''The Firm'' to the HBO cable movie ''The Positively True
Adventures of the Alleged Cheerleader-Murdering Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter left Georgia a quarter-century ago, but she has never
relinquished her stake (nor the tell-tale twang in her voice).
</P>
<P>
   ''The South carries a tremendous burden of heritage, and danger,
and drama, that a lot of places don't carry,'' she says.
''Southerners have a grand view of their lives, a way of looking at
their day with enormity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter currently lives in Hollywood with her husband of five
years, Janusz Kaminski (a cinematographer who won an Academy Award
for ''Saving Private Ryan''), and their Belgian sheepdog, Larry.
But the place she misses most is New York City and she pledges,
''We'll live here again.''
</P>
<P>
   She first moved to Manhattan in 1980 and, even for a girl
steeped in Southern politesse, she never saw New Yorkers as
off-putting. ''I find them to be very accessible, incredibly alert,
and of the world,'' she declares.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they're always ready to express their opinion. ''I kinda
like that,'' says Hunter, flashing an impish,
as-if-you-couldn't-tell kind of smile.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   CRYSTAL-CLEAR DIRECTION: Actor Billy Crystal will direct the HBO
Films production ''61,'' the true story of the pursuit of Babe
Ruth's home-run record by New York Yankees stars Roger Maris (Barry
Pepper) and Mickey Mantle (Thomas Jane). The film's title refers to
the year that baseball commissioner Ford Frick attached an asterisk
to Maris' single-season home run record. By 1961, the American
League had expanded its season from the 154 games played in Ruth's
day, adopting a 162-game schedule. Frick ruled that there would
have to be a ''distinctive mark'' to show that it had taken Maris
162 games to break the record that Ruth had set in 154 games during
the 1927 season. The film, starting production later this month,
will debut on HBO next year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
