<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 08:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Owner of residential care home convicted in kickback scheme  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Employees of a state-funded home for
disabled and elderly residents who were forced to give part of
their salary to their boss will get that money back.
</P>
<P>
   Under a settlement reached with the state Thursday, Camille
Frosolone of Guilford will serve no prison time for her conviction
on larceny charges. But the former owner of Yorkshire Manor will
have to reimburse her employees $8,500.
</P>
<P>
   An audit by the state Department of Social Services and
investigations by the chief state's attorney and attorney general
revealed that Frosolone forced about a dozen Yorkshire Manor
employees to pay her a part of their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people needed the jobs, and paying the kickbacks was how
they kept them,'' said state Attorney General Richard Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Frosolone will also be required to pay the state up to $200,000
in compensation for the schemes she ran at the East Haven facility,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, Frosolone and her chief bookkeeper,
Dawn Pascale, are banned from operating any state-funded facility
or program for the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The state is taking control of the facility, and will sell it to
a new owner, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   The health and safety of the 20 elderly and disabled residents
at Yorkshire Manor were not jeopardized by the scams Frosolone ran
between 1995 and 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But state dollars were spent for kickbacks, for padded
payrolls, for concealment of expenses that simply didn't occur,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state probes also turned up evidence that people were being
paid for jobs that did not exist, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Frosolone was charged in November with first-degree larceny by
defrauding a public community, lesser larceny charges and three
counts of receiving kickbacks. Under her settlement with the state,
Frosolone pleaded no contest to one charge of second-degree
larceny. She is scheduled to be sentenced June 21.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was financially impossible for Camille to fight the state
of Connecticut in a trial,'' Frosolone's lawyer, William Bloss
said. ''By pleading no contest, she maintains that she did nothing
wrong criminally.''
</P>
<P>
   Yorkshire Manor provides housing and care to elderly, disabled
and mentally handicapped people. It is reimbursed through monthly
payments its residents receive from Social Security and the state.
</P>
<P>
   Frosolone purchased the facility in 1991 from Dawn Pascale's
father, William. At the same time, Frosolone and Dawn Pascale had a
romantic relationship and co-owned the Haven Rest Home in New
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Frosolone and Dawn Pascale hid their relationship from the state
in order to get a higher reimbursement rate from DSS. The agency
told William Pascale that if his facility were sold to a related or
connected party, the new owner would not be eligible for the higher
rate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're putting people on notice -- especially nursing homes who
are taking care of our loved ones, our elderly,'' said Chief
State's Attorney John Bailey. ''That if you try to do this --
defraud the state of Connecticut or not give proper care -- you're
going to be arrested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
