<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State says inmates set cell fire  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A day after a fire in a cell at the
maximum-security Northern Correctional Institution forced the
evacuation of dozens of inmates, state and community officials
praised the prison staff's response.
</P>
<P>
   An emergency pager system alerted Somers First Selectman Gordon
Mello to Wednesday's fire during a town meeting on funding for a
new $2.2 million firehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first thought that ran through my mind was 'Gee, I hope
this is a test,' '' he said Thursday. ''Then I heard the sirens.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the quick response from the Department of Correction
and the town's volunteer firefighters, Mello said the public was
never at risk and he remained at the town meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt very comfortable continuing my duties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A DOC spokeswoman said the investigation into the fire at the
Somers prison, about 25 miles north of Hartford, shows two inmates
set items inside their cell ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Heather Ziemba said the department was investigating to
determine what the men used to start the fire and how they got the
materials. Smoking is not allowed in Connecticut prisons.
</P>
<P>
   The two inmates were injured in the fire. Alex Sostre, 25, who
is awaiting trial for the 1999 fatal shooting of East Hartford
police Officer Brian Aselton, was treated at Johnson Memorial
Hospital for smoke inhalation. His cellmate, Pedro Poupart, 18, a
New Haven man serving 17 months for assault on a police or fire
officer, was being treated for burns to his arm and back at the
MacDougall Correctional Institution in Suffield.
</P>
<P>
   Magazines, papers, boxes, mattresses and bedding were set ablaze
in the fire, which guards spotted during routine rounds about 7:45
p.m. in a unit housing about 50 inmates. The unit includes the six
men on Connecticut's death row.
</P>
<P>
   Six guards used extinguishers to douse the flames. When 30
firefighters arrived at the Somers prison about 10 minutes later,
the fire was smoldering and the inmates had been moved to another
area, Somers fire Chief Bill Meier said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The cell was fully involved, but the fire did not spread, Meier
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ziemba said that at no time was public safety threatened or the
security of the prison compromised. Guards doused the fire and
evacuated the inmates ''within minutes,'' she said. The evacuated
prisoners were held in other secure areas of the prison for about
four hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''The firefighters never felt threatened at all,'' Meier said.
</P>
<P>
   A third inmate, Julio Gomez, 29, was treated at Johnson Memorial
after he became unruly during the evacuation and was subdued with
pepper spray, Ziemba said. The Meriden man is serving three years
for violation of probation; his record includes burglary, larceny
and drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was being evacuated for his safety and he was
noncompliant,'' Ziemba said. ''In order to get him under control
and protect him, he was restrained with pepper spray.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire marked the first time the town's firefighters were
called to the prison since 1997, when the Department of Correction
disbanded its fire department. The prison houses more than 430 of
Connecticut's worst offenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
