<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Up on Dry Outlook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices pushed higher in early
dealings today on the Chicago Board of Trade on expectations of dry
weather in prime growing regions.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans made the biggest early strides, rising from the opening
bell on forecasts for a new pattern of dry, hot weather emerging
late next week in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Corn also was supported by the extended forecasts, although
gains were limited by short-term weather conditions deemed
beneficial to emerging crops.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat was helped higher by corn and soybeans, but the imminent
harvest and prospects for excellent yields from the winter wheat
crop pressured the market.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose } cent to $2.71\ a bushel; July
corn rose 2 cents to $2.27{ a bushel; July oats rose } cent to
$1.13} a bushel; July soybeans rose 5{ cents to $5.28 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   August live cattle rose .37 cent to 67.62 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle rose .10 cent to 85.27 cents a pound; July lean hogs
rose .60 cent to 69.20 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .18
cent to 87.40 cents a pound.
</P>
