<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Restores Acid Rain Monitoring  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Funding will be restored for the only three
sites in the nation that monitor acid levels in clouds, the
Environmental Protection Agency announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''These sites provide a real picture of what's going on in the
atmosphere. That's very helpful in keeping a long-term record of
the acid rain (prevention) effort,'' said Bob Perciasepe, EPA's
assistant administrator.
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring site in New York's Adirondack Mountains should be
operating by late June, while details for restarting the site in
Virginia's Shenandoah Mountains still are being worked out, he
said. The third site -- in Tennessee's Great Smoky Mountains -- never
stopped running because other agencies kicked in money.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported last week that the EPA had let
funding lapse for the program, which costs about $200,000 and tests
for the presence of nitrogen and sulfur in clouds and fog. EPA
officials said the 15-year-old program was always meant to be
temporary and had served its purpose of producing data scientists
could use to track acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki said Thursday that if the federal
government would not pay to continue the cloud monitoring site on
Whiteface Mountain, the state would pick up the tab.
</P>
<P>
   Acid rain is created when sulfur dioxide, produced primarily by
coal-burning power plants, and nitrogen-bearing gases, primarily
from automobiles, combine with water vapor in the atmosphere. That
creates acidic sulfate and nitrate solutions.
</P>
<P>
   While calcium and other minerals in the soil can neutralize some
of the acid, the large amounts of acid rain over the last century
have resulted in acidic lakes and streams, harming plant and animal
life.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 200 sites across the nation that test
groundwater for levels of nitrogen and sulfur. But supporters of
cloud testing say high mountains frequently are shrouded in mist
and clouds and the monitoring is necessary to keep a comprehensive
record of acid damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 1206 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Jumps 194; Dow Up 155  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks soared today, with the Nasdaq composite
index climbing more than 200 points, as the government's employment
report raised hopes that economic growth is slowing to a less
inflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 155.24 at 10,807.44.
</P>
<P>
   That added to the 129.87-point rise in the blue-chip index on
Thursday, when government and private reports pointed to slower
growth and raised hopes the Federal Reserve is nearing an end to a
series of inflation-fighting interest rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which rose is now trading about 18
percent higher this week, was up 194.28 at 3,776.78. It gained more
than 207 points in early trading.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also sharply higher for the second
straight day. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 26.70 at
1,475.51.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is wild on Wall Street today,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior
vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. ''We are now hearing talk again
of the Nasdaq going above 4,000 and the Dow through 11,000, which
we didn't think we'd hear so soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the market was growing more optimistic that the
Fed's six interest rate increases since last June might finally be
having an impact on the economy and that few, if any, additional
rate hikes will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   The news driving stocks higher today was a Labor Department
report that the unemployment rate climbed back to 4.1 percent in
May from a 30-year low of 3.9 percent in April. The jobless rate
rose as American businesses cut 116,000 jobs, the worst showing in
nearly nine years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the weak jobs report, the Labor Department said
average hourly earnings rose just 0.1 percent in May, a sharp
slowdown after a 0.4 percent increase in April.
</P>
<P>
   Separately today, the Commerce Department reported orders to
American factories fell by 4.3 percent in April, the biggest
decline since November 1990, when the country was mired in the last
recession.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the odds have now changed and there will not be
another rate hike soon,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, director of
market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis. ''I think
the Fed will be out of our face for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading today's rally were technology stocks, with investors
snapping up shares of market leaders that have been battered in the
past few weeks. JDS Uniphase rose $9.875 to $108.125 and Intel
jumped $3.438 to $133.125.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are vulnerable to rising interest rates,
were also higher. Citigroup rose $2.813 to $66.125, Morgan Stanley
gained $6.5 to $81.75 and Chase Manhattan jumped $4.438 to $81.563.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-1 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 575.58 million
shares, up from 424.73 million shares on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 17.17 at 509.64.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
