<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PBS Looks Behind the Scenes on B'way  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- On television screens in three small, dark
editing rooms, Broadway's most accomplished crafts workers are
explaining what they do and how they do it -- while examples from
their shows swirl around them.
</P>
<P>
   There's Tony Walton talking about the rambling, ramshackle
county house he has designed for a revival of Chekhov's ''Uncle
Vanya.''
</P>
<P>
   There's director and choreographer Susan Stroman revealing what
she looks for in a dancer, qualities needed to make such shows as
''Contact'' and ''The Music Man'' move.
</P>
<P>
   And there's composer and lyricist Michael John LaChiusa
discussing where he got the rhythms that musically bring ''The Wild
Party'' to life.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the bits and pieces that will make up ''The First 10
Awards: Tonys 2000,'' the other Tony Awards show, or rather, the
first hour of the Tony Awards show.
</P>
<P>
   The program is the classy PBS look at how people behind the
scenes -- all of them nominated for Tonys -- help create a Broadway
show. It will be interspersed with nearly half of the more than two
dozen awards that will be handed out Sunday at Radio City Music
Hall honoring the best of the Broadway season.
</P>
<P>
   The show, produced by Thirteen/WNET New York, raises the curtain
on the Tony ceremony. It begins at 8 p.m. EDT, before handing off
the festivities at 9 p.m. to CBS and the glitzy, star-stuffed
package presided over by Rosie O'Donnell and Nathan Lane.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier hour on PBS began in reaction to the 1996 Tony
Awards telecast. It was a year in which the 22 winners were
announced at warp speed in an effort to get all the awards on the
air in less than two hours. The pace left presenters breathless,
winners nervous and viewers exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the CBS two-hour segment allows for one hour and 27
minutes of entertainment. On PBS, the Tonys get a full 60 minutes,
according to producer Mark Mannucci.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's roughly split between the presentation of the awards
and the story of the season told through five short segments that
tell us about who made it happen: score, book and orchestration of
musicals, scenic design, lighting design, costume design and
directing,'' says Mannucci, a veteran of the three previous PBS
Tony shows.
</P>
<P>
   ''On CBS, they show you the numbers, who won how many awards. On
PBS, we tell you how they got there,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not making a documentary here. Our show is put together
as an entertainment show. Where CBS has a dance number, we take you
backstage, we take you into the story behind the dance number. We
also take you to the performances -- but through our point of
view.''
</P>
<P>
   Mannucci and crew begin shooting interviews in March, even
before the Tony nominations are announced, which doesn't happen
until early May. They make educated guesses, filming likely
nominees to get a head start on the rush to ''Tony Day,'' always
the first Sunday in June.
</P>
<P>
   There are nine Tony categories aired on the PBS show -- each with
four nominees. That's 36 stories to fit into our hour. Mannucci
admits some faces will get more air time than others.
</P>
<P>
   ''This year we have some amazing clustering: Susan Stroman
nominated twice in two categories -- for director-musical and for
choreography, while Michael Blakemore is nominated for best
director of a play and of a musical.
</P>
<P>
   ''We spend a lot of time shooting these stories so we can find
the right moment, the minute that best illuminates their show.''
</P>
<P>
   They also film short segments of each nominated play or musical.
</P>
<P>
   ''We shoot the shows to make them better illuminate what the
designer does, what the choreographer does, what the director does,
what the book writer does,'' Mannucci says.
</P>
<P>
   ''We try to have our cameras give you a really privileged view
that you won't normally get by sitting in the back of the house. If
you are going to do theater on television there has got to be a
reason -- and that reason is the way you shoot a show -- with
close-ups and details that are deliciously textural and beautiful
but also tell you the story of what went on.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to get you to viscerally enjoy the power that is
theater and, at the same time, learn about what these people do.
It's this visceral pleasure in enjoying their work that we want to
get across. And to find the images that do that best takes a lot of
time and a lot of shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a miracle that a musical can get on with the thousands of
elements that have to come together at the right time and the right
place. The creators of musicals make that look effortless and we
try to do the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
