<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hearing off, new sentencing date set for killer mom  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) -- A prosecutor has persuaded a judge to
proceed with the sentencing for a mother who burned down her house
with her 13-year-old autistic son inside.
</P>
<P>
   Cayuga County Judge Peter Corning canceled a hearing set for
Tuesday at which defense lawyers were prepared to argue that
Michelle Davis killed her son to stop his physical abuse and rapes.
</P>
<P>
   Corning, reversing his earlier position, said the hearing would
have ''limited value'' and served no purpose but to ''vilify a
defenseless victim ... and vilify an entire mentally challenged
group.'' He scheduled Davis' sentencing for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney James Vargason filed a series of objections
with the court. Police and prosecutors have said there was no
evidence to support Davis' allegations against her son.
</P>
<P>
   ''Murdering him was not enough. She now wants to shame his
existence to save herself a few years behind bars,'' Vargason said.
</P>
<P>
   Although prosecutors at one time considered bringing death
penalty charges against the 37-year-old Davis, she was allowed to
plead guilty in March to first-degree manslaughter and use an
''affirmative defense,'' which holds that she suffered from
''extreme emotional disturbance'' the night of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Davis admitted using a candle and nail polish remover to start a
fire in her Fleming home last Sept. 4, killing her 13-year-old son,
Daniel Leubner, who was asleep on the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis appeared in court for sentencing April 27, her
lawyers said she wanted a hearing to explore whether sexual,
psychological and physical abuse of her by her son was a factor in
her causing his death. Corning granted that request.
</P>
<P>
   Proof of abuse would have given Corning the option of sentencing
Davis to a lesser prison term, possibly as little as three to six
years. Without that option, she faces up to 25 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Vargason opposed the hearing. In a May 4 letter, he argued that
Davis' request violated the plea agreement they had reached.
Vargason repeated his arguments in a May 16 letter to Corning.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 22 ruling, Corning rejected Vargason's motion. He said
there was no agreement on the record regarding a promise not to
bring up the rape issue as a condition of the plea.
</P>
<P>
   Vargason repeated his arguments to Corning May 26.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe a great injustice will be done by allowing this
acknowledged murderer to put this little boy on trial,'' Vargason
wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
