<HEADLINE> CBN Relocates Lebanon TV Workers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) -- Some employees of a south Lebanon
television station owned by Pat Robertson's Christian Broadcasting
Network are coming to Virginia as refugees in the wake of Israel's
troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The studios of religious-oriented Middle Eastern Television in
Marjayoun were seized by Islamic fundamentalists in the chaos that
followed the Israeli army's sudden pullout May 24 from a long-held
security zone, CBN officials said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 55 Maronite Christian employees at station headquarters,
seven made it to Israel with family members before the border was
closed.
</P>
<P>
   CBN officials fear the others face arrest and persecution at the
hands of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gwartney, the Virginia Beach-based vice president of
programming for Middle Eastern Television, was heading to Israel to
help those who fled there gain passports and visas.
</P>
<P>
   They cannot go back to Lebanon, he said: ''All our employees
have arrest warrants out for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most probably would make the trip to the United States within
two weeks, he said, and CBN will help them find homes and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of an Israeli pullout in July, the station
already had moved a satellite uplink facility from Marjayoun to
Cyprus. From there, it continues to send religious programming and
American sports and entertainment shows to 16 nations, including
Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Syria, Iran and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   CBN acquired the station -- then merely a mobile van parked in an
olive grove -- as a gift from a California ministry in 1982. The
station was car-bombed in 1983 and 1984. Rebuilt and upgraded, it
became a 24-hour satellite network in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
