<HEADLINE> Blast Kills 11 in Kashmir  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAMMU, India (AP) -- An explosive device went off during Shiite
Muslim religious services in troubled Kashmir on Friday, killing at
least 11 people and wounding 16, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 500 people were gathered under a tent listening to
religious sermons when the explosion occurred in Gundqasim, a
village near Pattan, 15 miles north of Srinagar, the summer capital
of Jammu-Kashmir state.
</P>
<P>
   The wounded included a former state minister, Maulvi Iftikhar
Hussain Ansari, who is also a religious leader. Ansari received
minor head injuries, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Sringar said an improvised explosive device hidden
near the dais was triggered by remote control. Ansari appeared to
be the target, since the blast occurred while he was addressing the
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   No one claimed responsibility for the attack. Police couldn't
say whether a rival Sunni sect or an Islamic militant group set off
the blast.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion created tension between the Shiite and Sunni
communities as more than 15,000 protesting Shiites marched up to
Srinagar. They later dispersed after hearing that Ansari was only
slightly wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Police rushed reinforcements to Shiite-dominated towns and
villages in Kashmir and imposed a curfew.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a dozen rebel groups have been fighting for secession
from India since 1989. India accuses Pakistan of training and
arming the militants, a charge Islamabad denies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 1351 </TRAILER>
