<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Politician Standoff Persists  </HEADLINE>
By GILBERT DA COSTA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- In a bizarre standoff between Nigerian
politicians, police surrounded the residence of Nigeria's Senate
president early Friday and demanded he return two missing
ceremonial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Chuba Okadigbo refused to hand over the maces that symbolize the
authority of the Senate, saying he had rightful custody of them. He
later blamed President Olusegun Obasanjo for the incident and
accused the government of attempting to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they acted on unidentified senators' complaints that
members of Okadigbo's security staff removed the maces from the
Senate early Thursday. The arrival of dozens of officers in the
legislative residential compound was enough to send about 20
parliamentarians to the U.S. Embassy to seek refuge.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentarians met with embassy officials for about an
hour before deciding it was safe to return home.
</P>
<P>
   ''People can say whatever they like, but as a reasonable human
being, when I saw the situation was out of control, I ran for my
dear life,'' Diko Mohammed Samaila, a member of the House of
Representatives, said outside the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The police eventually withdrew, reportedly after Okadigbo told
them the maces had been sent to his home village in southeastern
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre standoff followed a series of political clashes
between Okadigbo and Obasanjo, as well as some senators.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, senators protested Okadigbo's decision to go into
recess Wednesday before all House bills had been considered.
Okadigbo also clashed with Obasanjo over the declaration of May 29
-- the first anniversary of the restoration of civilian rule -- as a
public holiday. Okadigbo claimed the president did not have the
authority to make that decision and boycotted Monday's festivities.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's standoff, Okadigbo accused the president of a
''desperate attempt'' to change the legislature's leadership. ''The
time has come to alert the nation and the world at large on the
dangers that face our nascent democracy,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The government, however, said it had nothing to do with the
police's presence at Okadigbo's home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have absolutely no intention whatsoever of intimidating the
Senate or the Senate president,'' Information Minister Jerry Gana
said.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo's election last year brought to an end 15 years of
military rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 1403 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army's Female 3-Star General Leaves  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army's highest-ranking woman bade an
upbeat farewell Friday with praise for progress on women's issues
and not a word about a sexual harassment investigation she
triggered by accusing another general of making an unwanted sexual
advance.
</P>
<P>
   At a retirement ceremony held 31 years to the day after she
entered the Army as a second lieutenant, Lt. Gen. Claudia Kennedy
said the institution she grew up with has made ''measured and
steady'' progress toward fairer treatment of female soldiers. She
held out hope that a woman one day will become secretary of
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our Army is filled with women and men who care and who are in
a position to change and improve the conditions under which we
serve,'' Kennedy, 52, attired in her dark green dress uniform, told
an audience of hundreds of friends, colleagues and family members
in the sun-filled center courtyard of the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, more than ever, women are a powerful force'' in the
U.S. military, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kennedy nor Army Secretary Louis Caldera, host at the
ceremony, mentioned her sexual harassment case. Army investigators
have substantiated Kennedy's claim that Maj. Gen. Larry G. Smith
made an unwanted sexual advance in 1996, but Smith has been given
time to challenge the determination.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Army quietly rescinded an assignment for Smith as
the service's deputy inspector general. It was the public
announcement of that assignment last August that spurred Kennedy to
tell superiors about the alleged 1996 incident. Smith has been held
in administrative limbo in the intervening months.
</P>
<P>
   Among senior officials at Friday's ceremony was Gen. John Keane,
the Army's vice chief of staff, who will decide whether to take
disciplinary action against Smith. Keane is expected to give Smith
a letter of reprimand, a move that would all but assure a quick end
to Smith's 34-year Army career.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks, Kennedy said she had more than fulfilled the
aspirations she held when she was commissioned a second lieutenant
on June 2, 1969 -- at a time when women served in a separate Women's
Army Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Army ad says, 'Be all you can be.' Today I can honestly
tell you I've been all I could be,'' she said. ''I've risen further
than I ever dared to hope. All I wanted to do was be a leader and
serve my country. I never dreamed there would be stars on my
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy had served since May 1997 as the Army's deputy chief of
staff for intelligence. With her departure, the Army has no
three-star female generals.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that since she entered the Army, thousands of
positions once held exclusively by men have been opened to women,
and she said of the Army's male-dominated culture: ''It is
responsive, it is changing, and it is highly accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The change has been measured and steady,'' she said. ''But all
of this occurs within the context of societal change. The position
of women in politics, sports, religion, academia and corporate
America is expanding. I am proud to have been the first woman in
the Army to have achieved lieutenant general, and I know I will not
be the last.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldera presented Kennedy with the Distinguished Service Medal
in honor of her accomplishments, and he praised her for ''steadfast
and faithful service.'' He called her an ''invaluable role model''
for young women.
</P>
<P>
   Although Friday was her last day at work, Kennedy's official
retirement date is Aug. 1. Her departure plans were set before her
sexual harassment case became public in March.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was born in Germany, the daughter of an Army colonel.
She gained her commission as a second lieutenant after graduating
from Southwestern at Memphis, now Rhodes College, with a bachelor
of arts degree in philosophy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
