<HEADLINE> US-German Custody Disputes Expedited  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's justice minister said Friday a new
working group approved by Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and
President Clinton should help speed up resolution of
German-American child custody disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The working group, comprised of officials from both countries,
will look into setting policies to deal with all cross-border
custody complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Herta Daeubler-Gmelin denied allegations from
some U.S. interest groups that German authorities illegally keep
German-American children from dissolved German-American marriages.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's always terrible when a father and a mother use the child
as a weapon when they are fighting,'' she said on ARD television.
</P>
<P>
   The German Justice Ministry put the current number of custody
cases involving parents who have split up, with one living in
Germany and the other in the United States, at about 66.
</P>
<P>
   International child custody disputes recently got political
attention in the United States and elsewhere when the U.S. State
Department and Congress said Germany and several other signatory
countries of the 1980 Hague Convention on abducted children were
not abiding by the agreement, which requires they be returned to
the country they are accustomed to living in.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is seen as more acute in Germany because the
presence of U.S. troops here over decades led to thousands of
German-American marriages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
