<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Defends Central Gov't Plan  </HEADLINE>
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Trying to reassure wary regional leaders,
President Vladimir Putin promised Friday that his efforts to
strengthen the central government wouldn't infringe on their
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Putin met with regional governors at the Kremlin and assured
them that his newly appointed regional envoys wouldn't try to
control all local affairs.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was ''thinking with concern'' about his
representatives getting too much power and offered to open up
discussion on ways to balance their power. He added that his moves
''wouldn't infringe on the regions' rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But he gave no indication that he was backing away from his plan
to rein in provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has divided Russia into seven administrative zones, each
of which would be supervised by a presidential representative. The
system replaces an arrangement under which the Kremlin had a
representative in each of the 89 regions, which Putin called
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main function of the presidential representatives would be
to streamline the action of the federal authorities in the
region,'' Putin said. ''The regional level of government must not
be weakened.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who was elected president in March, has made
strengthening federal control over Russia's independent-minded
provinces a top priority. He says the plan is necessary to fix the
ailing economy and keep Russia from breaking up.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would strip governors and heads of regional
legislatures from being members of the Russian upper house;
representation in the house would instead be given to full-time,
appointed legislators. It also provides for the president to
dismiss elected governors and dissolve local legislatures that
violate federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to confront Putin openly, most governors and
legislators have praised the plan and only a few dared to complain.
The strongest criticism so far has come from tycoon Boris
Berezovsky, a member of the lower house of parliament, who
denounced Putin's plan as a step toward dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Some news media reports suggested that Berezovsky is trying to
protect his business interests in the regions and preserve the
clout he enjoyed under Russia's former president, Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 1511 </TRAILER>
