<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State hopes to lure new anglers with free fishing day  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Using free tackle and lessons as bait,
the state hopes to reel in new anglers during Free Fishing Day on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The requirement that people over 16 buy a license to fish will
be suspended statewide and, at nearly a dozen sites, instructors
and equipment will be provided.
</P>
<P>
   Devoted anglers say such programs are the surest way to attract
new fans to a sport that has seen waning interest in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you don't have someone telling you where to go, how to get
started, you get frustrated,'' said Pete DeGregorio, who runs Dee's
Bait Shop in New Haven. ''What makes the population of fishermen
grow is when you get that novice come in, you teach him and he's
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's events are part of the 14th annual National Fishing
Week, sponsored by a nonprofit coalition of state and federal
agencies and the sportfishing industry. More than 2,000 clinics,
derbies, festivals and open houses are planned this weekend and
next in 41 states and the District of Columbia, organizers say.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Protection, which has been
participating in the program since its inception, estimates a few
thousand would-be anglers and others just looking for a day
outdoors will take part.
</P>
<P>
   ''The program's designed to bring families out,'' said George
Babey, a fisheries biologist with the DEP.
</P>
<P>
   There will be lessons on flycasting, prizes for large catches
and tours of state fish hatcheries. The state has stocked 300
rivers and streams and 80 lakes with some 476,000 fish this spring,
and because of high-running waters early in the season, there are
still plenty of big ones still out there.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers have tried to improve the odds for the rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We pick sites where we know there are a lot of fish that are
pretty hungry,'' Babey said.
</P>
<P>
   The state is just beginning to bounce back from a decline in the
number of fishing licenses sold. In 1995, the state issued 189,000
licenses; by 1997, that number had dropped to 175,000. This year,
185,000 of the $15 licenses have been sold, Babey said.
</P>
<P>
   Babey attributes the decline to the lingering effects of the
recession of the early 1990s, when the state lost many
manufacturing jobs and residents. But children who attended years
of DEP programs are now coming of age and fueling the resurgence in
fishing licenses, Babey said.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that the scores of other activities available to
children and adults has taken some people away from fishing. But
the state has won some fans back by releasing bigger fish, and more
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Devotees say that while fishing may seem old fashioned, it's a
sport that should be promoted because it transcends the barriers of
age and economic means.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can pay $2 for worms and $10 for a rod or you can buy a
$5,000 outfit,'' DeGregorio said. ''And whether you're young or
old, a fish doesn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Information on National Fishing Week --http://www.gofishing.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
