<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Port Authority approves Maersk lease, study for rail, toll increases </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A giant shipping line can begin expanding its
East Coast superport. The World Trade Center can open its doors to
private developers. And, down the line, commuters may pay more in
rail fares and bridge tolls.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey cleared its table
of old business Friday, approving a $200 million lease with the
Maersk shipping line, creating a $250 million fund for New York
transportation projects and allowing privatization of the World
Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   The bistate agency also agreed to begin a six-month review of
fares on the PATH commuter rail line, the tolls for the six
interstate bridges and tunnels linking New Jersey and New York and
the fees that commuter buses are charged to park at the authority's
Manhattan bus terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation officials predicted the review would likely lead
to an increase of the $1, one-way PATH fare and the $4 toll at the
Hudson River crossings.
</P>
<P>
   After months of largely unproductive board meetings, the
authority's commissioners unanimously approved 18 items of business
in a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've reached a level of fairness between the two states,''
said Charles Gargano, the authority's vice chairman and appointee
of Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came one day after the governors of both states
settled a 17-month feud believed to be the worst in the history of
the 79-year-old bistate agency, which controls the New York City
region's three airports, interstate crossings, shipping piers and
properties such as the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki had said that New Jersey benefited more from Port
Authority revenues, especially with the Maersk lease at Port
Newark-Elizabeth and the low fares on the money-losing PATH line.
Whitman countered that any project on either side of the river
benefited both states.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki initially voiced objections to the Maersk lease, and
Whitman retaliated by refusing to approve the World Trade Center
privatization and leasing of development rights above the Manhattan
bus terminal, both projects sought by New York.
</P>
<P>
   Authority Chairman Lewis Eisenberg, a Whitman appointee,
disputed reports that the agency completed no business during the
standoff.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no item was more important than the 30-year lease with
Maersk, the world's largest shipping carrier that last year courted
bids to relocate its East Coast hub in Baltimore before deciding to
stay at the Port of New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Officials had said the future of the port, with 1,000 jobs and
billions in business for both states, was at stake if Maersk took
business elsewhere. The Madison-based company had held off on
improvements it had pledged to pay for at the terminals until the
lease was approved.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will now move forward quickly in partnership with the Port
Authority to construct the premier gateway to world trade for the
Northeast market sector,'' Maersk President and CEO Tommy Thomsen
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners also agreed to develop a five-year capital
plan as part of its study of commuter fares and tolls. Eisenberg
said increased revenue could fund projects like an underground
freight tunnel that would help reduce truck traffic on increasingly
crowded roads.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation advocates appeared to agree that it was a time
for a fare increase. PATH fares have not gone up since 1987, and
bridge tolls have not been raised in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Such increases are reasonable but should occur together, said
John Orcutt, associate director of the Tri-State Transportation
Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you increase the PATH fare by 50 cents, you wouldn't bring
in a whole lot of dough in Port Authority terms,'' said Orcutt, who
said that the tolls would be much more lucrative for the authority.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the agency pair the PATH increases to make the
fares compatible with the New York City transit system's MetroCards
or NJ Transit's new light rail line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
