<HEADLINE> Horn of Africa Peace Talks Tesume  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLAS MARMIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Talks on finding a peaceful end for the
Horn of Africa's two-year border war resumed Friday as Ethiopia and
Eritrea continued to trade allegations of fighting on the eastern
front.
</P>
<P>
   Algerian Justice Minister Ahmed Ouyahia, the chief mediator, had
convened discussions Thursday in the Algerian capital, handing both
teams an offer on ways to prevent new military clashes during
Ethiopia's proposed pullout from Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Ouyahia met Friday afternoon with Ethiopian Foreign Minister
Seyoum Mesfin and later held talks with Eritrean Foreign Minister
Haile Weldensae. The current talks are focusing on the need for
security guarantees to keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Eritrean Radio reported Friday that Ethiopian war
planes bombed the main water depot at Assab port on the Red Sea,
according to the Eritrean Visafric news agency. It also said the
Eritrean army had repulsed an Ethiopian attack near Ksad Ika in
southern Eritrea, ''putting 2,500 Ethiopian soldiers out of
action.''
</P>
<P>
   Selome Taddesse, the Ethiopian government spokeswoman, denied
the allegations. ''There has been no bombing today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Selome said an Eritrean division had attacked
Ethiopian positions at Ailagundet and Ksad-Ika but had been
repulsed.
</P>
<P>
   The two impoverished countries' war over disputed lands near
their 620-mile border has cost hundreds of millions of dollars and
tens of thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   The warring sides had long been in agreement on a peace deal,
but not on the mechanics of implementing it. With the deal still up
in the air, Ethiopia sent its forces into Eritrea on May 12, saying
they would stay there until they had reclaimed all land it claimed
along the border and broken the Eritrean army's ability to contest
the matter further.
</P>
<P>
   In the days that followed, Ethiopia broke through Eritrea's
western and southern borders with surprising ease, pushing miles
deep into the country. Eritrea then pulled out of territory claimed
by its neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia has said it is ready to withdraw from undisputed
Eritrean land captured during the 19-day offensive if its neighbor
joins in a cease-fire. Ethiopia also said Thursday that it was
ready for direct talks -- a key step forward. But Eritrea was
holding out.
</P>
<P>
   The two delegations have not met face-to-face. Their remarks
have been mediated by the Organization of African Unity, whose
presidency is currently headed by Algeria. The group also presided
over a first round of talks that collapsed May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration special envoy Anthony Lake, the former
U.S. national security adviser, and Italian Undersecretary of State
Rino Seri, the European Union representative, also played key roles
in the discussions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
