<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killer gets 70 years for shooting bystander who intervened  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAYS LANDING, N.J. (AP) -- A man who gunned down a bystander in a
parking lot shooting was sentenced to 70 years in prison Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Carnell Gibbs, 24, of Pleasantville will have to serve at least
59{ years before becoming eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 22, 1998, Gibbs confronted a man who had allegedly been
bullying and threatening him and drew a 9 mm pistol, shooting him
more than a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   As Gibbs was emptying his gun into the man, bystander Alex
Crawford rushed up to Gibbs to stop him. With that, Gibbs shot
Crawford twice, killing him. The original target, John Byrd, 27,
survived.
</P>
<P>
   ''Alex Crawford was an innocent bystander, a Good Samaritan,
somebody who was trying to stop things when they'd gone out of
control,'' said Assistant Atlantic County Prosecutor Cary Shill.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, a jury convicted Gibbs of murder, attempted murder,
conspiracy to commit aggravated assault and weapons charges in the
attacks, which occurred outside Wash's Inn, a bar on Route 9 in
Pleasantville.
</P>
<P>
   In court Friday, his lawyer urged Superior Court Judge Robert
Neustadter to grant Gibbs a new trial because of jury misconduct.
Two jurors in the trial were distant relatives of Gibbs' and may
have voted to convict him to settle an old grudge, lawyer Scott
Becker told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Neustadter rejected the request, saying the jurors were polled
before being seated, and none mentioned any prior relationship with
Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs himself was unaware of any relation to jurors, and his
lawyer only found out after the trial, when Gibbs supporters wrote
letters to the judge to complain about the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Neustadter called the misconduct allegations ''scatter-gun
assertions'' that were not substantive enough to call the jury back
for questioning. The evidence against Gibbs was overwhelming, but
there was no indication the jury did anything improper, Neustadter
said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge likewise ignored in-court mercy pleas by Gibbs' mother
and a preacher who has known his family for years.
</P>
<P>
   ''This young man's gotten a bad deal,'' said the Rev. Willie
Williams, of Easton, Pa. ''He was raised right, but he was put in
an awkward situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Shill said Gibbs deserved stiff, consecutive sentences because
there were two victims who were shot independently of each other.
Byrd, who suffered a broken leg, broken arm, fractured sternum and
other injuries, is still undergoing rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   As Gibbs' mother sat sobbing in the gallery, Neustadter imposed
a 50-year term for Crawford's death and a 20-year term for wounding
Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Crawford, poor thing, is dead from trying to stop it
all,'' Neustadter said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's mother, Katherine Crawford, 50, was satisfied with
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted justice to be served, and it was. But it's not
going to bring back my son. And it's not going to give my grandson
his father back,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
