<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cabinet Member Discloses Bisexuality  </HEADLINE>
By CANDICE HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- An Italian Cabinet member has shattered a taboo by
publicly declaring himself bisexual amid the growing furor over
World Gay Pride week.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Minister Alfonso Pecoraro Scanio revealed his sexual
orientation in this week's issue of Panorama news magazine, which
hit the newsstands Friday. ''Courageous,'' said the caption under
his photo.
</P>
<P>
   Very few public figures in Italy outside the fashion world are
openly anything but heterosexual. Pecoraro Scanio's announcement
won quick praise in some circles.
</P>
<P>
   ''He broke a taboo,'' the daily newspaper La Repubblica said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The only openly gay member of parliament, Niki Vendola, also
praised Pecoraro Scanio.
</P>
<P>
   ''A double morality is in force in our country in which some
things can be done, but they can't be spoken about,'' Vendola said
in a television interview. ''I think a lot of colleagues are afraid
to come out of the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alessandra Mussolini, granddaughter of dictator Benito
Mussolini, was quick to criticize Pecoraro Scanio for going public.
Mussolini is a member of parliament from the National Alliance, a
party born out of the ashes of her grandfather's political
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sexuality should remain a private matter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In its interview, Panorama asked Pecoraro Scanio if he is gay.
The 41-year-old lawyer replied that he is bisexual.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm against choosing just homosexuality or heterosexuality in
a rigid, old-fashioned style,'' he said. ''Me, I choose absolute
sexual liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Pecoraro Scanio, a member of the Green Party from the southern
city of Salerno, joined the Cabinet last month when Giuliano Amato
became premier.
</P>
<P>
   Amato's opposition to World Gay Pride week has divided his
center-left coalition and helped stoke a controversy ignited by the
Roman Catholic Church's attempts to get the event canceled or
postponed.
</P>
<P>
   World Gay Pride is a weeklong celebration in July that is
expected to draw tens of thousands of people to Rome. The Vatican
says Catholic pilgrims visiting Rome for the Holy Year would be
offended by the sight of gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The church teaches that homosexual behavior is a sin. Rightist
politicians also want the event canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Pecoraro Scanio said in the Panorama interview that the church
is wrong to oppose the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see where the offense to religion is,'' he said. ''The
church, instead, is trying to portray Gay Pride as some sort of
'sex' show.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Rome's leftist mayor buckled under Vatican pressure
and withdrew the city's official sponsorship of World Gay Pride
week. Amato ordered his equal rights minister to do the same thing
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   World Gay Pride organizers say the event will go ahead anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
