<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Highlights US-Russia Summit  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER R. MEARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- At a Kremlin summit held in the twilight of one
man's presidency and the beginning of the other's, Bill Clinton and
Vladimir Putin will be measuring one another on issues that will
outlast them both.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flies to Moscow on Saturday after five days of
conferences and ceremonies with western European allies, who are
restive about at least one proposal he'll take to Putin: the idea
of amending an arms control treaty so the United States can build a
limited anti-missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   On less contentious ground, Clinton on Friday called for
European unity that reaches to Moscow, and said, ''America must not
listen to those who say we should go it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   He summoned western Europeans ''to build a partnership with
Russia'' for stability and democracy, part of his own agenda for
the summit with President Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Putin have met twice before at international
conferences prior to Putin's election. The White House does not
expect the meeting to yield major agreements, certainly not on the
disputed idea of an American missile shield against rogue states,
which would require changes in the 1972 Anti-ballistic Missile
Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Clinton is seeking a sense of Putin's
priorities as he discusses his own with the new man in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder agreed when they
conferred in Berlin that Putin will be a key player in world
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''They both see Putin as likely to be president of Russia for
the next four years and therefore, an extraordinarily important
figure ... in the evolution of relations between Russia and Europe,
Russia and the United States,'' said Sandy Berger, Clinton's
national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has fewer than eight months remaining in his presidency
as he confers with Putin on issues that also are expected to
include a new nuclear arms reduction treaty, the ethnic conflict
raging in Chechnya and the ravaged Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Putin seems committed to modernizing the Russian
economy, struggling since the disintegration of the old Soviet
Union a decade ago. That recovery would put democracy there on a
more stable footing.
</P>
<P>
   But the missile defense system Clinton is considering, designed
to guard America against strikes by outlaw nations -- Iraq and North
Korea are the two cited as potential threats -- raises what might be
the most contentious point of the summit.
</P>
<P>
   The system is still being tested and Clinton won't decide
whether to go ahead with it until fall, a move he will then
bequeath to Congress and the president elected to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the administration wants room to make the
decision without breaching the 1972 treaty, although Berger did say
that abrogating it would be within Clinton's rights.
</P>
<P>
   But that would roil western relations and risk steps by Russia
and China to make sure their nuclear missiles are not vulnerable to
a U.S. shield. And Schroeder said the national missile defense plan
must not be allowed to ''trigger a new arms race.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABM treaty was written so that the superpowers could count
on their mutual nuclear deterrence, with each side agreeing not to
build systems to render the other's impotent. The Russians have
rebuffed administration suggestions that they agree to changes.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans are concerned about a plan they fear could shake
past arms accords and leave them more vulnerable than before.
</P>
<P>
   ''This issue could have an impact far beyond the U.S.A.,''
Schroeder reminded Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also intends to urge Putin that the rebellion in
Chechnya be settled politically rather than militarily. Moscow has
insisted the conflict is an internal issue.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton and Putin also will discuss the broader question of
strategic nuclear arms reduction. There too, they differ. The
Russians have talked of far deeper mutual arms cuts than the
Pentagon is willing to accept in a new strategic arms treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The summit could produce some sort of understanding, or effort,
to arrange an early warning system that would share data on
possible missile launches. Berger said some of the technology of a
missile defense system might also be shared.
</P>
<P>
   There is one nuclear agreement in prospect: Clinton and Putin
are expected to sign a deal in which each of their nations will
destroy 34 tons of weapons grade plutonium, enough to produce tens
of thousands of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the diplomatic results, summits are also about
symbolism -- a U.S. president conferring in the Kremlin with a
democratically elected president of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Putin seems less the politician than the burly, backslapping
Boris Yeltsin, who sat opposite Clinton at prior Russia summits,
sometimes in first name friendship, sometimes in explosive tirades.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, the former KGB officer who became Yeltsin's prime
minister, is reserved and cautious, not one to tip a hand of
diplomatic poker. ''I think the United States can do business with
this man,'' Clinton said earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 1556 </TRAILER>
