<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Entrepreneurs to Visit U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Cuban government will allow some private
entrepreneurs who run restaurants and small farms to visit the
United States this fall as part of an exchange program, a senior
U.S. Chamber of Commerce official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Johnstone, vice president of the chamber, outlined the
plan to a reporter after returning from a visit to Cuba that
included talks with officials from Cuba's Chamber of Commerce, a
state entity. Membership in the Cuban chamber is limited to
government-run firms and foreign firms with Cuban government
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   When U.S. chamber officials broached the possibility of
exchanges involving private sector representatives from Cuba last
year, Cuba rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a substantially different atmosphere now,'' Johnstone
said, adding that he expects the Cuban entrepreneurs to visit the
United States in September.
</P>
<P>
   For years, private businesses were forbidden in Cuba but faced
with a steep economic decline earlier this decade, the government
began to allow self-employment in specified areas under strict
controls. There are an estimated 150,000 such enterprises nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the U.S. embargo against Cuba, representatives of
American businesses have been visiting Cuba for years. This coming
week, the fourth US-Cuba Business Summit, to be held in Cancun,
Mexico, and Havana, is expected to attract dozens of U.S. business
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Johnstone, on an unrelated issue, said Cuban officials also
agreed to begin a dialogue with the chamber on compensation for the
thousands of U.S. businesses and other properties that were
nationalized by Cuba during the early stages of the revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Johnstone, a former foreign service officer, said companies
interested in obtaining compensation can explore that possibility,
using the chamber as a go-between with the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government has certified 5,911 U.S. claims for
compensation from Cuba. There has been virtually no headway on the
issue since the claims were certified 30 years ago. Cuba has
expressed a willingness to deal with the compensation issue as part
of a broader settlement with the United States, but Washington has
ruled out such talks so long as the island is under authoritarian
control.
</P>
<P>
   The original combined value of the confiscated properties was
$1.8 billion but that figure has grown several fold over the years
because of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba has its own claims against the United States. Last
November, a Cuban court found the U.S. government liable for deaths
and damage to the island during 40 years of economic sanctions and
other ''aggressive policies.'' It ordered the United States to pay
about $181 billion in reparations but has no way of enforcing the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/wha/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Cuban newspaper Granma: http://www.granma.cu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
