<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hartford hockey team in championship series has core of fans  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- He's still emblazoned with a Hartford
Whalers tattoo, continues to wear their jerseys and refuses to take
down the National Hockey League paraphernalia from the walls of his
New Britain home.
</P>
<P>
   The Whalers are gone, long since moved to North Carolina and
renamed the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop Paul Adamowich from buying tickets to Game
5 of the Hartford Wolf Pack's Calder Cup championship series
against the Rochester Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still hockey fans,'' Adamowich said Friday as he waited
in line at the Hartford Civic Center box office. ''We're still
here. We've got to support the hometown team.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Wolf Pack, of the American Hockey League, has not
found the support that bandwagons a University of Connecticut
basketball team, it has its share of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of them, in fact, said Kevin Kavanagh, director of
public relations for Hartford Sports. The Wolf Pack drew 11,000
people to Game 2 of the championship series last week, Kavanagh
said, and expected close to 12,000 at Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   The team's all-time attendance record is 14,115 people during a
January 1998 game, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolf Pack came to Hartford in 1997. Their increasing
popularity has meant more business for downtown restaurants, bars
and retail shops, said Harry Freeman, executive director of the
Hartford Economic Development Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a very real impact,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   And the fans are flocking, says John Pettit, senior vice
president of Hartford Sports, owners of the Wolf Pack and New
England Sea Wolves arena football team.
</P>
<P>
   During the past three seasons, the Wolf Pack has acquired its
own fans, many of them families with small children, he said. But
now that the team has reached a championship level, some die-hard
Whaler watchers -- whose hearts were broken by the 1997 defection --
are coming back to their beloved sport.
</P>
<P>
   The Calder Cup series, which was tied at 2-2 before Friday's
game, is ''doing a great job putting us on the map with
credibility,'' Kavanagh said. ''We are in the public's eye.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged with a chuckle that it's unusual for a market
such as Hartford to focus on hockey while the temperature hovers
near 90 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a nice problem to have if you're worrying about ice
conditions in June,'' Kavanagh said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Whalers left, Hartford has flirted with several pro
sports franchises, including two abortive efforts to lure the New
England Patriots away from Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Major league action may get more attention than minor league
sports, but Hartford loves a winner, said Dean Pagani, spokesman
for Gov. John G. Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   ''While the attention may not be comparable to a UConn game, I'm
sure the excitement will flow into next season,'' Pagani said.
''It's the kind of thing that builds on year to year. It takes time
to build a franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn's basketball teams have claimed national championships for
the last two years running -- the men in 1999, the women this year.
Pettit said he thinks UConn's winning ways have whetted appetites
for another championship team.
</P>
<P>
   But not far from the Civic Center ticket window, Nathan Miller
and Steve Pinto, both 16, had a different opinion of the Wolf
Pack's success.
</P>
<P>
   ''Minor league hockey doesn't really excite people,'' said
Pinto, an Ellington High School student in Hartford on a field
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Because the games don't have widespread TV coverage, it's hard
for fans to get to know the players, the teens said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's annoying,'' added Miller, a student at Hartford
High School. ''I don't think people do care. Honestly, I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon Scott, a disc jockey with WTIC-FM radio is probably the
Pack's most visible uber-fan. Dressed in full team uniform and
sporting a head of dyed blue hair, Scott does crowd motivation at
the games.
</P>
<P>
   The team's success is ''the blessed rebirth of hockey in
Hartford,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Wolf Pack brings home the Calder Cup? Scott said
he'll paint his entire body blue.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Hartford Wolf Pack -- http://www.wolfpackhockey.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
