<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big donor admits funneling $53,700 to Torricelli campaign  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A political donor who gained White House
access pleaded guilty on Friday to breaking election laws by
funneling $53,700 into the successful 1996 Senate campaign of
then-Rep. Robert Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   David Chang, who operates several trading companies in the
Democrat's former district, has agreed to cooperate with the
Justice Department's investigation into fund-raising abuses in the
1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Chang is among 25 people charged by the Campaign Financing Task
Force and the sixth to admit wrongdoing regarding Torricelli
fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   None of the six has implicated the New Jersey Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Chang was the second international businessman from Bergen
County to plead guilty in as many days regarding the 1996
Torricelli campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, who served on the campaign's finance committee, was to go
on trial Tuesday from indictments returned in December, January and
March.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, David Schertler, declined to say what information
Chang could offer the task force.
</P>
<P>
   In its plea bargain with Chang, prosecutors said they anticipate
filing additional charges against him regarding ''payments made to
a certain former government employee.'' They declined to identify
that person.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, who has described Chang as a friend, is not accused
of any wrongdoing. He has maintained he was unaware of the improper
donations. All such money is donated to charity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Torricelli lawyer Abbe David Lowell said ''the
senator and campaign officials are concerned to learn that David
Chang and people with whom he was working reimbursed some
contributions in the 1996 campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The ''improper acts remain just a handful,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli raised $9.2 million to defeat Rep. Richard A. Zimmer
in 1996. His fund-raising ability led to his appointment as
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell said the ''Justice Department has confirmed that neither
the senator nor anyone in the campaign are the focus of any
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of the campaign task force, Robert J. Conrad, declined
to comment on whether Torricelli was aware of straw donations.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, 57, of Cresskill, pleaded guilty to five misdemeanor
election law violations and a felony obstruction charge -- telling a
potential grand jury witness to lie.
</P>
<P>
   He faces about two years in prison when sentenced Sept. 7, but
the deal calls for prosecutors to request a lesser term if he
provides ''substantial cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 and 1999, Chang made soft-money contributions ranging
from $30,000 to $100,000 to the Democratic Party, which were
interspersed with three White House visits.
</P>
<P>
   He was listed by Mother Jones magazine as one of the nation's
top 400 donors during the 1997-98 election cycle with contributions
of $41,586.
</P>
<P>
   Chang did not speak to reporters after his plea. He remains
under house arrest pending a hearing Monday to reconsider his bail
status.
</P>
<P>
   Chang operates several international trading companies based in
Englewood Cliffs, including Bright &AMP; Bright, Nikko Enterprises Inc.
and Panacom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged conspiring to break donation laws with Cha-Kuek
''Charles'' Koo, an executive with a South Korean conglomerate;
Berek Paul Don, a former Bergen County Republican leader; and Don's
former law partner, Carmine Alampi, a Democratic leader in Bergen
County who served on a Torricelli campaign committee; and unnamed
others.
</P>
<P>
   Federal rules bar corporate contributions. Individuals can
contribute up to $2,000 to a candidate during an election cycle --
primary and general election. Reimbursements are not permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Chang and Koo admitted to roles in ''conduit'' donations, which
are designed to evade restrictions by secretly repaying ''straw
donors'' -- those who supposedly made the contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Don and Alampi pleaded guilty last year to charges related to
soliciting $11,000 worth of donations to the Torricelli campaign,
which Chang admitted he reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   Chang also admitted he collected $21,000 for the Torricelli
campaign in December 1996, improperly reimbursing donors with
Bright &AMP; Bright money.
</P>
<P>
   Chang also admitted arranging 19 flights for Torricelli in late
1996, using Bright &AMP; Bright funds, even though he knew corporations
were barred from making ''in-kind contributions'' to campaigns.
Chang had the campaign report that Bright &AMP; Bright employees had
made the contributions, totaling $1,700, for the travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli spokesman Richard McGrath said the campaign rejected
the $1,700 because it did not cover the cost of the trips. The
campaign reimbursed Bright &AMP; Bright $9,280.75, he said. That sum is
the equivalent of first-class airfare for the trips, which campaign
rules set as the benchmark, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koo pleaded guilty on Thursday to recruiting eight ''straw''
donors at Chang's behest, and Chang on Friday admitted that he gave
Koo $20,000 in cash to reimburse those donors.
</P>
<P>
   Koo, 54, of Alpine, a South Korean citizen, is president of LG
Group's executive office for the Americas in Englewood Cliffs. The
LG Group is one of South Korea's largest conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Chang may yet face charges ''arising from his failure to
disclose the involvement of LG Group in his trade with North
Korea,'' according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   In court on Thursday, Koo acknowledged that in late 1995 Chang's
companies owed LG Group more than $50 million used by Chang to
finance the shipment of goods to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea had failed to pay Chang's companies in full, so
Chang was unable to repay LG Group, Koo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
