<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Ambassador Criticized  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- A Canadian political party leader says Ottawa
should consider bringing its ambassador to the United States home
until the U.S. election is over because of comments he made
appearing to favor Al Gore in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Leader Joe Clark said remarks by Ambassador Raymond
Chretien, nephew of Liberal Prime Minister Jean Chretien, ''could
cause serious implications for Canada down the line in our
relations with the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador, in a speech broadcast Wednesday to officials
back in Ottawa, said of the Democratic presidential candidate: ''We
know Vice President Gore. He knows us. He's a friend of Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Bush, on the other hand, doesn't know us as much.
Seems to have forgotten the name of our prime minister.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to a prank played on George W. Bush in
March by a Canadian TV comic, posing as a reporter, who told Bush
that prime minister ''Jean Poutine'' was endorsing him. Bush, the
likely Republican nominee, did not catch the fake name and
expressed appreciation for the support.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Chretien said in his speech that when the Texas governor
''thinks of borders, he thinks of Mexico, not Canada. Obviously we
have to work on him.'' He also said ''We will deal with whomever is
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Herb Gray defended the ambassador, saying
his intent was not to declare a preference but to emphasize Canada
will maintain strong relations with the United States no matter who
wins.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark, a former prime minister, said any Canadian ambassador
other than Chretien's nephew would have been reprimanded for
talking like that.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may be a good thing to remove him from temptation and to
keep him home for briefings here,'' Clark told The Canadian Press.
</P>
<P>
   Poutine is a fast food meal of french fries, gravy and cheese
curd popular in French-speaking Quebec.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
