<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fired top trooper's personal injury claim dismissed, discrimination lawsuit remains </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A state Superior Court judge Friday
dismissed an attempt by an ousted State Police superintendent to
collect $21 million in a personal injury lawsuit, but kept alive
his claims of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Williams alleges that he was emotionally damaged after Gov.
Christie Whitman ordered his resignation at the height of the
state's racial profiling controversy in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman ordered then Attorney General Peter Verniero to call
Williams at his Mount Laurel home and ask for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   That request came after a newspaper interview quoted Williams
linking minority groups to drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Williams subsequently filed a lawsuit. However, Superior Court
Judge Judith A. Yaskin ruled Friday that Williams did not file the
required notice of his lawsuit to the state until October, well
beyond the 90-day deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Yaskin rejected Williams' argument that he was too emotionally
disturbed to find a lawyer and that he relied on Verniero for legal
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' personal injury lawsuit alleged that he and his wife
suffered severe emotional trauma from the abrupt resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The discrimination charge contends that Whitman wanted Williams
removed so she could replace him with a younger, black man.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Clifford Van Syoc argued that Williams was so emotionally
troubled that he could not seek legal guidance for months.
</P>
<P>
   A psychiatrist hired by Williams reported that the career state
trooper suffered ''adjustment disorder'' until sometime before
meeting with Van Syoc in mid-August that year.
</P>
<P>
   Yaskin said she believes Williams and his claims, but they do
not rise to the standards set by the law for waiving the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ''Carl Williams knew he was injured by his termination and he
knew it was unfair from the outset,'' Yaskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Syoc said he would appeal Yaskin's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Yaskin gave Van Syoc two weeks to provide further legal
arguments on why the discrimination lawsuit should continue. No new
hearing date was scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both Whitman and Verniero argued that Williams can
make no claim of discrimination since he served as a political
appointee.
</P>
<P>
   ''No matter what you do in this case, you can't get around the
fact the man resigned,'' said Wayne Positan, Verniero's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman can appoint a minority to head a council of minority
affairs and an elderly resident to lead a senior citizen
commission, lawyer Rosemary Alito said. That is a matter of public
policy for the executive branch to decide, not for the government's
judicial wing to approve, Alito said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor has an absolute right to make her appointments in
accordance with those considerations,'' Alito said.
</P>
<P>
   Yaskin agreed, saying that the courts could intervene when a
chief operating officer makes such appointments in private
industry, but not when a chief executive does that in government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because there is a difference in making widgets or making
money and making policy in a democracy,'' Yaskin said.
</P>
<P>
   After the 90-minute hearing, Van Syoc said he will proceed with
plans to ask the state for documents and evidence to bolster the
discrimination claims.
</P>
<P>
   Van Syoc said he wants a copy of a photograph of Whitman with a
black man during a State Police patrol of Camden in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to those who have seen the photograph, Whitman is
wearing a white nylon jumpsuit, a baseball cap and black gloves
similar to those used by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The governor appears to be ''arresting and/or frisking a young
black male'' according to another subpoena filed May 2 in state
Superior Court on an unrelated case. Sources familiar with the
operation said the suspect was not charged with any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe it will demonstrate the clear involvement of race
politics in her decision,'' Van Syoc said of the photograph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
