<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Stamp Enrollment Up in March  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- More people were on food stamps in March, but
enrollment in the program was still more than 1 million below the
year before, the government reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment in the program is off about 30 percent over the past
4 years for a variety of reasons, including the strong economy and
tighter eligibility requirements, federal officials say. Some 17.3
million people were on food stamps nationwide in March, an increase
of 98,000 from February.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 37 percent of people eligible for food stamps
aren't getting them, and the Agriculture Department plans a series
of public meetings this summer in seven cities to find what the
government can do to get more of them into the program.
</P>
<P>
   USDA officials say some states have discouraged participation,
and some potential recipients are declining to take food stamps
because of the stigma.
</P>
<P>
   ''As people go to work there is still some confusion about
whether they know they are eligible for benefits,'' said Shirley
Watkins, USDA's undersecretary for food, nutrition and consumer
services. ''One of the things we don't want to see continued is a
continued spiraling down in food stamps when demand for food banks
is going up dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   The meetings will be in New York, Washington, Atlanta, Chicago,
Dallas, Kansas City and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Seven states have recorded enrollment declines of at least 10
percent since March 1999, led by Maryland with a drop of 17.2
percent and Colorado and Nebraska at 15.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment in the program peaked at more than 27 million
nationwide in 1994. At the time, 72 percent of the eligible people
were participating.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton relaxed eligibility rules last July and
announced a public education campaign to stem enrollment declines
in the program. USDA also is asking Congress for $10 million in the
department's 2001 budget to pay for outreach programs.
</P>
<P>
   States could help the working poor by limiting paperwork and
keeping their offices open longer hours so families who need food
stamps can get them, said Ellen Vollinger of the Food Research and
Action Center, an advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ''If people are doing so much better that they don't need the
program, that's fine and perfect. But too many of the people
dropping off the program are still eligible and still in need,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   A family of four that earns up to $1,810 a month is eligible for
the program in most states. Limits in Alaska and Hawaii are higher.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: USDA's Food and Nutrition Service:
http://www.fns.usda.gov/fns
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
