<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pipeline Overseers Seek Record Fine  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Olympic Pipeline Co. should be fined $3.05
million for failing to test and monitor a pipeline that gave way
last year and caused three deaths in Bellingham, Wash., federal
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The fine is the largest ever sought by the Transportation
Department's Research and Special Programs Administration and the
maximum the agency can recommend. The previous record was more than
$600,000 sought against Koch Industries in 1991, a case that was
later settled.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bellingham episode, ''There were sustained and multiple
violations of our safety standards,'' Kelley Coyner, the agency
administrator, said at a news conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Last June 10, two 10-year-old boys and an 18-year-old fisherman
died after a pipeline broke and spewed 229,000 gallons of gasoline
into a Bellingham park. The spilled gasoline ignited into an
enormous fireball that raced more than a mile down a creek.
</P>
<P>
   Research and Special Programs Administration officials detailed
eight proposed fines in the case, including $500,000 each for
failing to have properly trained employees on duty when the pipe
broke, failing to test relief valves at a terminal 15 miles south
of Bellingham and not keeping records of discharge pressure and
abnormal events at pump stations.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Vice President Carl Gast would not comment on the
proposed penalties but defended his company's actions since the
rupture and explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to point out that during the past several months,
Olympic has worked very hard to comply with all of the safety
directives issued by the Office of Pipeline Safety, and even now is
engaged in a comprehensive internal inspections program of its
entire 400-mile network,'' Gast said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline runs from refineries in northwestern Washington
southward to Portland, Ore. A 37-mile segment has been closed since
the blast.
</P>
<P>
   The company contends its pipeline ruptured because of damage
from work on nearby water-carrying pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic has 30 days to request a hearing with the officials of
the agency's chief counsel's office. Those officials would
determine whether grounds exist to sustain the fines.
</P>
<P>
   Either side could ask for a rehearing, and appeals could move
the case into the federal court system. Either side also could
instigate talks to reach a settlement, agency officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason King, 26, a brother of 10-year-old victim Wade King, said
even a $3 million penalty was insufficient punishment for the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that a company is able to, in so many words, deny
responsibility for their own actions and try to place blame on
third parties, ... and then be allowed to continue to operate, is
the real tragedy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic is owned by a consortium of the oil companies Arco,
Equilon Enterprises and GATX. Houston-based Equilon, a joint
venture of Texaco and Shell, operates the line.
</P>
<P>
   The company is seeking to restore full service on the Washington
state line and is conducting comprehensive internal tests of the
pipeline system.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Office of Pipeline Safety, a part of the
Research and Special Programs Administration, are overseeing the
internal testing. Coyner said she could not say when the agency
will decide whether to allow Olympic to reopen the 37-mile section
of pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Research and Special Programs Administration:
http://www.rspa.dot.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
