<HEADLINE> Kosovo Land Mine Kills 2 Serbs  </HEADLINE>
By DANICA KIRKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serb villagers traveling on a back
road drove over a land mine Friday, triggering an explosion that
killed two men and injured a mother and her two young children.
</P>
<P>
   The blast just south of the regional capital, Pristina, prompted
Serb leaders to criticize the Western officials who run Kosovo,
claiming too little is being done to safeguard Serb lives.
</P>
<P>
   The killings -- bringing to eight the number of Serbs killed in
the province this week -- came just weeks before the peacekeepers
mark their first year in the province.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basic security for the Serbs does not exist, they are still
being killed. That has even been intensified,'' said Olivier
Ivanovic, leader of the Serbs in the divided northern town of
Kosovska Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanovic said the attacks were aimed at driving the remaining
Serb population out.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials have been trying to persuade the tens of
thousands of Serbs who fled this Albanian-dominated province after
NATO airstrikes last year to return home.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-led peacekeepers said the two men, who were killed, were
driving from their village of Batuse toward Gracanica, five miles
south of Pristina, when their vehicle drove over the mine.
</P>
<P>
   Natasa Ristic, 32, and her daughters, 5 and 2, were in the back
seat of the car, but escaped with cuts and scratches, said Capt.
Kath Hurley, a spokeswoman for the British forces.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was just a big bang all of a sudden. I do not remember
anything else,'' Ristic told Belgrade television. ''I pulled my
children out.''
</P>
<P>
   The independent news agency Beta reported that Serbs from Kosovo
Polje and the surrounding villages demanded Friday that the
commander of the peacekeepers in Kosovo visit them next week and
promise to ''stop violence and terror against Serbs and find and
punish those responsible for terrorist acts against Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Polje Serbs threatened to block a major road between
the cities of Pristina and Pec unless their demands are fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Even before this week's attacks, Serbs were fleeing the
province, fearing retaliation for Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's 18-month crackdown on ethnic Albanian militants.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus has been the most marked in the American sector,
where the greatest number of Serb enclaves remained after the war,
said Peter Kessler of the U.N. refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''In some communities, every single Serb property is for sale,''
Kessler said. ''In some communities, if the pace of departures
continues, there will be no Serbs left by the end of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
