<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Closing arguments delivered in Russell Peeler trial  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Prosecutors admit their case against a
Bridgeport man accused of plotting the murders of an 8 year-old boy
and his mother consists largely of the tangled testimony of drug
addicts, criminals and an admitted liar.
</P>
<P>
   But in closing arguments Friday, they asked jurors to believe
that testimony, saying the horrific killings of Leroy ''B.J.''
Brown and his mother, Karen Clarke, compelled Russell Peeler's drug
associates and jailhouse buddies to testify against him.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers argued that those witnesses knew they could get
lighter treatment from the state if they implicated Peeler.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler is accused of masterminding the murders to prevent the
boy from testifying against him in the 1998 slaying of Clarke's
boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Adrian Peeler, is accused of being the actual
triggerman who killed the mother and son in January 1999 in their
Bridgeport home. Adrian Peeler is awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler's case is scheduled to go to the jury Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In more than 100 minutes of arguments, Bridgeport State's
Attorney Jonathan Benedict reviewed how carefully they prosecutors
believe the killings were planned out and how the Peeler brothers'
alibis were crafted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who in the entire world would have anything to gain from the
killing of this little boy, other than Russell Peeler?'' Benedict
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler was required to be home by 9 p.m. and was wearing
an electronic monitor that kept track of his whereabouts. In the
weeks leading up to the killing, he was home a little after 9 p.m.
each day, but on the day of the killing, he was home by 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A record of cellular telephone calls showed Adrian was talking
on the telephone at about the time of the killings, and he checked
into a Milford motel no later than 6:35 p.m. that night. Witnesses
testified the shooting happened at around 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous witnesses, including the Peelers' drug associates and
people Russell met in prison, testified they heard allusions to the
killings, before and after the alleged plan was carried out.
</P>
<P>
   But the state's star witness, Josephine Lee, also was their most
problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who lived across the street from Clarke and B.J., testified
she agreed to be a lookout for Adrian Peeler in exchange for a
handful of crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said she waited for Clarke and B.J. to get home, then rang
their doorbell. When Clarke opened the door, Adrian Peeler started
shooting, Lee testified.
</P>
<P>
   She recanted these statements in letters to her landlord,
writing: ''I was scared when the police came to the house to get me
so I told them that I had something to do with the murder. But I do
not know anything.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lee was called back on the stand, she said the letters were
lies.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer John Walkley said Lee's story did not match the
forensic evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Lee testified Clarke was shot in an upstairs bedroom, where she
fled to use the phone, but no bullet was found there. She said the
shooting started when Clarke and B.J. were running up the stairs,
but blood was found near the door and people who heard the gunshots
said they were loud, as if they happened outside.
</P>
<P>
   No forensic evidence was found to show that Lee or Adrian Peeler
were ever in the house, Walkley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Adrian Peeler was never there. Josephine Lee was never
there,'' Walkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Judge G. Sarsfield Ford denied a defense request to add two
other letters to evidence. In the letters, Lee states that she was
in bed with her landlord's son at the time and does not know
anything about the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish that somebody will come fort and tell the truth,'' she
wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
