<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Up 231; Dow Up 143  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index wrapped up its best
week in history Friday as investors poured money back into the
technology stocks they had abandoned amid fears of rising interest
rates. Stocks soared after the government's employment report
raised hopes that economic growth is slowing to a less inflationary
pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq rose 230.88 points, or by 6.4 percent, to close at
3,813.38. The index rose 608.27 points for the week -- a stunning 19
percent gain that easily eclipsed the previous record of 9.7
percent from April 17-21.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's dramatic recovery was just part of a broad-based
advance that saw every major market index post sharp gains. The Dow
Jones industrial average rose 142.56 points to close at 10,794.76.
For the week, the Dow shot up 495.52 points, or 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also sharply higher. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 rose 28.45 to 1,477.26.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is wild on Wall Street today,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior
vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. ''We are now hearing talk again
of the Nasdaq going above 4,000 and the Dow through 11,000, which
we didn't think we'd hear so soon.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with the gains, the Nasdaq index remains 24.5 percent,
or more than 1,200 points below the record 5,048.62 set March 10,
less than three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks zoomed Friday after Wall Street received exactly the news
traders had hoped for: a clear sign of moderation in the red-hot
growth rate of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported that the unemployment rate climbed
back to 4.1 percent in May from a 30-year low of 3.9 percent in
April. The jobless rate rose as American businesses cut 116,000
jobs, the worst showing in nearly nine years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the weak jobs report, the Labor Department said
average hourly earnings rose just 0.1 percent in May, a sharp
slowdown after a 0.4 percent increase in April.
</P>
<P>
   That still left labor markets tight, but eased many fears of an
inflationary spike in wages that could bring down the longest
economic expansion in U.S. history. The figures delighted investors
who gave in to growing optimism that the Fed's six interest rate
increases since last June might finally be having an impact on the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The most optimistic said that few, if any, additional rate hikes
will be needed to keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the odds have now changed and there will not be
another rate hike soon,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, director of
market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis. ''I think
the Fed will be out of our face for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Added ammunition came from the Commerce Department, which
reported orders to American factories fell by 4.3 percent in April,
the biggest decline since November 1990, when the country was mired
in the last recession.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks led the rally, with investors snapping up
shares of market leaders that have been battered in the past few
weeks. JDS Uniphase rose $12.125 to $110.375 and Intel jumped $4.50
to $134.188.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are vulnerable to rising interest rates,
were also higher. Citigroup rose $2.75 to $66.063, J.P. Morgan
gained $6.625 to $138.563 and Chase Manhattan rose $3.50 to
$80.625.
</P>
<P>
   Online brokerages, which have slumped in recent weeks as trading
volume has weakened, were also significantly higher. Schwab Corp.
rose $4.50 to $32.938.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, volume was brisk as investors who had stepped to the
sidelines to await the jobless report eagerly jumped back into the
market. On every major index, advancing stocks easily outnumbered
decliners.
</P>
<P>
   ''Volume and breadth have really improved,'' said Tony Dwyer,
chief market strategist with Kirlin Holdings. ''You put that
together with the weak economic reports and a washed-out market and
it looks pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 1.39
billion shares, compared with 1.15 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, advancers led by a 7-to-2 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 20.57 to
513.03.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.6 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index rose 2.3 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
gained 2.4 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 1.1 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
