<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Probe Caused FBI-Justice Tensions  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Quarrels between the Justice Department and
the FBI over appointment of an independent campaign finance
investigator had a ''devastating impact'' on relations among those
investigating fund-raising abuses, officials acknowledged in a
report obtained Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The differences -- Justice's determination that no special
prosecutor was warranted and the FBI's support for one -- have
surfaced before. But the General Accounting Office report, based on
interviews with several key players, described the disagreements
and their impact in detail.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Radek, chief of the Justice Department's public integrity
section, spoke to congressional investigators as did FBI officials
about the bitterness that has enveloped the department's Campaign
Finance Task Force, created in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno has kept the investigation under
Justice Department control, unswayed by arguments by Republican
lawmakers, FBI Director Louis Freeh and former task force chief
Charles LaBella.
</P>
<P>
   The animosity became so severe that Freeh, seeking an expansive
probe, ordered his agents to strike out on their own to interview
White House and Democratic Party officials. Cautious prosecutors
not only opposed the move but told the GAO that the agents
virtually paralyzed the task force's operations for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the prosecutors and agents had to be separated on
separate floors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Radek said that he believed that the FBI was too anxious
to recommend the need for an Independent Counsel and that in his
opinion the information gathered did not justify seeking the
appointment of an independent counsel,'' the report said. ''He
added that their disagreement over this issue had a devastating
impact on the relationship between the FBI and PI (the Public
Integrity section).''
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department statement said Friday that ''it is not news
that there were fundamental disagreements in 1997 between
prosecutors and FBI investigators'' but contended that Reno and
Freeh ''moved decisively'' to bring in new leadership and address
the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing in the report suggests that the frictions continued
beyond that time, and one only need look at the task force's
success record to see that any personal disagreements that may have
existed three years ago did not affect the task force's work
product,'' the department said.
</P>
<P>
   Radek's comments referred to the period in 1997 when he was
directly in control of the investigation, but even after he
relinquished the direct role, he remained a key player in opposing
an independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Gallagher, an FBI assistant director, ''believed that Mr.
Radek's criteria for what information was needed to trigger the
seeking of an independent counsel were too stringent,'' the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh recommended to Reno in a November 1997 memo that she seek
an independent investigation, and in July 1998, LaBella made the
same recommendation. Reno refused on grounds evidence was
insufficient to trigger the independent counsel law, which since
has expired.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreements encompassed other matters, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials also accused the attorneys of ''excessive
participation in traditional investigative functions, especially
interviews of witnesses where agents felt they were being used
mainly as note takers.''
</P>
<P>
   There were severe differences in the investigative approach,
with the Justice prosecutors seeking to build the investigation
methodically, ''from the ground up,'' and the FBI agents trying
''to pursue several investigative tracks simultaneously.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice officials wanted ''to avoid prematurely tipping off
potential witnesses and investigative targets,'' the report said.
It added that Radek ''did not believe specific predication existed
... to justify all the investigative tracks proposed by the
investigators.'' He also ''believed the press created expectations
for a major scandal, rather than allowing the investigative process
to make that determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher said that on the basis of news reports about White
House coffees for campaign contributors, ''The FBI wanted to
investigate ... whether the White House had violated campaign
finance laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, Freeh directed investigators to interview more
than 100 individuals including White House and Democratic National
Committee employees who were not yet the focus of the task force
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the task force at the time, Laura Ingersoll, said as
a result of the interviews, 90 percent of the investigative
resources were unavailable for two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The task force has charged 25 individuals and one corporation
for violations of campaign finance laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 1927 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School construction bill faces uphill political, legal battles  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A day after an Assembly committee
unenthusiastically released a multibillion dollar school
construction bill to the full House, two questions emerged Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Will the measure pass? And is it constitutional?
</P>
<P>
   The first question will be answered Monday, when the Assembly
considers the legislation that pumps no more than $6 billion into
30 poor school districts and $2.5 billion into all other New Jersey
districts to repair or replace crumbling and overcrowded school
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the second question is not so clear. Critics,
though, say the bill does not comply with the state Supreme Court's
order that the state pay full freight for building projects in the
poor schools, no matter how much they cost.
</P>
<P>
   But fiscal controls, including final legislative oversight over
spending, are needed to rein in escalating costs in what amounts to
the state's largest building program in history, according to
Assemblyman Joseph Malone, R-Burlington, the bill co-sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing in there that's onerous,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Venetis, of the Constitutional Litigation Clinic at
Rutgers University School of Law, said she believes a clause
inserted by Assembly Republicans granting the Legislature veto
power over special needs spending runs afoul of court rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's ridiculous. That wasn't contemplated by the court,''
she said. ''It completely politicizes the process.''
</P>
<P>
   All bill backers will accomplish is to force the issue back into
court, Venetis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a tremendous waste of resources, if people have to run
back to the Supreme Court every few weeks,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Sciarra of the Education Law Center, the group that sued
the state more than 25 years ago on behalf of poor school children,
agreed with Venetis that the Assembly is usurping the court's
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Sciarra said he would rather see lawmakers exercise control over
the state agency that will ultimately be charged with managing
construction in the poor schools. The state has never taken on such
a huge task.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last thing we want is to launch this and then six months
later have the newspapers report that the program is mired in
delay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said such direct control over the poor schools is
necessary because voters in those districts will have no say over
local projects. He said he wants to prevent local abuse of the
state funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like, this good old boy talking to that good old boy about a
project he really likes, and nobody can do anything about it,'' the
assemblyman said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone answered that critics have selective memories. Democrats
have clamored for more state oversight of the state's embattled
auto emissions system, for example, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They harped about no oversight on Parsons, now here we are
spending the largest amount of money in state history and no one
wants oversight? On the stupid scale, that goes to about a 12,''
the assemblyman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sciarra also took issue with the addition of spending caps in
the Assembly bill. Both the Assembly version and a competing Senate
version that passed two weeks ago assume about the same level of
spending; only the Assembly bill caps those amounts.
</P>
<P>
   He said special needs districts' spending needs actually top $7
billion, and that does not include extra space for court-ordered
preschool programs. The numbers could still grow depending on the
outcome of a review of the Department of Education, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''To cap the program now when we don't have a handle on the full
universe of needs is deeply problematic,'' he said. ''That would
violate the court decree. The court wanted a needs-driven
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he has no idea whether the bill will pass Monday. It
was released from the Assembly Appropriations Committee Thursday on
a party line vote. Committee members released it ''without
recommendation,'' meaning they are leaving it up to their
colleagues in the full House to make the final call.
</P>
<P>
   ''Monday's going to be interesting. Whatever happens, happens,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed concerns that the Legislature may miss the Supreme
Court's spring 2000 deadline to make the money available to the
special needs schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing sacred about that deadline,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone placed on Assembly Democrats, who comprise the minority
in the House, the responsibility of passing the bill. He noted that
most special needs districts are located in Democratic strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   ''They want the benefit, they'll have to do the heavy lifting,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblyman Joseph Suliga, D-Union, pointed out that Malone
ignores the fact that the Senate version of the school construction
bill, which contains no caps or lawmaker oversight, passed with
bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Suliga was not sure whether Democrats will take a party position
Monday opposing the bill. Of the 11 members he spoke to Friday, out
of 35, all said they will vote no, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the bill passes, though, Suliga said it may face an
uphill battle in the Senate, where it would have to go next because
differences between the bills remain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-02-00 1930 </TRAILER>
