<HEADLINE> N.C. Congressman Pays Property Tax  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYLVA, N.C. (AP) -- U.S. Rep. Charles Taylor has paid, under
protest, $3,800 in back property taxes owed on forest land he owns
in his home district, his congressional office said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A tax collector sent Taylor and the congressional pay office a
garnishment notice May 1 for the unpaid taxes. Jackson County
officials said Taylor did not submit the proper paperwork to keep
the acreage in a land-use management program, where it was taxed at
a reduced rate. Taylor paid the reduced rate, but owed the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign leaders accused Taylor's Democratic opponent,
attorney Sam Neill, of persuading county tax officials to pursue
the claim -- charges Neill has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has a hearing pending before the Jackson County Tax
Appeals Board. He is confident the payment ''will be returned once
the appeal process moves beyond the control of the Democrat
Party-dominated Jackson County board,'' spokesman Roger France
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
