<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Chavez Ally Says He's Innocent  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA HERNANDEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- The leader of Venezuela's legislature,
a key ally of President Hugo Chavez, told the country's highest
court Friday that he was innocent of the corruption charges against
him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have done nothing but fight in the trenches of the people
for my entire life, spending the best years of my youth in jail
defending the interests of the democracy we enjoy today,'' Luis
Miquilena, who was imprisoned a half century ago for opposing a
military dictatorship, told the Supreme Tribunal of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Miquilena comes at a politically charged moment
for Chavez, a former paratrooper who took office on an
anti-corruption platform but whose administration is now plagued by
allegations of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez remains popular among the poor majority of the South
American nation's 23 million people. However, critics blame him for
an economic recession and accuse him of amassing too much power.
</P>
<P>
   Miquilena's lawyers on Friday asked the Supreme Tribunal to drop
the investigation, saying the attorney general failed to present
any real evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of pro-Chavez demonstrators gathered outside the high
court Friday, and about 20 policemen arrived at the scene to head
off street violence.
</P>
<P>
   The case against the congressional head is likely to add to
Chavez's political woes because it follows the suspension of last
Sunday's general elections due to technical glitches and the
resignation on Monday of the entire electoral board.
</P>
<P>
   Miquilena was the president of an assembly that rewrote
Venezuela's constitution, and is currently the president of the
temporary legislature. He was also instrumental in selecting the
electoral council members who were forced to resign this week.
</P>
<P>
   Miquilena faces charges stemming from a state contract awarded
to a printing company in which he holds shares. He is also accused
of giving a lucrative Justice Ministry contract to an insurance
company owned by a business partner.
</P>
<P>
   His attorneys dismissed the allegations. Attorney General Javier
Elechiguerra said Friday he wasn't ''accusing'' Miquilena, but
instead sought to open an investigation and reach a conclusion of
innocence or guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The court now has five days to decide whether to continue with
an investigation against Miquilena or drop the charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
