<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A fast moving storm fells trees and power lines, some homes damaged </HEADLINE>
AP Photos
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A fast-moving storm thundered through
eastern and central New York on Friday, felling trees and power
lines and leaving thousands of residents without electricity.
</P>
<P>
   In Syracuse, there were as many as 6,000 people without power.
In eastern New York, Columbia and Saratoga County were hit
particularly hard. Officials from Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.
reported that as many as 25,000 people were without power.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're expecting to have power restored to the majority of our
customers in eastern New York by midnight,'' Nick Lyman, a
spokesman for NiMo, said. ''But we expect to work throughout the
night and for much of Saturday to restore power for the rest of
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Saratoga County Sheriff's Department,
significant damage was reported in the town of Milton, were as many
as ten homes were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had multiple houses with trees on them and road closures,''
Saratoga County Undersheriff Michael Woodcock said. ''No injuries
were reported as a result of the storm.''
</P>
<P>
   In central New York, thunder, lightning and high winds also
brought down trees and caused power outages.
</P>
<P>
   In parts of Syracuse, winds moved as fast as 55 mph. In East
Syracuse, Wal-Mart shoppers got quite a scare when lightning struck
the building. Merchandise outside the store was also damaged.
</P>
<P>
   High winds knocked over swing sets, trashed bicycles and brought
down tents. Some of the hardest hit areas in central New York were
Lysander, Manlius and DeWitt, according to NiMo officials.
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Electric and Gas Corporation says the storm
knocked out power for about 3,500 of their customers, most of them
in the Town of Owasco, the Village of Cayuga, and the City of
Auburn.
</P>
</TEXT>
