<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Rebels Issue Warning  </HEADLINE>
By CESAR GARCIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A guerrilla group announced Friday it
would arrest corrupt officials and businessmen, making it the
latest in a series of controversial rebel ''laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement follows previous rebel edicts including one
vowing to kidnap millionaires who refuse to pay rebel ''peace
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas have long kidnapped the wealthy for ransom and
executed or subjected local officials to ''revolutionary trials''
for alleged corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But by issuing ''laws'' formalizing these practices, the FARC is
apparently trying to claim status as a parallel government.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy seeks to stem ''the systematic sacking of public
finances,'' Raul Reyes of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, or FARC, said in a telephone interview with The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Officials found to have stolen public funds or facilitated their
theft may be arrested, fined, and forced to return the money -- with
interest. Those offering bribes will face the same punishment those
who pocket them.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC's latest ''law'' comes after months of political
turmoil following President Andres Pastrana's March 30 proposal to
dissolve congress through a popular anti-corruption referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The plan resonated with Colombians fed up with the Andean
country's daily diet of corruption scandals, including revelations
earlier this year of $2.7 million in phony contracts by the
congress.
</P>
<P>
   However, Pastrana withdrew his plan a week ago after opposition
legislators threatened to force new presidential elections in the
same referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides demonstrated they are only interested in protecting
their shares of the public ''cake'', the FARC said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
