<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From Friday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressINTERLEAGUE:
Tigers-Cubs:
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT: Juan Gonzalez was back in the starting lineup after
missing three games because of a sore foot but may be sidelined
after aggravating it while running the bases when he hit a triple.
A bone scan and MRI done Thursday were negative. ''It's a relief
for the player to know (there's no break),'' manager Phil Garner
said. ... Someone posted a newspaper clipping from a Chicago paper
in the Detroit clubhouse which implied the Tigers were pushovers.
Garner claimed innocence.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: INF Julio Zuleta was sent to Triple-A Iowa and
switch-hitting OF Gary Matthews Jr., son of the former Cubs
outfielder, was recalled. Zuleta was told to play some third base
as well as first in the minors. ... Scott Downs posted his second
career win Friday with Rick Aguilera's 300th save. When Downs
recorded his first major league victory on April 15, Aguilera ended
that game with his 1,000th career strikeout.
Orioles-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: The Orioles have lost 17 straight games in Canada
since their last win in Toronto on June 12, 1998. The Expos swept a
three-game set from Baltimore in Montreal from June 26-28, 1998 in
the Orioles' only previous appearance at Olympic Stadium. Baltimore
has lost its last 14 games at Toronto's SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: The Expos wore a black No. 9 on the right sleeve of
their jerseys Friday night in honor of Montreal Canadiens hockey
great Maurice ''Rocket'' Richard, who died last Saturday. The
tribute, which will also appear on the team's road jerseys, will
continue for the rest of the season. It's the first time in major
league history that an individual from another sport has been so
honored. A moment of silence was observed prior to Friday night's
game against Baltimore. ... C Charlie O'Brien has changed his
number from 2 to 21.
Blue Jays-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   BLUE JAYS: Toronto has outhomered opponents 61-32 at SkyDome,
but the Blue Jays have been outhomered 32-26 on the road. ...
Friday's game was the first of a seven-day road trip. Toronto will
travel to Atlanta for three games next week and then play an
exhibition game June 8 against the Tennessee Smokies, their
Southern League Double-A affiliate. ... Overall since May 23,
Toronto is in a stretch where it will play 31 of 43 games on the
road before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   MARLINS: Florida has the best record of any team in interleague
play, notching a 31-18 record against the American League entering
this weekend's series. The Houston Astros at 26-18 are next best,
followed by the New York Mets and Cleveland Indians at 28-21. ''The
last two years, I think in some ways teams looked past us,'' OF
Mark Kotsay said. ''They see us a young club they can come in and
take advantage of, take a couple of games from. But it also seems
like we elevate our game against the good teams. I don't have an
explanation.'' ... In an effort to attract more young fans, the
Marlins are launching a television show for children on FOX Sports
Net. The half-hour program, Marlins Strike Zone, will air for 16
Saturday mornings beginning this weekend. ... Top prospect Josh
Beckett, 19, returned to the mound earlier this week after a 48-day
absence due to shoulder tendinitis. He pitched two innings to notch
his first professional victory for Single-A Kane County. The No. 2
overall pick in last year's draft, Beckett allowed an unearned run
on two singles and no walks.
Royals-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: 3B Joe Randa's contract has been extended through
2001. He would have been eligible for salary arbitration following
this season. Randa started his career with Kansas City, spent the
1997 season with Pittsburgh, played for Detroit in 1998 and then
was traded back to the Royals. He took a .326 average in Friday's
game with seven home runs and 34 RBIs. ... DH Dave McCarty lost his
position because Friday's game was played in a National League
park. McCarty has a nine-game hitting streak and is coming off a
series in Boston in which he was 6-for-13 with a home run and five
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Reserve OF Adrian Brown has literally built himself
into a useful player. He has spent plenty of time in the weight
room bulking up and hits the ball with more authority. Brown is an
asset to the Pirates because he switch hits, can be used as a pinch
runner and plays all three outfield positions well. ... Manager
Gene Lamont admitted he and the staff have discussed the idea of
moving Jose Silva into the starting rotation. The fifth spot could
be open because Jimmy Anderson has struggled (1-3, 6.39 ERA) in his
rookie season. The Pirates pushed back Anderson's turn this time
through the rotation because of Thursday's open date. Anderson's
next start will be Tuesday against Detroit.
Devil Rays-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Trying to win their third straight game for the first
time this season, the Devil Rays returned to the city where they
last won three in a row although not to the same stadium. Tampa Bay
won its final three games of a series at Yankee Stadium last Sept.
25-27, 1999, and have not won three straight since. ... The Devil
Rays have had 14 games decided in the last inning, tied with Los
Angeles for the most in the majors. They are 5-9 in those 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Manager Bobby Valentine reshuffled his lineup Friday
night after C Mike Piazza was sent to a Manhattan hospital for an
MRI as a result of being hit by Gary Sheffield's bat Wednesday
night in Los Angeles. Robin Ventura moved into the cleanup spot and
Todd Pratt took over at catcher, hitting sixth. ... Pre-game roster
moves also left the Mets short personnel with two players reporting
from Norfolk (OF Ryan McGuire and C Vance Wilson), OF Jon Nunnally
designated for assignment and utilityman Lenny Harris not yet
arrived from Arizona after the trade with the Diamondbacks for P
Bill Pulsipher.
Red Sox-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Knuckleballer Tim Wakefield will start for the Red Sox
on Saturday night in place of Pedro Martinez. Wakefield has made
two starts this season allowing four runs in 8 2-3 innings. He
leads the bullpen with 33 2-3 innings, with a 1-3, 4.28 era. ...
Reliever Rod Beck, who has been on the DL since March 19 with a
nerve problem in his neck, has been assigned on injury-rehab to
Pawtucket of the International league.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Paul Byrd, who was on the 1999 NL All-Star team,
was optioned to Scranton Wilkes-Barre on Friday had no excuses in
regards to his demotion. ''I just haven't been able to keep the
ball down,'' said Byrd, who is 1-5 with a 7.86 ERA. ''I'm going to
try to make some radical changes in my delivery and hopefully
things will work out.''
Twins-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Twins pitchers went 1-for-18 without an RBI or a run
scored in interleague games last season, striking out eight times.
... In Minnesota's last seven games, their starters had gone 5-2
with a 2.61 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: 1B Sean Casey is confident he'll pull out of his
.227 season slump. ''There's no way I would ever hit .220 for the
year,'' he said. ''If I do, I'll be the first to get on a flight
home. I believe in my ability. I know I'll put things together.
It's just a matter of when.''
Yankees-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Orlando Hernandez was back in the rotation after
missing one start with tightness in his back. El Duque started the
season 4-0, then lost his next four decisions. ... Yankees owner
George Steinbrenner was not in Atlanta for the series opener.
Instead, The Boss watched the Class A Tampa Yankees play the Fort
Myers Miracle with team vice president of player personnel Billy
Connors. ... Derek Jeter had three hits in three of his first five
games after being coming off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: The Braves have the best home record in the majors, but
they haven't fared well at Turner Field in interleague games. Prior
to Friday night's game, Atlanta was 9-14 at home when facing AL
teams, compared with a 17-9 mark on the road since the format was
instituted in 1997. ... Bruce Chen failed to capitalize on two
chances to earn a spot in the Braves rotation, but he had been one
of the most effective members of the bullpen since being recalled
from the minors. The 22-year-old left-hander was 4-0 with a 1.93
ERA in 12 relief appearances before Friday.
White Sox-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Kip Wells, Chicago's starter on Saturday, grew up in
nearby Missouri City, Texas, and he wonders what all the flap is
about with realignment. He likes it just the way it is with the
White Sox playing the Astros every year. ''As long as we keep
coming here, it's fine,'' he said. ''It's nice to get a few nights'
sleep in your own bed. I've still got a couple of days to relax,
see my friends and eat some of that good Houston food.''
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Manager Larry Dierker expects his team's bad fortunes
to change. ''We've got to find some kind of streak somewhere when
we go for 10 or more days of playing good baseball and we begin to
believe we're going to play good baseball and begin to expect a
positive outcome,'' he said. ''We're not getting killed. I just
feel like we're not far away from starting to play better and
moving back toward .500.''
Indians-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: The Indians have placed 12 players on the disabled
list, with OF Manny Ramirez the latest addition on Friday due to a
leg injury. Since May 18, the Indians have made a total of 26
player transactions. ... The Indians had already used 18 pitchers,
five of them rookies. The team record is 26 in 1993 and they used
25 last year. ... Bartolo Colon, 5-2 with a 4.66 ERA, makes his
eighth start on Saturday. He was on the disabled list from April 16
to May 12 with a pulled left oblique muscle. ... Manager Charlie
Manuel is trying hard to conserve closer Steve Karsay, who has 10
saves in 12 chances. All but six of his 23 appearances have lasted
one inning. ''Our biggest goal is to get to Karsay in the ninth,''
Manuel said. ''I don't want to burn him out.''
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Garrett Stephenson, the first Cardinals pitcher to
start 8-0 since Bob Gibson in 1965, will go for his ninth straight
victory Saturday night. He says he pitched better in 1997, when he
finished 8-6 with the Phillies in his first full season, but didn't
get the run support. ''I don't think Randy Johnson goes in and
envisions he's going to be 9-0 or 10-0,'' Stephenson said.
''Because he knows he needs the rest of his team. He's not alone,
and he's an awesome pitcher.'' ... The Cardinals entered the game
19-24 in interleague play. Manager Tony La Russa used to be a big
fan. ''It's interesting,'' he said. ''It'd be more interesting if
we were seeing different divisions.''
Diamondbacks-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: When Mike Morgan takes Randy Johnson's spot in the
Arizona rotation for Monday's game at the Chicago Cubs, the
40-year-old pitcher will be facing one of his 11 former teams.
Morgan played for the Cubs from 1992-95 and then again in 1998
before playing last season in Texas. Johnson (9-1) is skipping his
next start because of pain in his pitching shoulder. ... Arizona's
interleague opener at Texas on Friday night began a 16-game stretch
in which the Diamondbacks will play 13 games on the road. After
playing three games each at Arlington and the Chicago Cubs, Arizona
returns to Bank One Ballpark for three games against Anaheim before
seven more games away.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: P Darren Oliver, who has complained of having a tired arm
in his last two starts, will likely miss his next scheduled start
for the Rangers. Manager Johnny Oates said he won't make a final
decision until consulting with the team's doctor, but anticipates
that someone will be called up from Triple-A Oklahoma to make
Oliver's start Monday against Los Angeles. Oliver (2-3 in his 11
starts) should return to the rotation June 11 vs. Colorado.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Rockies-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Jeff Cirillo, in his first season with the Rockies
after five-plus years with Milwaukee, likes playing at Coors Field,
where the Rockies are 19-6 this season. ''It's a great place to
hit. You go up to the plate with confidence,'' said Cirillo, who is
hitting. 324. ... Cirillo doesn't remember ever being six games
above .500 in the major leagues. ... Although appearing in 21
games, reliever Mike Myers has pitched only 8 2-3 innings. He has a
0.00 ERA. ... The Rockies started this weekend's series in
Milwaukee with a five-game winning streak, their longest since
winning seven straight in September 1998. Their 28-22 record is the
team's best after 50 games.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: C Henry Blanco is returning home to Venezuela to be
with his father, who has cancer. Blanco dressed Friday, but manager
Davey Lopes said he wouldn't play against the Rockies. ''He's very
close to his father,'' Lopes said. ''He's too distraught to play.
It's not good. He can stay as long as he has to.'' ... The Brewers
are 10-3 in games started by former Colorado pitchers Jimmy Haynes
(6-3, 4.20 ERA) and Jamey Wright (1-0, 6.35 ERA). Wright will start
Saturday and Haynes goes Sunday against their ex-teammates. ... C
Tyler Houston was activated from the 15-day DL. To make room for
Houston, the Brewers placed OF Lyle Mouton on the DL (strained
hamstring) retroactive to May 27. ... P Hector Ramirez, outrighted
to Triple-A Indianapolis on May 30, opted for free agency. ... Mark
Loretta leads NL shortstops with a .991 fielding percentage (2
errors in 224 chances).
</P>
</TEXT>
