<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xerox Shootings Trial Delayed  </HEADLINE>
By JEAN CHRISTENSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- Jurors in the murder trial of a Xerox copier
repairman who gunned down seven co-workers were forced to take a
10-day break beginning Friday so the judge could teach a legal
course on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said the intermission was unusual, particularly
since last November's rampage was one of the nation's deadliest
workplace shootings and the worst mass killing in Hawaii history.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said the break raises the prospect that jurors will
be exposed to news coverage of the case, but defense attorney Jerel
Fonseca said he does not consider that a problem. Prosecutor Peter
Carlisle declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if it's going to be problem, but it obviously is
a concern,'' said Honolulu attorney Keith Shigetomi, who is not
connected to the case. ''If you're the defense, you're always
concerned about the impact of delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Marie Milks informed both sides before the trial
began May 15 that she was teaching a course on legal ethics at the
National Judicial College in Minneapolis next week. Closing
arguments will be held when the trial resumes on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   The defense does not dispute that the defendant, Byran Uyseugi,
40, shot and killed the seven Xerox employees, but he has pleaded
innocent by reason of insanity. He would face up to life in prison
if convicted. Hawaii does not have the death penalty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 2103 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
