<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Putin: Fight Rogue Missiles Together
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian political and military officials lined up Friday
behind President Vladimir Putin's proposal that Russia and the United States
work jointly on a nuclear defense against so-called rogue nations. President
Clinton was due to arrive in Moscow on Saturday for talks with the new Russian
leader. Topping the agenda at the summit will be the U.S. proposal to modify the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. The United States wants to construct a
national missile defense against possible nuclear strikes by states such as
North Korea and Iran, which it fears may acquire nuclear weapons. Russia objects
to ABM Treaty changes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
UN Won't Probe Charges Vs. NATO
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The chief U.N. war crimes prosecutor said today there
was no basis for a U.N. investigation into allegations that NATO committed war
crimes during its air campaign on Yugoslavia. ''Although some mistakes were made
by NATO, I am very satisfied that there was no deliberate targeting of civilians
or unlawful military targets by NATO during the bombing campaign,'' Carla del
Ponte told the Security Council.
</P>
