<HEADLINE> UN Wants Money for Women's Issues  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Five years after most of the world's
nations pledged in Beijing to push for women's equality, a lack of
money and political will have largely thwarted progress toward the
goal, the president of the U.N. General Assembly said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Theo-Ben Gurirab spoke ahead of Monday's opening of a five-day
conference to review progress on the platform for action adopted at
the 1995 U.N. women's conference in Beijing, which laid out a
roadmap for achieving equality for women.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there had been political will we would have gone a long way
toward meeting the goals and objectives set in Beijing,'' said
Gurirab, who is expected to be elected president of next week's
special session of the General Assembly to assess progress since
the Beijing conference.
</P>
<P>
   The platform of action, adopted by consensus by 189 countries,
called on governments to revise laws to ensure equal rights for
women, equal education for girls, and to ensure the right of women
to decide matters of sexual and reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
   It also urged governments and businesses to put women in top
decision-making positions and called for the elimination of
violence against women.
</P>
<P>
   Gurirab, who is also Namibia's foreign minister, said that a
''failure to provide the necessary financial resources to implement
the agreed commitments'' also contributed to the failure to reach
the Beijing goals.
</P>
<P>
   At next week's conference, ministers from 188 countries are
expected to debate, and possibly adopt, a new action plan to speed
up implementation of the Beijing platform. U.N. officials are
expecting 10,000 men and women to attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
   In two reports published this week, the United Nations said that
although progress could be noted in several fields -- including
education, health, and the participation of women in politics --
there remains much to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ''Women still are among the most illiterate, they are certainly
the largest proportion of the poor and the hungry, they suffer from
dislocation, violence, poor nutrition and ill-health,'' said Angela
King, special adviser to the U.N. Secretary-General on gender
issues and the advancement of women.
</P>
<P>
   ''They still lag behind men in virtually all aspects of life,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   There is still serious disagreement over the final document to
be adopted when the conference ends next Friday, especially on
issues of health and family, said Christine Kapalata, chairwoman of
the conference preparatory committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have different social systems, you have different
religious dispensations, and to have a common position on these
issues at first sight is not very easy,'' Kapalata said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
