<HEADLINE> Cuban To Debut with Yankees  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The New York Yankees already have ''El Duque.''
Now, they have ''El Duquecito.''
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Hernandez, who defected from Cuba by sneaking aboard a
plane to Costa Rica, will formally sign with the Yankees on
Saturday, according to a baseball official, speaking on the
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez will make U.S. pro debut Saturday night when he starts
at home for Class A Tampa against Fort Myers in the Florida State
League.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez defected Jan. 2 and has been pitching for the Yankees'
extended spring training team in Florida. The 25-year-old
right-hander said in early April that he had agreed to a four-year
contract with New York, but the team refused to confirm the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said I would play for any team that wanted to sign me and
the best team in baseball came here with a contract,'' Hernandez
said in April. ''New York is now the city for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is nicknamed ''El Duquecito'' because his pitching
motion is similar to that of Orlando ''El Duque'' Hernandez,
another Cuban defector who started for the Yankees on Friday night
against the Atlanta Braves. The two are not related but both
pitched for Cuba's top team, the Havana Industriales.
</P>
<P>
   Several major league teams sent scouts to watch Adrian Hernandez
work out in Guatemala after he defected. He throws 93 mph and has
been impressive since arriving at extended spring training in
Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   In one game, he struck out seven and allowed only one hit while
pitching four shutout innings. In another, he had nine strikeouts
in four innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
