<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Hope Ice Slows Devils  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The slushy, bumpy ice at Reunion Arena might be
exactly what the Dallas Stars need to gain control of the Stanley
Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   With an 'N Sync concert forcing the ice to be covered Friday
night, the Stars know the playing surface will be in its usual
less-than-frigid condition for Game 3 Saturday night against the
New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like anywhere else in a lot of multipurpose buildings,
it's a matter of when does it get choppy and are you willing to
adjust your game because of it,'' Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said.
''You can't play the same game the last five minutes of periods.
You have to play a territorial game, and we're very good at that.''
</P>
<P>
   The defending champion Stars took over home-ice advantage in the
finals by splitting the first two games in New Jersey. Dallas would
keep the Cup if it wins all games at Reunion, regardless of what it
does on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have shown more speed and more lines of skill
players. The melting ice, then, could be more of a problem for them
than the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been fighting that all year,'' rookie forward Brenden
Morrow said. ''It's really hot in Dallas now, so the ice won't be
much better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will continue to be without forward Jamie
Langenbrunner. He's missed the last four games with a knee injury
and isn't sure when he'll be able to return.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do believe I'll be back,'' he said. ''I'm doing everything
in power to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Because hockey rinks don't vary as much as baseball stadiums and
fans are loud everywhere, some people question the benefits of
being at home. It could be argued that the road is more peaceful
because there's not the hassle of family and friends trying to get
tickets to the hottest event in town.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, though, is convinced there's no place like home for
his team. The Stars are 9-1 in Reunion this postseason and have won
11 of the last 12 playoff games there dating to last season.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it is a loyal fan base. They shower goalie Ed Belfour
with chants of ''Ed-die!'' before the national anthem, and they've
done their best to rattle opponents. They had a field day with
Colorado's Patrick Roy, even weighing in on the Belfour vs. Roy
debate by screaming ''Eddie's better'' during Game 7 of the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very emotional building for our players,'' Hitchcock
said. ''It's a different crowd here. They stick with us for a long
time. It's a very significant advantage for us, we feel. And we
feel we're going to need it the way Jersey played in Philadelphia,
which is a loud building.''
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage the home team has is the last shift change,
which will allow Hitchcock to pick the best matchups once he sees
which players Devils coach Larry Robinson sends out.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, though, isn't sure how much that will help.
</P>
<P>
   ''Larry really doesn't care about line matchups,'' Hitchcock
said. ''He pretty much lets 'em fly. He's got three lines that are
freewheeling and he can roll them whenever he wants. We have more
definitive checking lines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 2133 </TRAILER>
