<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rules on Saipan Workers  </HEADLINE>
By BOB EGELKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court ruled Friday that
garment workers on Saipan can sue their employers over alleged
sweatshop conditions anonymously because they fear disclosing their
names could get them fired or deported.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned a ruling by a
judge on the island who had required that 23 women suing factories
on the island must reveal their names or their lawsuit would be
dismissed. The suit seeks damages for 25,000 garment workers.
</P>
<P>
   Saipan, part of the U.S. Commonwealth of the Northern Marianas
in the western Pacific, is home to numerous garment factories where
workers, mostly immigrant women, are not protected by U.S. minimum
wage laws but where goods can be stamped ''Made in U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accuses 21 manufacturers on Saipan of failing to pay
overtime and forcing them to work 12 hours a day, seven days a week
in unclean and unsafe conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The 23 plaintiffs, nearly all from China, say they were warned
by Chinese recruiters not to complain about working conditions,
speak to Americans or criticize the Chinese government. Some said
they were threatened with arrest for filing labor complaints or
that complaints prompted fines against their relatives in China.
</P>
<P>
   Factory owners challenged the anonymous suit, submitting
statements by the Chinese government and other Chinese workers on
Saipan denying retaliation for labor complaints.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Alex Munson, on Saipan, sided with the
factory owners, finding insufficient evidence of threats and saying
he had no power to protect workers from the retaliation the women
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   But in Friday's appellate court ruling, Judge Harry Pregerson
wrote that federal courts can conceal plaintiffs' identities to
protect their privacy or safety from non-parties to a suit,
including a foreign government.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissal of the lawsuit without a ruling on the merits would be
against the public interest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling means Saipan's garment workers ''can utilize the
American courts without fear of retaliation,'' said Al Meyerhoff, a
lawyer for the women.
</P>
<P>
   E. Patrick Swan, a lawyer for the owners of two factories being
sued, said knowing the plaintiffs' names would have enabled him to
interview potential witnesses and do other necessary research.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a basic principal in our jurisprudence, that if you are
sued by someone you should have the right to know who they are so
you can properly investigate their claims. We have been deprived of
the opportunity to defend ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his clients are considering an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The ruling is available at
http://www.ce9.uscourts.gov/; case No. 99-16713.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 2135 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0162 </DOCNO>
