<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belize Families Bury Victims  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUNTA GORDA, Belize (AP) -- Families on Friday buried two victims
of a high-seas hijacking this week that left five dead, three
others injured and one still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Belize's Alice Ireheta and Juan Choc were buried in this port
village where the palm trees outnumber the people.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am trying to be strong and I'm trying to ask my family to be
strong,'' said Evelyn Ireheta, whose mother owned a grocery store
here and was headed home after doing charity work in Puerto
Barrios, Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   The daily commuter boat, Mariestela, was 20 minutes into the
75-mile trip between Puerto Barrios and this coastal village
Tuesday afternoon when three of the passengers pulled out machine
guns and began firing. The gunmen then threw the surviving women
and children overboard.
</P>
<P>
   Five people were shot to death. Three others were rescued
Wednesday morning, after spending 17-hours huddled together,
floating in the sea. Two of them, including American Larry Smith,
suffered gunshot wounds. Smith, who has lived in Belize for 27
years, was the assistant captain on the boat. He is the only one
who remains hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   The captain, Julio Requena Jr., who jumped into the water after
being shot, is still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Belizean authorities on Friday recovered the 35-passenger skiff
found in Guatemalan waters but the assailants were nowhere to be
found. Officials still do not know the motive for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, a Belizean tour cruiser recovered the bodies of
two Belizeans, a Honduran man and two Guatemalans.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants are believed to be Guatemalans but a motive is
still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point there really is no evidence as to why this
happened,'' said Bernard Lino, Belize's top investigator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 2137 </TRAILER>
