<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers Make NBA Finals  </HEADLINE>
By HAL BOCK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For the Indiana Pacers, that last step has
always been the most difficult of all -- a roadblock to the NBA
Finals they never managed to get around.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller reminded them of just how tough the New York
Knicks could be when they were cornered in the playoffs. ''We've
got to kill the dog,'' Miller said after the Pacers won the pivotal
fifth game of the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 6, he did away with the dog, almost singlehandedly in
Indiana's 93-80 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana opened a nine-point lead at halftime, saw it evaporate
and then methodically reconstructed the edge on Miller's long-range
shooting in the fourth quarter to eliminate the Knicks, who had
beaten the Pacers three times in previous sixth games.
</P>
<P>
   After the Pacers managed an all-time playoff low of 12 points in
the third quarter and fell behind early in the fourth, Miller
brought them back. Stepping gingerly back from the 3-point line
time after time, Miller nailed long-range shots from both sides of
the court, ignoring frantic New York defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Miller scored 17 of his 34 points in the fourth quarter as the
Pacers charged from behind to finish off New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had to exorcise some demons,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he did.
</P>
<P>
   He also got under the skin of the Knicks. On one sequence he was
followed up the court by the usually placid Patrick Ewing who
marched behind Miller, shouting at him.
</P>
<P>
   Miller never looked back. Instead, he was looking ahead, to his
first NBA Finals, the last of 32 NBA players with 20,000 points to
reach the championship round.
</P>
<P>
   This was a major mountain for the Pacers to climb. They had been
disappointed four times in the Eastern Conference Finals since
1994, beaten each time in seven games,
</P>
<P>
   First, they lost to the Knicks in 1994, then to Orlando in 1995,
then in the last gasp of the Michael Jordan Chicago Bulls in 1998
and then again by the Knicks last year.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they made sure there would be no seventh game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 2151 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Convicted in Shelter I. Murder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- In the first recorded murder on Shelter
Island since it was settled 348 years ago, a man was found guilty
Friday of fatally shooting his neighbor and longtime friend.
</P>
<P>
   A Suffolk County jury convicted Kenneth Payne, 44, of
second-degree murder for the April 1998 death of Curtis Cook. Payne
faces 25 years to life in prison when he is sentenced June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The men had known each other for 20 years, and after Cook was
charged with sexually abusing an 8-year-old girl, Payne refused to
believe he was guilty, police said.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities said an answering machine greeting in which Cook
expressed certainty he would beat the molestation charges
apparently angered Payne. He took a 12-gauge shotgun from his
trailer home to Cook's nearby house and shot Cook in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   The killing shocked the community of about 2,500 year-round
residents. The 12-square-mile island is off the eastern end of Long
Island and accessible only by ferry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
