<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Date Set For Fiji Hostage Release  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The leader of the armed rebels holding much of
Fiji's government hostage said Friday he will ask the country's
tribal chiefs to make him prime minister and that he may free his
captives this weekend to ''set the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebel leader George Speight set no firm timetable for releasing
the more than 30 hostages still held in the parliament complex --
his final card in the two-week power play for control of tiny Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Fiji's new martial law regime, Capt. Howard
Politini, said discussions had moved to the fine points of a deal
for releasing the captives and a surrender of arms by Speight and
his rebels who stormed the government May 19.
</P>
<P>
   ''These have been agreed in principle -- it's just a matter of
the details,'' Politini said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to elaborate as talks resumed between the military,
the rebels and representatives of the chiefs, who hold no formal
power but wield considerable influence in tiny Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   Speight said Fiji's influential tribal chiefs will decide what
the next step should be in this Pacific nation, where the military
responded to the hostage crisis by declaring martial law Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He said rebels and the military agreed to put two options to the
Great Council of Chiefs: let the military run Fiji until a new
constitution is drawn up and elections called or allow a civilian
government led by Speight to guide the country to elections.
</P>
<P>
   Speight said he is confident most of the chiefs from Fiji's 14
provinces support him, and that he will be installed as prime
minister after the council meets on Monday. Although Fiji's chiefs
hold little formal power, they command considerable respect and
influence among the indigenous majority here.
</P>
<P>
   The new military regime's leaders have not publicly said whether
they will honor the wishes of the chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis is rooted in simmering tensions between the country's
large ethnic Indian minority and the Fijian majority, many of whom
are angry that the Indians have gained power.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are indigenous Fijians, while Prime Minister Mahendra
Chaudhry and other hostages are ethnic Indian. The rebels want
Chaudhry, Fiji's first prime minister from the minority, removed
from power and Fijians of Indian ancestry barred from leading the
country again.
</P>
<P>
   Since the crisis began, gangs have attacked ethnic Indian homes
and businesses, in some cases looting and burning the homes and
beating residents.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the parliament, more violent skirmishes erupted on
Friday. One Speight supporter was shot, apparently by another, in
circumstances that were not clear, local radio reported. Earlier,
about 10 rebel supporters were beaten and detained by police.
</P>
<P>
   In the most positive sign yet that the hostages will soon be
released, Speight said he wants Monday's meeting with the tribal
chiefs to be ''uninhibited or untainted by ... issues,'' including
the fate of the captives.
</P>
<P>
   ''All going well, my plan is to release them before the Great
Council of Chiefs meeting,'' Speight told a news conference. He
later told British Broadcasting Corp. that he would release the
hostages ''probably on Sunday because it is a church day -- it is
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Australia and New Zealand have all threatened
sanctions if Fiji is not returned to democratic rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
