<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gretzky To Lead Coyotes' Operations  </HEADLINE>
By MEL REISNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky returned to hockey
Friday, not as a general manager or coach, but as the man with the
final say on all on-ice decisions for the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   He will decide the fate of GM Bobby Smith, coach Bob Francis and
others left dangling since owner Richard Burke agreed to sell the
franchise to Phoenix developer Steve Ellman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any decision regarding hockey operations is the decision of
Wayne Gretzky,'' Ellman said during a news conference that felt
more like a public celebration of Gretzky joining the team as
managing partner in charge of hockey operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no reason to believe that Bobby won't be with our
organization for a long time, but that decision isn't mine, it's
Wayne's,'' Ellman said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say what Gretzky's share of the team would be.
</P>
<P>
   Ellman said team president Shawn Hunter, whose contract expires
June 30, will run all business aspects of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky joked that his mother-in-law told him everyone needs to
be employed, but he said he did not take a day-to-day job.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see myself as a sounding board,'' said Gretzky, the most
prolific scorer in NHL history. ''Hopefully, I have some knowledge
and expertise about hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   The Great One joined Ellman's ownership group on May 26, the day
the developer had to come up with a $10 million down payment on the
team, which the group is buying for $87 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ellman originally was to pay another $17 million and transfer
Burke's debt on a $60 million loan to himself by June 30, but he
and Burke reset the deadline. Ellman now has to make a $6.5 million
payment this month, with the rest due Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Ellman was confident he would be able to raise another $100
million to complete the sale and erase the team's debt months in
advance of the revised deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, the Coyotes have the highest debt level in the NHL,
and we need to get rid of that,'' Ellman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's entry into the partnership kept the Coyotes in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Had Ellman defaulted on the down payment, Burke has said he
would have sold to Microsoft billionaire Paul Allen, who wanted to
acquire an NHL team to share Portland's Rose Garden with the Trail
Blazers, his NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank you for saving our hockey team,'' one fan yelled out
during Gretzky's introduction.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't think I was going to be back into this quickly, quite
honestly,'' said Gretzky, who retired from the New York Rangers
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ellman is the principal of a company redeveloping a run-down
mall in Scottsdale. The $535 million project includes a new arena
for the Coyotes, who are tied to the America West Arena in Phoenix
the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hadn't decided whether to rename the team Arizona
Coyotes or keep Phoenix in the name.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the city's request for a reduced silhouette of the
arena, the playing area will need to be about 70 feet below ground,
and Ellman said architects only recently came up with a way to
allow trucks and buses to drive into the basement without a steep
climb. Having resolved that, the company will soon present a site
plan to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Burke's operating losses in America West Arena were $7 million
for the 1996-97 season, the team's first in Phoenix, but they have
doubled because of obstructed-view seats and limited revenue
streams.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Coyotes' $31 million payroll ranks in the
bottom dozen in the NHL, and Gretzky was impressed with what Smith
did to acquire players.
</P>
<P>
   ''They had a pretty remarkable year considering that (holdout
goalie Nikolai) Khabibulin wasn't in there,'' Gretzky said.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk said having Gretzky in Phoenix
might assure his own future in Arizona. Tkachuk was the subject of
trade rumors this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 2157 </TRAILER>
