<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressRussell T. Adrine:
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Russell T. Adrine, a civil rights activist and
pioneering black attorney, died Friday after suffering a stroke. He
was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Adrine was among a group of attorneys that formed the first
black incorporated law firm in Cleveland in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   He served as chairman or co-chairman of all but one of the
congressional campaigns of Democrat Louis Stokes, the first black
congressman from Ohio, and also served on the Ohio Board of Tax
Appeals for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Adrine was a past president of both the Urban League of
Cleveland and the city chapter of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
Horace W. Busby Jr.:
</P>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Horace W. Busby Jr., an aide and
speechwriter for Lyndon B. Johnson who wrote the president's
announcement that he would not seek re-election, died Wednesday of
respiratory failure. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Busby worked for Johnson on and off for nearly two decades, and
wrote speeches discussing civil rights and other causes during
Johnson's ''Great Society'' presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Busby was first hired by Johnson as a speechwriter in 1946, two
years before Johnson was elected to the Senate. He served as
special assistant to Johnson from 1964 to 1965.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, at the height of Johnson's unpopularity because of the
Vietnam War, Busby wrote the president's announcement delivered
before a national TV audience: ''I shall not seek, and I will not
accept, the nomination of my party for another term as your
president.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the White House, Busby became a political
consultant for businesses such as Mobil Oil and American Airlines.
He also wrote political newsletters and was a frequent commentator
on the political scene.
Havanpola Ratanasara:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Havanpola Ratanasara, a prominent Southern
California Buddhist monk who led efforts to unite culturally
diverse believers and to ordain women as monks, died May 26. He was
80.
</P>
<P>
   Ratanasara was a United Nations delegate for Sri Lanka in 1957.
In 1980, he came to the United States and later became a citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Ratanasara founded the Buddhist Sangha Council of Southern
California and co-founding the American Buddhist Congress, serving
as its executive president until 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Ratanasara also was the Buddhist representative during Pope John
Paul II's visit to Los Angeles in 1987, and he co-founded the
Buddhist-Catholic Dialogue with the Roman Catholic archdiocese.
Bill Thomas:
</P>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Bill Thomas, a costume designer who
won an Academy Award for ''Spartacus'' and created outfits for
actors from John Wayne to Lana Turner, died Tuesday at 79. He had
suffered three heart attacks since January.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' career covered some 300 movies and TV shows, from
Westerns to historical romances to science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   His Oscar was for the gowns worn by Jean Simmons in 1960's
''Spartacus.''
</P>
<P>
   He also received Academy Award nominations for nine other
movies, including ''Ship of Fools'' and ''Bedknobs and
Broomsticks.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas designed Judy Garland's clown suit for ''The Pirate'' and
the silvery futuristic clothing of ''Logan's Run.'' He also created
personal wardrobes for actress Kim Novak and singer Helen Reddy.
Irving Rudd:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Irving Rudd, a sports publicist who worked for
the Brooklyn Dodgers and several boxers, died Friday of
complications from heart problems. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd began his career in the 1940s, working at fight clubs in
the New York area. He worked for the Dodgers from 1949 until they
left for Los Angeles after the 1957 season and was involved in such
promotions as Bat Day, Camera Day and Music Un-Appreciation Day.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Rudd also worked for Don King and at Madison
Square Garden and publicized fights involving Muhammad Ali, Sugar
Ray Leonard, Marvelous Marvin Hagler and Thomas Hearns. He is in
the International Boxing Hall of Fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
