<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dunkirk Boats Arrive in France  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNKIRK, France (AP) -- Scores of boats crossed the English
Channel to France on Friday, as part of the 60th anniversary
celebration of the rescue hundreds of thousands of Allied troops
from Dunkirk during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed back by the Germans in May 1940, British and French
troops were rescued from the encircling enemy by a British flotilla
of hundreds ships and boats manned by the military and civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Braving attack by German submarines and dive-bombers, the
flotilla managed to bring 338,000 troops to Britain between May 27
and June 4.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the older ships took just under eight hours Friday to
complete the 24-mile journey. The largest vessel was a 123-foot
luxury yacht; the smallest was 27-foot-long boat.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the celebration, Britain's Prince Charles is scheduled
to travel to Dunkirk on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
