<HEADLINE> Pirates 9, Royals 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Pat Meares and Warren Morris homered as the
Pittsburgh Pirates extended their winning streak to a season-best
four games by beating the Kansas City Royals 9-3 Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine Dye hit his 15th home run and Gregg Zaun also connected
as Kansas City took a 3-1 lead in the second inning against Todd
Ritchie (3-3).
</P>
<P>
   Meares hit a two-run homer in the fourth off Miguel Batista
(1-4) after Kevin Young drew a leadoff walk.
</P>
<P>
   Morris led off the fourth with his second home run and first
since April 29 for a 4-3 lead. He had gone 99 at-bats without one.
</P>
<P>
   Meares and Morris hit RBI singles and John Vander Wal doubled
home two runs in a five-run eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Royals designated hitter Dave McCarty, batting .342 and coming
off a 6-for-13 series in Boston, did not play. The DH is not used
in interleague games played at NL parks.
</P>
<P>
   Bench coach Rick Renick managed the Pirates in the absence of
Gene Lamont, who was in Sarasota, Fla., for his daughter's high
school graduation.
</P>
<P>
   The start of the game was delayed by rain for 62 minutes. The
crowd of 23,527 was slightly above the Pirates' average of 22,121
for Friday night games at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates hadn't won four consecutive games since July 31-Aug.
4 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie, pitching for the first time since signing a two-year,
$5.25 million contract extension, worked seven innings and allowed
four hits and three runs.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the second time in his last five starts that Ritchie
was charged with fewer than five earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Batista, who previously pitched for Montreal, has lost three
consecutive starts and is 0-4 lifetime against Pittsburgh. He gave
up a single to Jason Kendall in the first and walked three
consecutive batters to give the Pirates their first run.
Notes: In eight starts with the Royals, Batista has allowed at
least four earned runs seven times. ... Kansas City pitchers have
given up 95 home runs in 53 games, most in the major leagues. ...
Kendall had two singles and been held without a hit just once in
the last 17 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
