<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Detroit Girds for Anti-OAS Protest  </HEADLINE>
By GERALDA MILLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) -- Officials in Detroit and the neighboring
Canadian city of Windsor are shuttering windows, closing courts and
beefing up police presence in anticipation of protests against a
meeting by the Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit police Friday night arrested 20 protesters carrying
anti-OAS signs and using bicycles to block traffic heading into the
Detroit-Windsor tunnel, Police Chief Benny Napoleon said. He said
the protesters were charged with misdemeanors for interfering with
traffic and could face up to 90 days in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to be as nice and kind and friendly and gentle as
possible,'' Napoleon said. But ''we are not going to allow this
city to be taken over by anybody. Anybody who disagrees with any
action, we take can take it to court.''
</P>
<P>
   The OAS, which represents more than 30 Western Hemisphere
nations, is meeting Sunday through Tuesday in Windsor, a
middle-class city of 262,000 across the Detroit River from the
Motor City.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of the 52-year-old OAS say it fails to link trade
with workers rights, environmental protection and human rights.
Others say it threatens North American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A group called the Coalition to Shut Down the OAS held a
workshop Friday at the University of Windsor on Friday, discussing
issues such as protesters' legal rights and dealing with pepper
spray. They also painted signs for Sunday's demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ''My concern is that we have precious little left of a public
arena, of a public space where the citizens have any voice at all
in how they will be governed,'' said Jean Grossholtz, a 71-year-old
professor at Mount Holyoke College in Massachusetts who spoke at
the workshop Friday. ''We want to have some kind of voice ... Shut
down the meeting so that they listen and hear as they listened and
heard in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators hampered the World Trade Organization meeting in
Seattle last year and clogged downtown streets. A small number of
people smashed windows and looted stores, resulting in an estimated
$3 million in damage. More than 500 people were arrested, and
police have said they had not prepared properly.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Windsor and Detroit said they learned a lesson from
Seattle and are ready for any problems. Officers in both cities are
being issued riot gear; Windsor police also will be equipped with
gas masks.
</P>
<P>
   On the Michigan side, Wayne County Circuit Courts will be closed
Monday and Tuesday because of confidential information provided by
police, Chief Judge Michael Sapala said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a miserably difficult decision,'' Sapala said.
''Hopefully it will turn out that it was unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   With some protests planned near the Renaissance Center along the
Detroit River, tenants in the complex are being urged to come to
work in casual clothes, out of the belief that demonstrators often
approach people wearing suits.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp., the largest tenant in the center, sent a
memo to its employees telling them to check in before coming to
work Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from the OAS conference site in Windsor, the
CIBC Bank covered its windows on the advice of police. The bank
will remain open Monday and Tuesday, however.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Organization of American States: http://www.oas.org
</P>
<P>
   Protest coalition: http://www.tao.ca/(tilde)stopftaa
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 2240 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000602.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hewlett-Packard CEO Addresses Grads  </HEADLINE>
By THEO EMERY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Carleton ''Carly'' Fiorina is the
nation's top woman in the computer industry, but she still plays by
what she calls ''the rules of the garage'' -- never put your tools
away, know when to collaborate and, above all, invent.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorina, chief executive officer of Hewlett-Packard Co., shared
that advice Friday with graduates of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, where she earned her master's degree in business
management in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   She also sealed a deal Friday for Hewlett-Packard to give MIT
$25 million over the next five years for research.
</P>
<P>
   In the entrepreneurial world of high-tech the most innovative
ideas are often born in the most humble workshops, Fiorina told the
commencement audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''Leadership comes in small acts, and not just bold strokes,''
she said. ''The only limits that really matter are the ones you
impose on yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Limits are not something Fiorina succumbs to, judging by a
career path that led her last year to become the head of the
world's second-largest computer manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Now widely hailed as a role model for women in business,
Fiorina, 45, majored in philosophy and medieval history at Stanford
University. She started law school but dropped out, and once worked
as shipping clerk at the company she now heads.
</P>
<P>
   ''Engage your whole self in everything you do ... trust your
whole self and don't blink,'' she told the 2,139 graduating
students and an audience of thousands at the MIT campus.
</P>
<P>
   The $25 million research grant will go toward programs such as
the Laboratory for Computer Science, the Artificial Intelligence
Laboratory, and the Sloan School Center for eBusiness@MIT.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
