<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees 5, Braves 2  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The New York Yankees picked up where they left
off in October.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee homered and drove in four runs for the second game
in a row, Orlando Hernandez pitched seven strong innings and the
Yankees defeated the Atlanta Braves 5-2 Friday night in a rematch
of last year's World Series.
</P>
<P>
   New York, which began the three-game series at Turner Field
trailing Boston by 1 game in the AL East, used a familiar formula
to beat the team with baseball's best record: dominating pitching
and timely hitting.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it was last fall, when the Yankees swept Atlanta
for their third championship in four years. They won the Series
opener 4-1, as Hernandez allowed just one hit in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque was nearly as dominating Friday, surrendering only four
hits and striking out seven. He retired 10 of the last 11 hitters
he faced, the streak broken when Brian Jordan reached on an error
by Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez (5-4) snapped a four-game losing streak after skipping
his previous start because of a sore back. Jeff Nelson surrendered
Chipper Jones' 12th homer in the eighth before Mariano Rivera got
the final four outs for his 13th save in 15 chances.
</P>
<P>
   New York has the upper hand in the rivalry between the most
dominant franchises in each league, having also defeated Atlanta in
the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are seeking their sixth consecutive postseason
appearance, while Atlanta, which has lost its last two games,
appears headed toward its ninth straight trip to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves scored their other run in the third. Quilvio Veras
singled with one out, stole second and came home on Andruw Jones'
single to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees bounced back in the next inning against Kevin
Millwood (4-4). With one out, Tino Martinez doubled over Andruw
Jones' head in center, Jorge Posada walked and Ledee lined a
fastball into the second row of the right-field stands for his
fifth homer, a three-run shot.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee struck again in the eighth off reliever Bruce Chen,
doubling against the center-field wall to bring in another run. The
Yankees outfielder also had a three-run homer and four RBIs in New
York's previous game, an 8-7 loss to Oakland on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, who has struggled much of the season, now has 11 hits in
his last 33 at-bats to raise his average to .246.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood went seven innings, giving up seven hits with three
walks and six strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter had an RBI double in the ninth against Kerry
Ligtenberg.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Rivera struck out Galarraga on three pitches to end the
eighth. First batters are 1-for-19 against the New York closer. ...
The Yankees are expected to formally announce the signing of
pitcher Adrian ''El Duquecito'' Hernandez on Saturday. The Cuban
defector will make his U.S. pro debut that night when he starts at
home for Class A Tampa against Fort Myers in the Florida State
League. ... Ho hum: Gold Glover Andruw Jones made another
sensational catch, leaping in the seventh inning to snare Paul
O'Neill's liner to the gap in left-center. ... The game attracted
the third sellout of the year at Turner Field, 48,524. ... Braves
reliever Greg McMichael has a slight tear in his right rotator
cuff, a similar injury to the one that required surgery in October.
Surgery is not an option for now. McMichael will rest his arm for
the next two weeks, then begin a ''conservative'' rehab program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
