<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Unemployment Up To 4.1 Percent
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Labor Department said today the nation's unemployment
rate rose to 4.1 percent in May as businesses cut 116,000 jobs, the biggest
reduction in nine years. The report showed the jobless rate rose by 0.2
percentage point from a 30-year low of 3.9 percent reached in April. While
private sector jobs declined, this was offset by government hiring of temporary
Census workers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Feds Seek Alaska Air Repair Ban
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After finding nearly 150 cases where aircraft maintenance
could not be documented, the Federal Aviation Administration proposed to strip
Alaska Airlines of the right to perform maintenance on its planes. The step
could eventually force the airline to park its planes and stop flying. ''We have
serious concerns about critical processes, including management effectiveness,''
Nick Lacey, director of Flight Standards Service for the FAA, said today. The
FAA's investigation is proceeding and enforcement actions -- usually civil fines
-- could be announced in coming weeks, Lacey said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Defense Highlights US-Russia Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- At a Kremlin summit held in the twilight of one man's
presidency and the beginning of the other's, Bill Clinton and Vladimir Putin
will be measuring one another on issues that will outlast them both. Clinton
flies to Moscow on Saturday after five days of conferences and ceremonies with
western European allies, who are restive about at least one proposal he'll take
to Putin: the idea of amending an arms control treaty so the United States can
build a limited anti-missile defense system.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Census-Takers Seek the Final 8.6M
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Armed with stacks of blank questionnaires, census-takers
head back to big-city neighborhoods, gated communities and isolated farm houses
in their final attempt to find people who still haven't been counted in Census
2000. Their mission: Track down 8.6 million households by early July. The
biggest tool for census-takers may be their persuasiveness -- how well they can
convince the wary to answer their questions: What is your race? Do you own or
rent?
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore: Focus More on Fathers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore said today that national family policy needs to
focus more on fathers as he expanded on ideas to help ''dead broke'' dads find
work and pay child support -- proposals that make his feminist friends nervous.
To accommodate those allies' concerns, the Democratic presidential contender
added a domestic-violence-prevention component to his ''pro-fatherhood''
initiative. He also promoted his plan, which Republicans derided as ''lip
service,'' to alleviate the tax code's so-called marriage penalty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Police Departments Seek Recruits
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- With the economy booming and rookie police salaries
relatively low, the number of people lining up for badges is dwindling. Chicago,
which tested 25,000 applicants seven years ago, has lined up just 1,900
potential recruits for the latest exam, which is given twice a year. The story
is much the same in Los Angeles, New York and other cities around the country.
''All of law enforcement is experiencing the same problems we are, and that's
finding qualified applicants,'' said Officer Frank Banuelos, a spokesman for the
Los Angeles Police Department.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rain Helps Slow New Mexico Fire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PECOS, N.M. (AP) -- Firefighters tackled a 25,000-acre wildfire head-on
today, seizing a break in the hot, dry weather as a chance to surround the fire.
''We are attacking with all our might today,'' fire information officer Tom Mott
said. ''When it's safe, it's time to strike.'' The blaze was 60 percent
contained. Thunderstorms yesterday and today gave firefighters a chance to
bolster their efforts against the blaze, which had been burning since Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Rises 231; Dow Ends Up 143
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index wrapped up its best week in
history today as investors poured money back into the technology stocks they had
abandoned amid fears of rising interest rates. Stocks soared after the
government's employment report raised hopes that economic growth is slowing to a
less inflationary pace. The Nasdaq rose 230.88 points, or by 6.4 percent, to
close at 3,813.38. The index rose a stunning 19 percent this week. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 142.56 points to close at 10,794.76. For the week, the
Dow shot up 4.8 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pacers Beat Knicks, Make NBA Finals
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Reggie Miller scored 34 points and made five 3-pointers --
four in a span of 6{ minutes late in the game -- to lead the Indiana Pacers past
New York 93-80 tonight in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference finals. With the win,
the Pacers are vaulted into the NBA Finals for the first time ever. Returning to
Madison Square Garden, the scene of some of his greatest performances, Miller
played the villain again and came through in the clutch.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
