<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reds 4, Twins 3  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Michael Tucker and Dante Bichette each homered
and had three hits Friday night, leading the Cincinnati Reds over
the Minnesota Twins 4-3 in their interleague opener.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Bell (4-3) settled in after giving up Jacque Jones'
game-opening homer, allowing only three more hits during seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins rallied in the ninth by loading the bases off Scott
Williamson and getting a two-run single by pinch-hitter Midre
Cummings with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Graves relieved and got Jones on a disputed strikeout --
Jones claimed catcher Benito Santiago's mitt hit his bat on the
final swing, but plate umpire Jerry Layne declined to change his
call. Cristian Guzman hit into a force out, giving Graves his ninth
save in as many chances.
</P>
<P>
   Slumping Ken Griffey Jr. returned to the Reds' lineup after an
unwanted day off and went 0-for-3 with a walk in his return to
American League pitching. Griffey, acquired from Seattle during the
offseason, is hitless in his last 17 at-bats, dropping his average
to .209.
</P>
<P>
   By winning their interleague version of home run derby, the Reds
improved to 3-4 on a 12-game homestand. Minnesota lost for only the
second time in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's solo homer and Bichette's two-run shot came off Joe
Mays (2-7), who gave up seven hits in five-plus innings and took
the loss because of his two glaring mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Bichette fouled off two 0-2 pitches before hitting his
tiebreaking homer in the fourth, his second in two games. Since
returning from a three-day benching, Bichette has been the Reds'
hottest hitter, going 22-for-48 (.458) in the last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey made the best defensive play of the game, sprinting into
right-center field to make a backhand catch of Brian Buchanan's
sinking liner in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, who took over for Griffey in center on Thursday and had
three hits, extended his surge by hitting Mays' second pitch over
the 404-foot marker in center in the second inning, tying the game
at 1.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker also singled twice and flew out, leaving him with 12 hits
in his last 18 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Casey drove in Cincinnati's final run with a sacrifice fly
following consecutive singles by Bichette and Tucker in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Bell ended two dismal days of pitching by the Reds, who gave up
19 runs and 33 hits in consecutive losses to Montreal. Jones hit
the rookie's second pitch for his eighth homer, but the Twins
couldn't do much more.
</P>
<P>
   Bell pitched out of a two-on, one-out threat in the sixth by
striking out Corey Koskie and Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Mays, who throws right-handed but is a switch-hitter, had an
infield single for his first career hit in the third inning. Casey,
at first, and Bell both went for his high-hop grounder, leaving
Bell late covering first on the play. Mays ran hard down the line
for his first hit in four career at-bats.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The start was delayed 17 minutes by rain. ... The Twins are
24-25 in interleague play since 1997, including 5-5 against the
Reds. Cincinnati is 24-20 overall in interleague play. ... With his
infield single, Mays matched last year's hit total by Twins
pitchers in interleague games. They were 1-for-18 without an RBI or
a run scored, striking out eight times. ... It was the fifth time
in his career and the third time this season that Jones has led off
a game with a homer. ... Bichette is 7-for-9 in his last two games.
... Slumping Reds 2B Pokey Reese (3-for-22) was out of the lineup,
but came in for defense in the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
