<HEADLINE> BBC Orders Disco To Get a New Name  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAUGUS, Mass. (AP) -- One is a venerable broadcasting
organization. The other is a disco with 3-D murals of dancing
aliens. Both are called BBC.
</P>
<P>
   That's a problem in the eyes of the British Broadcasting
Corporation, which sent the owner of the dance club BBC 2000 --
a.k.a. the Bahama Beach Club -- a cease-and-desist order for using
its name.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are apt to associate the letters BBC with the British
Broadcasting Corporation,'' the BBC's trademark lawyer Mark Sommers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Club owner Russell Robbat said he got Sommers' notice three
weeks ago and does not plan to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to joke that BBC stood for 'Big Brother is coming,'''
Robbat said. ''Now Big Brother IS coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
