<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Rebels: Military Backed Out  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Rebels who have seized control of Parliament
charged Saturday that Fiji's military has backed out of an
agreement that would have led to the quick release of 30 hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel leader George Speight had earlier said he might release
his captives this weekend, following an agreement with the military
to let Fiji's influential tribal chiefs determine the next form of
government -- military or civilian.
</P>
<P>
   But the rebels said Saturday that the military had changed its
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been a breach of faith,'' said Speight spokesman Joe
Nata. He said the military had signed off on a plan to let the
chiefs resolve the dispute, but later insisted Fiji would remain
under military control.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after rebels met with representatives of
new martial law leader, Commodore Frank Bainimarama.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the military, or comment
from Speight on how the deadlock would affect the fate of the
hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, a spokesman for the military, Capt. Howard Politini,
said discussions had moved to the fine points of a deal for
releasing the captives and a surrender of arms by Speight and his
rebels who stormed the government May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Speight has maintained that he's confident most of the chiefs
from Fiji's 14 provinces support him, and that he will be installed
as prime minister after the council meets on Monday. Although
Fiji's chiefs hold little formal power, they command considerable
respect and influence among the indigenous majority here.
</P>
<P>
   Speight threw Fiji into crisis on May 19 by seizing Prime
Minister Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry and 30 other members of
the government. The crisis eventually prompted the military to
declare martial law and throw out the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis is rooted in simmering tensions between the country's
large ethnic Indian minority and the Fijian majority, many of whom
are angry that the Indians have gained power.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are indigenous Fijians, while Chaudhry and other
hostages are ethnic Indian. The rebels want Chaudhry, Fiji's first
prime minister from the minority, removed from power and Fijians of
Indian ancestry barred from leading the country again.
</P>
<P>
   Since the crisis began, gangs have attacked ethnic Indian homes
and businesses, in some cases looting and burning the homes and
beating residents.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the parliament, more violent skirmishes erupted on
Friday. One Speight supporter was shot, apparently by another, in
circumstances that were not clear, local radio reported. Earlier,
about 10 rebel supporters were beaten and detained by police.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Australia and New Zealand have all threatened
sanctions if Fiji is not returned to democratic rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-02-00 2322 </TRAILER>
