<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies 2, Red Sox 1, 11 Innings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Slumping Alex Arias doubled home the winning
run with one out in the 11th inning Friday night and the
Philadelphia Phillies defeated the Boston Red Sox 2-1 to end their
three-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter drew a one-out walk off reliever John Wasdin (0-2)
and went to second when Desi Relaford was hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Arias, who began the night in a 6-for-49 slump, then hit a 3-2
pitch to deep left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Jeff Brantley (1-0) pitched two scoreless innings for
his first win since April 27, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Brantley has been hampered with shoulder problems, missing most
of the 1999 season, and was on the disabled list this year until
May 3.
</P>
<P>
   Boston lost its third in a row. Carl Everett's 18th homer, his
fourth in four games, tied it in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox got no help at the plate from its pitchers. Their
pitchers are just 1-for-50 since interleague play began, the only
hit being a bunt single by Vaughn Eshelman against the Mets June
15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The game was delayed for 19 minutes with one out in the top of
the first when a bank of lights went out.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Person shut out the Red Sox for seven innings and Wayne
Gomes took over with a 1-0 lead. Gomes retired the first two
batters in the eighth before Everett lined a 2-2 pitch just over
the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up consecutive singles to Troy O'Leary and Jason
Varitek, Gomes got the final out of the inning when Ron Gant threw
a perfect strike to cut down O'Leary at the plate after Wilton
Veras singled.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia scored in the second off Brian Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Jordan singled with one out, Mickey Morandini walked and
Hunter hit a sinking liner to center that bounced past Everett for
an RBI double.
Notes: Jeff Frye singled as a pinch-hitter in the Boston seventh,
extending his hitting streak to a career-high 12 games. ...
Phillies rookie 1B Pat Burrell did not start for the second
straight game because of a sore right hand, but appeared as a
pinch-hitter in the ninth was walked. ... Attendance was 22,194,
about average for the Phillies this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
